<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVS-NETS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVS STUMBLE IN NEW JERSEY DESPITE HOLDING LATE LEAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Don Nelson will have to wait to enter
the 900-win fraternity.
</P>
<P>
   On the verge of victory, the Mavericks collapsed down the
stretch and lost, 98-95, yesterday to the New Jersey Nets before a
Saturday-matinee crowd of 13,682 at Continental Airlines Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks wind up this three-game road trip at 6 tonight
against the Detroit Pistons at the Palace of Auburn Hills. But
before they take on the Pistons, the Mavericks are still trying to
figure out how they lost to the Nets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just shot ourselves in the foot once again in a game we
should have had,'' guard Michael Finley said. ``Every loss is
tough, but this one was tough because we were put in a situation
where we could have won the ballgame, but we just came up short.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks led 91-86 with 3:14 left, but errant shots and
blown defensive assignments helped leave Dallas with a 13-26 record
and prevented Nelson from joining Lenny Wilkens, Pat Riley, Red
Auerbach, Bill Fitch and Dick Motta as the only NBA coaches with
900 career wins.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks also wasted another 30-plus-point outing from
Cedric Ceballos. Ceballos scored 39 points in Monday's loss to
Houston, and pumped in a game-high 36 against the Nets on 17-of-26
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Ceballos also was involved in one of the game's crucial plays.
With 31.6 seconds left and Dallas up, 95-94, Ceballos drove hard to
the basket, but his hook shot was rejected by Kerry Kittles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where he came from,'' Ceballos said. ``I saw the
shot go up clean, and he just came out of nowhere and got it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nets picked up the loose ball, and point guard Stephon
Marbury (20 points, eight assists) zipped downcourt for a layup and
a 96-95 Nets lead with 24.5 seconds remaining. But instead of
calling a timeout, the Mavericks worked the ball downcourt, and in
the confusion, Hubert Davis missed a running jumper with 4.3
seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was on different pages,'' Finley said. ``I was
calling for Ced to come get the ball. He thought that the play was
called for Dirk \RNowitzki\S to get the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was just scattered, and it was kind of hectic at the
end. And I ended up throwing a \Rcrosscourt\S pass to Hubert that
almost was stolen, and Hubert threw up a desperation runner, and
that's how the game went.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Burrell hit a pair of free throws with 4.3 seconds left to
give the Nets some breathing room. After a Mavericks timeout,
Nowitzki stepped on the 3-point line and missed a long two-point
shot at the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a bad move,'' Nowitzki said. ``They switched
everything, so I had Marbury on me, and I didn't want him to steal
the ball, so I did a spin move and I was on the line. Maybe I
should have shot it over him.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than Ceballos, the Mavericks contributions were mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Davis scored 13 points and kept a stranglehold on first place in
the NBA in 3-point shooting with a 3-for-3 effort. Finley (5-of-18)
struggled for 10 points, seven rebounds and nine assists.
</P>
<P>
   Nowitzki was 4-of-11 from the floor with 11 points and 10
rebounds. Shawn Bradley had 10 points and 11 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks were dealt a big blow when forward Gary Trent
aggravated his tender left groin when his shot was blocked by
Kittles. Trent, whose availability for tonight's game is unknown,
did not play after the first quarter and finished with only four
points and two rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally couldn't get the ball in the bucket, but coach
kept calling my number,'' Finley said. ``Everything that could have
gone wrong, went wrong in those last couple of minutes.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
