<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-A&AMP;M-OKLA.-STATE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS A&AMP;M PULLS SHOCKER ON OKLAHOMA STATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ When Oklahoma State's 12th-ranked
Cowboys arrived at Reed Arena yesterday, they were welcomed by a
struggling Texas A&AMP;M team with four freshmen in the starting
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   They departed a few hours later with the throbbing beat of the
/Aggie War Hymn'' reverberating in their heads, as hundreds of
screaming patrons gathered a midcourt to mob the home team. Some
were a bit tentative, since it's a routine that hasn't happened in
a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this is a beginning of what Aggie basketball will be
like in the future,'' said coach Melvin Watkins, following a 64-59
victory over the stunned Cowboys (14-2, 3-1 Big 12).
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to start somewhere, and today was as good a day as
any.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Aggies (6-10, 2-3), facing their fourth ranked team in
the past five games, it was a day that seemed to defy logic.
Trailing 43-35 early in the second half, they were being wiped off
the boards by OSU and missing free throws with alarming
consistency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was beginning to look like another one of those games,''
said Bernard King, who led the Aggies with 17 points and nine
rebounds. ``But we said, `Not this night,' '' and a comeback that
broke a string of 29 consecutive losses to ranked opponents was
soon under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a moment when things were looking pretty bad,'' said
Jamaal Gilchrist, ``but the coaches called us over and said, `Get
your heads up ... don't quit, keep fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, the game's complexion changed and, as OSU's
Glendon Alexander noted, ``They stuck around, and when the momentum
changed, they bit us like a wounded dog.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, the Aggies had their first victory over a
ranked team since an 81-70 victory over 15th-ranked TCU in the
opening round of the 1987 Southwest Conference tournament. The last
victory over a team ranked higher than OSU was a 1982 victory over
fifth-ranked Texas.
</P>
<P>
   OSU still seemed in command when Desmond Mason gave the Cowboys
a 45-39 lead with 17:30 remaining. But it would be six minutes and
20 seconds before Oklahoma State scored again. Mason _ who riddled
Texas with 30 points in a showdown of ranked teams Wednesday, soon
picked up his fourth foul and sat out much of the last half. He
scored only two more points, finishing with 19.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the wounded dog kept biting. In the second half the
Aggies improved on a 2-of-10 first-half performance from the line
and evened a 10-rebound deficit and, as Cowboys coach Eddie Sutton
noted, ``They had 17 offensive rebounds and killed us in the second
half. They scored four or five times on rebounds after missed free
throws and that just shouldn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   With 2:37 left, OSU's last lead disappeared when Aaron Jack's
two free throws lifted A&AMP;M to a 58-57 lead. A jumper by Larry Scott
and free throws by Gilchrist and Jack pushed it to 62-57 with 27
seconds left. The Cowboys then lost a key possession when they let
the ball slip out of bound.
</P>
<P>
   OSU's last gasp _ a hook by Fredrik Jonzen _ was countered by
two King free throws with nine seconds left, and it was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I challenged them at halftime to be aggressive on the boards,
and I told them if they didn't come back, I wouldn't feed them
tonight,'' Watkins quipped.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been playing all these ranked teams, and I think it made
us better,'' Gilchrist said. ``We wanted to beat one of them _ just
one _ and this was the game. I know it's just one win ... but, oh
my, it feels good. I'm happy for the school and the fans _ it was
great to have them out there screaming and dancing and pounding on
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the gym, OSU point guard Doug Gottlieb shook his head
and said, ``For years, our goal has been to be in the top 10, and
after beating Texas, we would have been there if we'd won this one.
It's so disappointing.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
