<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-IOWA-ST.-OKLAHOMA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OKLAHOMA NUDGES IOWA STATE IN OT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORMAN, Okla. _ Kansas learned it. Oklahoma State was schooled.
And so was Iowa State. They found out that winning on the road,
especially in conference play, isn't exactly life in the fast lane.
More like life in the on-coming lane.
</P>
<P>
   The Cyclones entered the day one of three undefeated teams in
Big 12 Conference play. And yesterday's 80-75 double-overtime loss
to No. 17 Oklahoma (15-3, 3-2) handed Iowa State (16-3, 4-1) its
first league loss of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw some of the other top teams lost and we knew this could
be a turning point for us,'' said Sooners guard Tim Heskett, who
came off the bench to score 18 points and lead an OU 3-point
downpour. ``We had lost two on the road and you've got to defend
your home court. We needed to win this one.''
</P>
<P>
   After losing two consecutive road games, Oklahoma was faced with
a must-win situation. And the Sooners nearly fumbled it away.
Victor Avila, who is averaging 4.6 points per game, scored all of
OU's four points in the first overtime. The Cyclones' Jamaal
Tinsley had his driving shot rim out at the end of regulation. And
Michael Nurse made just one of two free throws with 4.8 seconds
remaining at the end of the first OT.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of chances and we didn't capitalize on it,'' said
Iowa State coach Larry Eustachy, whose team's school-record 13-game
winning streak ended. ``I can't believe Jamaal's layup didn't go
in. You've got to win games like this. This was a great opportunity
that got away.''
</P>
<P>
   Down 16 points late in the first half and trailing 52-38 with
6:47 remaining, the Cyclones nearly stole a road victory.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma's zone defense limited Iowa State to a season-low 19
first-half points and 30 percent shooting. The Cyclones went the
last 7:47 of the first half without a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Eustachy's pleas to attack the Sooners' zone started to sink in,
particularly late in the second half. Iowa State overcome OU's lead
by forcing turnovers and converting. Nurse, who had just three
points at halftime, scored 16 after intermission. His 3-pointer
with 1:38 remaining in regulation tied it at 59-all.
</P>
<P>
   In the first overtime, neither team's top player took a shot.
Oklahoma's Eduardo Najera (25 points, 14 rebounds), though, got hot
in the second overtime while Iowa State's Marcus Fizer (20 points,
six rebounds) missed his only attempt. In 48 minutes, Fizer
(averaging 20.8 points per game) managed just 13 shots.
</P>
<P>
   After 3-pointers by Heskett and J.R. Raymond gave the Sooners a
69-67 lead, Najera's three-point play with 2:18 remaining provided
some separation. On OU's next possession, Najera beat a double team
with a pass to the corner to Heskett. Swish. 75-69 lead with 1:37
remaining. Ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll make that pass to Tim 100 times out of 100,'' said
Najera, who was involved in 10 of OU's 17 points in the second OT.
``I knew he'd make that shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Eustachy and Oklahoma coach Kelvin Sampson described the game as
a slugfest. Heskett talked to the media wearing four ice packs _
one on each shin, one on his left knee and one on his back. He also
had a bandage on his left elbow. Najera wore a post-game ice pack
on his left elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our kids bent,'' said Sampson, whose team hit 13 3-pointers.
``But these kids are tough. Hesketh can't touch the rim. But
there's a lot to be said for making open shots.'' \Ntagtop:Wendell
Barnhouse, (817) 390-7238 \Ntagbottom:wbhoops\Nstar-telegram.com
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
