<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-TECH-KANSAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TECH PRESSURE OVERWHELMS KANSAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUBBOCK _ The Texas Tech Lady Raiders employed a ``hands-on''
approach during yesterday's Big 12 game against No. 23 Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Little went uncontested by the 15th-ranked Lady Raiders, who
transformed a matchup between two nationally ranked programs into
no contest during their 76-56 victory at United Spirit Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive-minded Lady Raiders' fingerprints covered the
basketball with 12 steals and four blocked shots, and that did not
include the 23 turnovers their defensive pressure created.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no secret that we're going to feed off of our defense,''
coach Marsha Sharp said after the Lady Raiders' 25th consecutive
Big 12 victory in Lubbock.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Raiders (15-2, 4-2 Big 12) went on their decisive feast
during the final four minutes and eight seconds of the first half.
Texas Tech forced four turnovers and mustered three steals and a
blocked shot during a 14-0 run that doomed the Jayhawks (12-5, 3-2)
and gave the Lady Raiders a 43-29 lead at the half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started playing well defensively and got our hands on the
ball,'' said Texas Tech guard Katrisa O'Neal, who had three steals.
``That got our offense going and the crowd into the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Forwards Keitha Dickerson and Aleah Johnson silenced Lynn Pride
of Kansas, whom Sharp called ``as good an athlete as we'll play
against.'' Pride, a Sam Houston High School graduate, converted
only four of her 16 shots from the field and scored a season-low
eight points during her 34 minutes before fouling out.
</P>
<P>
   Center Plenette Pierson also made the afternoon difficult for
Kansas' Jaclyn Johnson, who missed 10 of 13 shots from the field
and scored only 10 points. The Jayhawks shot only 35.4 percent (23
of 65) from the field.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Raiders' Johnson matched her career high with 21
points, and Pierson added 17 points and 11 rebounds. Guard Melinda
Schmucker-Pharies also made 3-of-6 attempts from behind the 3-point
arc and directed the offense near flawlessly with eight assists and
only one turnover during her 39 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we got as complete an effort for 40 minutes as we've
had all year from everyone on the floor,'' Sharp said. ``Everyone
we put on the floor did her job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
