r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-COACH-TEX     01-23 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-COACH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VERY THOROUGH JERRY JONES KEEPS UP COWBOYS' COACHING SEARCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Cowboys' head-coaching job has come open
three times in six years, and twice in the past 24 months.
</P>
<P>
   This raises a question: How good a job can this really be?
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones has spoken to a large number of
coaches, scouts and front-office personnel around the NFL that have
produced an outpouring of opinions during an intense
information-gathering process, which is heading into its third
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this \RCowboys' head-coaching\S job has become the
Bengals and the Raiders,'' scoffed one longtime NFL general manager
this past week.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Jones has indicated that most of the feedback has been
constructive. After all, the Cowboys' head-coaching vacancy still
represents one of only 31 jobs in league, and is one of only three
unfilled head-coaching positions.
</P>
<P>
   Head-coaching jobs remain open at Dallas, New England and New
Orleans after Green Bay hired Seattle Seahawks offensive
coordinator Mike Sherman and the New York Jets appear set to
promote linebackers coach Al Groh.
</P>
<P>
   Like Mike Brown in Cincinnati and Al Davis in Oakland, Jones has
the dual role of hands-on owner and personnel-involved general
manager. Although the Cowboys have won three Super Bowls since the
Bengals (1989) or Raiders (1984) have appeared in one, their
head-coaching job is one of the most treacherous in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Jones has used his coaching search to gather ideas from those he
respects around the league on what kind of offense the Cowboys need
to run. His next head coach and offensive coordinator _ whether
it's one person or two _ are only part of what Jones hopes will
come from these conversations. He has yet to ask for permission to
interview a candidate from another team for either the job of head
coach or offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a process for Jerry,'' one NFL coach said. ``He's
smart enough to use this time to ask a lot of people around the
league a lot of questions about his franchise. What do they think
of the Cowboys? What would they do against the Cowboys?
</P>
<P>
   ``This might take a little time. Who knows? And if Jerry ends up
hiring someone \Rsuch as Dave Campo or Joe Avezzano\S from inside
the organization, people are going to wonder why he didn't do that
from the get-go. Well, that's not the point. The point is that
Jerry has gathered a lot of valuable information on his team in the
meantime.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody seems to know for sure what Jones will do, or when he
will do it, in selecting a successor or successors to Chan Gailey,
who was fired Jan. 11 after only two seasons as head coach and
offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry is a lot like I am,'' the Raiders' Al Davis said. ``He
doesn't care about public perception. He cares about only one thing
_ winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones still covets Washington Redskins coach Norv Turner. Owner
Daniel Snyder, however, has said that Turner isn't go anywhere and
Turner has said he isn't interested in leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Turner's status quo, the recent promotion of Dave
Wannstedt to head coach in Miami and the designation of St. Louis
Rams offensive coordinator Mike Martz to Dick Vermeil's heir
apparent, has limited Jones' field of candidates.
</P>
<P>
   This has resulted in a runaway rumor mill: Al Saunders, the
Rams' receivers coach and former San Diego head coach (17-22 in
1986-88); Art Shell, Atlanta's offensive line coach and former
Raiders head coach (56-41 in 1990-94), and an unemployed Lindy
Infante, who once coached at Green Bay (24-40 in 1988-91) and
Indianapolis (12-21 in 1996-97).
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cowboys are still, in my opinion, the most visible sports
franchise in the world,'' Jones said. ``Of course, that doesn't
make it a good coaching opportunity ... \Rwhat does\S is that we
have a reputation for doing whatever it takes financially to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Cleveland, Green Bay and New England reportedly spent more
money than the Cowboys last season. Jones paid $41.5 million in
signing bonuses alone.
</P>
<P>
   Jones continues the search, with few clues being left behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry is really tight-lipped on this one,'' the Bengals' Brown
said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
