<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS SEARCH FOR BACKUPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Coach Phil Jackson took a break from his
Bill-Bradley-for-President advocacy to offer another endorsement
with political overtones: I like Ike.
</P>
<P>
   That would be Ike Austin of the Washington Wizards, who
according to a Washington Post report, has attracted the interest
of the Lakers. Austin is languishing on the Wizards bench but could
fill the Lakers' greatest need - a big body off the bench to spell
Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the prototype of what we were kind of hoping to have as a
backup center - 6-10, mobile,'' Jackson said Saturday. ``But right
now that hasn't been addressed in those terms or the kind of
urgency or the kind of seriousness that was kind of denoted in that
article. I don't know who was responsible for that (rumor), so I
can't comment on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lakers executive Jerry West indicated last week that he might
hesitate to make a trade in light of the team's success. But
Jackson sounds ready to add frontcourt depth if it's available.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to make good chemistry important as an ingredient,
but you also have to be realistic about what we have as far as
backing up power players,'' he said. ``We don't have a lot of
poundage on this team. After you get rid of Shaq, there's not a
whole lot of big bodies on this team to go against the big-bodied
teams like Portland, San Antonio and Utah.... We could use another
big body.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Lakers have the NBA's best record, Jackson wouldn't
say if he's comfortable with the roster as is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could say I'd be very comfortable doing it this way,
but who knows? I mean, we're sitting here with Shaq having averaged
almost 40 minutes a game... and I'm very comfortable with where
he's at physically, but today's the halfway point of the season,
and the games come a little more fast and furious toward the end of
the year. With playoffs ahead, you can always use an extra body.''
</P>
<P>
   Approving: Jackson seemed pleased with Kobe Bryant's decision to
skip the slam-dunk contest at All-Star weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``That can be a very draining weekend, not only the attention
that you have but also the number of events that you participate
in, and it can be extremely difficult for players to recover after
that,'' Jackson said. ``I think it's a smart move for him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
