<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-23 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3813 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-TEXAS-TEXASTECH-H     01-23 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXAS-TEXAS </SLUG>
 TECH-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Texas smoothly avoids road rage
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JEROME SOLOMON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
LUBBOCK _ After the road team took it on the chin in the five
earlier Big 12 Conference men's basketball games Saturday,
including nationally ranked Kansas and Oklahoma State, Texas had to
figure an upset was a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   But the Longhorns were having none of that.
</P>
<P>
   With only a couple of lapses that made things interesting for a
minute or two, Texas put in a business-like performance and
disposed of Texas Tech 72-69 in front of 14,045 at the United
Spirit Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Five players scored in double figures for the 14th-ranked
Longhorns. Center Chris Mihm led the way, tallying his 10th double
double of the season with 15 points, 10 rebounds and four blocked
shots.
</P>
<P>
   Junior forward Chris Owens had a solid effort as well, scoring
14 points in 22 minutes off the bench. Darren Kelly and William
Clay, with 11 points each, and Lawrence Williams (10 points) were
in double figures as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``With what went on in the league today, this was obviously a
big win for us,'' said Texas coach Rick Barnes, whose team is tied
for first place in the league standings. ``For the most part,
everyone that played (contributed).''
</P>
<P>
   Texas (12-5 overall, 4-1 in the Big 12) held Tech to 37.3
percent shooting and improved to 9-0 this season when its opponent
shoots less than 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Rayford Young scored 18 points to lead Tech, which dropped to
9-6 overall and 0-4 in conference play. Jayson Mitchell and Mario
Layne added 11 points and Brodney Kennard 10 for the Red Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   Texas held a 30-20 advantage at the half, but the short-handed
Red Raiders made a run early in the second period and closed to
within 39-38. But Tech never managed to regain the lead it held
five minutes into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Fatigue could have played a role down the stretch as the Red
Raiders were forced to play four player 35 minutes or more, while
Texas had the luxury of sending seven players to the court for 18
or more minutes with only Mihm and Gabe Muoneke playing more than
30.
</P>
<P>
   Tech was playing its first game without center Andy Ellis, who
is out for the season with an injured shoulder. With Ellis and his
16.9 points and 8.9 rebounding averages on the sideline, arm in a
sling, his replacement, Johnny Phillips had four points and five
rebounds in 25 minutes. All three were season highs for the
little-used Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   Kennard got free down low against the bigger Longhorns for a
pair of layups, Layne added a dunk, and Mitchell threw home a
two-handed stuff following up a Young miss to pull Tech within
39-38 with 12:16 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams drilled a 3-pointer, and after a Young layup, Texas
regained its composure by reeling off seven straight points.
</P>
<P>
   Muoneke got it going with a one-handed touch pass to Kelly for a
3-pointer. Muoneke grabbed an offensive rebound off a missed free
throw and Mihm cashed it in with a spinning layup. Kelly converted
a long pass from Mihm for a basket to give the Longhorns a 49-40
lead. Tech would get no closer than seven points the rest of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the difference in the ballgame was they made plays
when they had to,'' Tech coach James Dickey said. ``Texas just made
more plays than we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickey was not about to accept kudos for just hanging around the
Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no moral victories just because we stayed close and
had a chance,'' he said. ``I'm not interested in being close. I'm
interested in victories.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
