<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-23 01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3814 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-RICE-SANJOSEST.-H     01-23 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RICE-SAN </SLUG>
 JOSE ST.-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Rice squanders late lead in 58-56 loss
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By NEAL FARMER &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
There are only so many of the games remaining on the schedule that
injury-riddled Rice could or should win, and Saturday's was one of
them.
</P>
<P>
   But San Jose State's David Egans made an uncontested layup with
two-tenths of a second remaining off a long pass from R.J. Powell
after Rice failed to get back on defense, capping an improbable
comeback for a 58-56 victory at Autry Court.
</P>
<P>
   Egans' basket capped a 7-0 San Jose State run to offset what had
been a five-point Rice lead with 1:06 left in the Western Athletic
Conference game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what the score was, I didn't know what the time
was,'' Egans said. ``I was just trying to get there as quick as
possible. What crossed my mind was whether I should dunk it or lay
it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice coach Willis Wilson said he thought he had seen everything
that could happen in a college contest before witnessing the late
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody told me when I got into coaching that every day
you'll see something you've never seen before,'' Wilson said.
``That's an example of the things you see in college basketball.
Tonight was a night we had a chance to control the outcome of the
game, and we just did not do a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   It looked like the Owls had this game won. Rice guard Michael
Walton has deftly put in a jumper as the shot clock wound down to
give Rice a 56-51 lead at the 1:06 mark.
</P>
<P>
   But on SJSU's ensuing possession, guard Billy Landrum was fouled
by Rice center Alex Bougaieff outside the 3-point arc, and made two
of three free throws to draw the Spartans to within 56-53 with 52
seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Rice then tried to take time off the clock but, with 19 seconds
to go, a pass from Mike Wilks to Walton bounced off Walton's chest
and out of bounds. San Jose missed a shot, but Darnell Williams
grabbed the offensive rebound and scored _ and he was fouled by
Bougaieff. He converted his game-high 22nd point to tie the score
at 56.
</P>
<P>
   Wilks, who led Rice with 18 points, dribbled out front before
getting the ball inside to Jay Christian. But Christian's shot was
blocked by Williams, and the game took a surreal twist.
</P>
<P>
   Rice players neglected to get back on defense as Powell took
control of the ball. He spotted Egans streaking alone up the court.
Egans took the pass in for the winning layup that stunned the Autry
Court crowd of 2,413.
</P>
<P>
   Rice called two timeouts and SJSU one as each team tried to see
how the other would line up for the Owls' last play, which would
require a length-of-the-court pass. With only two-tenths of a
second left, the Owls could not grab an inbounds pass but only tip
the ball. After a successful pass, a tip by Bougaieff missed the
mark and the Spartans escaped with the emotional victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking it was going to go into overtime,'' said SJSU
coach Steve Barnes. ``But the (game-winning) play developed so
quickly. We kicked it out before they got back.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time that San Jose State (11-8, 2-2) has
defeated Rice in four meetings. The victory broke a 16-game
regular-season road conference losing streak for the Spartans,
dating back to Feb. 25, 1997, at San Diego State.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, saddled with a seven-game losing streak, drops to 4-11,
0-4 in league play.
</P>
<P>
   Can Rice overcome the draining loss and win again this year?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if our guys believe that tonight was our best chance
to win, then we won't win a game,'' Wilson said. ``But if we
believe in ourselves and continue to get better and improve as a
team, and execute and learn from our mistakes, then we are going to
beat teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we think anything other than that, then we are not going to
win a game. I don't believe that and I don't think our players
believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
