<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYMPIC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMARANCH STILL HAS A DANCE STEP OR TWO
</HEADLINE>
 REPORT-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   His flamenco days are behind him, but Juan Antonio Samaranch can
still dance.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking before a House of Representatives subcommittee last
month, the Spanish-born president of the International Olympic
Committee deftly dodged bureaucratic bullets and soft-shoed any
notion of a premature resignation.
</P>
<P>
   What the panel of eight lawmakers was trying to do, other than
shamelessly grandstand like Rep. Joe Barton (R-Texas), is unclear.
The subcommittee sought Olympic reforms, but Samaranch beat them to
it, unveiling the IOC's to-do list before he ever got to Capitol
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Barton wanted the 79-year-old Samaranch to resign on the spot, a
suggestion that smacked of American arrogance. I'll go if that
misbehaving president of yours goes, Samaranch could have said.
</P>
<P>
   One more time: Samaranch isn't resigning. His term expires in
2001, and there is every indication that he will stay the course
till the end. The storm of last year's scandal clearly has passed,
as evidenced by the announcement last week that two major Internet
sponsors and the Marriott hotel chain had signed on as Olympic
sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch can rightfully cite progress on Olympic reforms,
because as former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger _ a wise
choice as a member of the IOC's reform commission _ said, ``There
was not a single proposal that we made which was not accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   Barton, Texas' own, showed his tackiness by disparaging
Samaranch for his alleged preference for the title ``Your
Excellency.'' The weak chiding fails to consider that the IOC is an
absurdly diverse group, whose ranks indeed include princes, sultans
and assorted royalty. The ``Excellency'' title, which Samaranch has
not encouraged in recent years, is a bow to old protocol.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch doesn't understand why IOC matters are any U.S.
legislator's business. He fails to acknowledge that we must subject
him to the same scrutiny that we would any other foreign
businessman whose firm regularly takes away billions of American
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the subcommittee persisted, grilling the IOC leader on
things like his wife's all-expenses-paid trip to Atlanta in 1990. A
congresswoman from Colorado argued that gifts to IOC members should
be banned.
</P>
<P>
   Sure. That sort of stuff never happens to U.S. politicians.
Right.
</P>
<P>
   If asked again to testify, Samaranch said that, of course, he
would come to address the subcommittee again.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were only asking questions to get information,''
Samaranch told reporters with a shrug after the first inquisition.
</P>
<P>
   His Excellency, in other words, can still dance.
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:SPOTLIGHT ON ...
Cancer latest obstacle for triathlete
There was a point, somewhere among the 26 miles of running in the
Hawaii Ironman triathlon, when Karen Smyers was passed by an old
rival.
</P>
<P>
   But Smyers wasn't thinking of losing. She was wondering about
the mystery of it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had convinced myself that there must be some mistake,'' said
the 38-year-old Lincoln, Mass., native.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `How could I be feeling this good and have cancer?'
''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Smyers has thyroid cancer. First feared after an
examination last September, she came back in October to finish
second at the Hawaii Ironman competition, completing the demanding
three events in 9 hours, 20 minutes, 40 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not Smyers' whole story.
</P>
<P>
   She was already an accomplished triathlete _ twice voted the
U.S. Olympic Committee's triathlete of the year _ when, in June
1997, she severed a hamstring muscle while trying to change a storm
window. She was forced to miss the race of the triathlon season.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1998, Smyers gave birth to her daughter Jenna by Cesarean
section. Three months later, she competed in the Goodwill Games.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 12 of that year, Smyers was out training when a
semi-truck struck her, breaking six ribs and separating a shoulder.
Again, she had to miss the rest of the triathlon season.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1999, Smyers returned to competition, placing fourth
at a triathlon in Chile. In July, she was selected by team captains
to carry the U.S. flag in the opening ceremonies of the Pan
American Games.
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, she went to the doctor to be treated for
bronchitis and mentioned that she thought her neck glands were
swollen. The doctor scheduled an ultrasound examination, during
which six nodules were discovered in the area of her thyroid.
</P>
<P>
   Smyers kept training. ``The first few days after finding out
were a little bit tough,'' she said. ``I was kind of thinking
what's the point of training for the Ironman when you have cancer?'
</P>
<P>
   ``But I kind of realized that I wasn't going to just lay down
and give up. So I might as well continue on. I wasn't feeling bad
or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   No, the pain part came in November. That's when Smyers crashed
her bicycle while trying to avoid a fallen cyclist. Smyers suffered
a broken collarbone.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I guess, after hearing all that, no one wants to get on an
airplane with me, right?'' Smyers joked.
</P>
<P>
   Thyroid cancer strikes an estimated 16,000 Americans each year.
It is a slow-progressing cancer, said Smyers' physician, Dr.
William Burtis of Concord, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 10-year survival rate with this type of cancer is about 98
percent,'' Burtis said. ``The fact that Karen is an elite athlete
in optimum physical condition, I'm sure, is all to her benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   Four weeks ago, Smyers underwent six hours of surgery to have
her thyroid and two lymph nodes removed. With her doctor's
approval, she has decided to postpone the next phase, a radioactive
iodine treatment, until after the Olympic Trials in Irving on May
27-28.
</P>
<P>
   Smyers said she has taken strength from cyclist Lance Armstrong,
a testicular cancer survivor, and from a Canadian, rower Emma
Robinson, who had the same disease as Smyers yet came back to win a
world championship six months later.
</P>
<P>
   ``My role model,'' Smyers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luckily,'' she added, ``I'm not new to overcoming obstacles
and challenges, given the last couple of years. So I'm kind of
taking all this in stride.''
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:QUICK HITS Olympic appeal \Nagatea:A Harris Poll of
American kids and teen-agers showed that the Olympic Games are
their favorite sporting event.
</P>
<P>
   According to the recent poll, 81 percent of young people, ages 6
to 17, enjoy watching the Olympics on TV.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of name recognition, the poll reported that 91 percent
know what the Olympics is, compared with 88 percent for the Super
Bowl and 87 percent for the World Series. Among those who said they
liked a particular event ``a lot,'' the Olympics was first,
followed in order by the X Games, Super Bowl and World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is particularly important to see that the Olympic Games
appeal to children, many of whom have only had the opportunity to
see one or two Olympic Games in their lifetime,'' said David
Ogrean, the marketing deputy director of the USOC.
</P>
<P>
   ``The appeal of the Olympic Games seems to be something that is
passed on from parents and older siblings to younger children.''
\Nsubheds:Cycling, wrestling set \Nagatea:Road trials for spots on
the U.S. Olympic cycling team will be held May 20 in Jackson, Miss.
Mountain bike trials will take place in Phoenix, March 4-8. And the
track event trials are set for April 25-29 in Frisco.
</P>
<P>
   Wrestling's Olympic Trials will be held at Reunion Arena in
Dallas, June 22-24. \Nsubheds:U.S. trial dates \Nagatea:
</P>
<P>
   Gymnastics: Artistic, Aug. 15-20 in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing: Tampa, Fla., Feb. 9-13. Olympic Team Box-offs,
Mashantucket, Conn., Feb. 26-29.
</P>
<P>
   Swimming: Aug. 9-16, Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Track and field: Sacramento, Calif., July 14-23.
</P>
<P>
   Summer Olympics: Sydney, Australia, Sept. 15-Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Winter Olympics: Salt Lake City, Feb. 8-24, 2002. \Ntagtop:Gil
LeBreton, (817) 390-7760 \Ntagbottom:lebreton\Nstar-telegram.com
