<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-23 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3819 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-GYM-ATLER-COMEBACK-TE     01-23 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GYM-ATLER-COMEBACK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRESH START HAS OLYMPIC HOPEFUL VANESSA ATLER BACK ON THE BEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEIDI PEDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLANO, Texas _ Vanessa Atler's failures were becoming bigger
news than her successes.
</P>
<P>
   Atler, the 1996 U.S. junior gymnastics champion, had fallen
during a difficult release move in the uneven bars at the past
three U.S. Championships. In each of the past two years, the fall
cost her the senior all-around title and raised questions about why
she would risk performing the move.
</P>
<P>
   Then Atler left her California gym one month before the 1999
World Championships in China. At the Worlds in October, the lack of
regular training _ and a sore ankle _ resulted in an underwhelming
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Atler returned home feeling underwhelmed about the sport. When
she found out her ankle was broken, she debated whether to quit.
</P>
<P>
   She decided instead to make a fresh start. Following the advice
of renowned gymnastics coach Bela Karolyi, she moved to Plano and
the World Olympic Gymnastics Academy, where she has rekindled her
interest _ and potential _ heading into the 2000 Summer Olympic
Games in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew I didn't really want to quit. That's not the
kind of person I am,'' said Atler, who will turn 18 next month. ``I
just wanted to be happy again, and I feel awesome now. My goal is
to go over \Rto Sydney\S and win.''
</P>
<P>
   Atler says she is on the right path again. In Plano, she trains
under coach and World Olympic co-owner Valeri Liukin, the 1988
Olympic men's all-around silver medalist and high-bar champion from
the former Soviet Union. The gym has several national team members,
but Atler is its first star.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she got here, we needed to pump her up. She needs to
believe that she's a very good gymnast,'' Liukin said. ``She's got
a desire to be the best. If everything's right, I think she can
be.'' \Nsubheds:DOWNFALL \Nbody:Atler said she has waited a long
time for things to be ``right'' again.
</P>
<P>
   Things started going wrong in 1997, she said, at about the same
time her coaches at Covina's Gliders Gymnastics inserted a
particularly difficult release move into her uneven-bars routine.
</P>
<P>
   Atler struggled with the move, named after Olympic gold medalist
Nadia Comaneci. The skill set the tone for the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   She achieved impressive results in international competition
when the skill was removed from her uneven bars routine. When it
was included, as it was in the 1997, 1998 and 1999 U.S. Senior
Championships, the almost inevitable fall cost her. She had to
settle for a tie as U.S. co-champion with Kristy Powell in 1997,
and lost the 1998 and 1999 crowns outright.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1999 nationals, Atler said it was her decision to keep
the move in her routine. Actually, she says now, she wanted to take
the move out because it was as inconsistent in practice as it was
in competition.
</P>
<P>
   Atler said it was one of severaldisagreements she had with her
coaches, and the fall from the bars at the 1999 nationals may have
been the final straw. When she arrived home after the meet, she
told her parents she wanted to leave Gliders, where she had trained
since age 11, and her coaches, Steve and Beth Rybacki.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of little things added up, and I didn't really notice it
until championships. And it wasn't just the bars situation,'' Atler
said. ``It was more making me feel just like _ like I'm not good.
All of my confidence was down. That's not going to help me.''
</P>
<P>
   Atler's parents, Ted and Nanette, said they weren't shocked by
their daughter's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it coming probably in the last year or so. She just
wasn't too happy in the gym,'' Nanette Atler said. ``I think it
worked really well in the beginning. The problem was when she
matured and started to become her own woman. She couldn't speak her
own mind.''
</P>
<P>
   After USA Gymnastics officials agreed to fly in a national team
coach to temporarily train Atler at another local gym, Ted Atler
phoned the Rybackis to inform them of the decision. Beth Rybacki, a
1980 Olympian, said the call came as a total surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no problem as far as we understood. There was really
no explanation. We never spoke to \RVanessa\S,'' she said. ``Our
relationship with that athlete could not have been any better.
Vanessa always did everything we asked her to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Atler said she would have preferred to fade into the background
for awhile, but instead went to the World Championships with the
U.S. team and temporary coach Arthur Akopian. In China, she had to
deal not only with the presence of Steve Rybacki, who was coaching
fellow team member Jamie Dantzscher, but an ever-worsening left
ankle injury she had originally suffered at a meet in March in
France. \Nsubheds:UPSWING \Nbody:Atler said Rybacki's presence
wasn't a problem, but the ankle was. It showed in her performance.
She hit all four routines in team preliminaries to qualify seventh
into the all-around competition but faltered in the final to place
31st overall. Citing her injured ankle, she withdrew from floor
exercise and balance beam finals.
</P>
<P>
   The experience was enough to make Atler consider quitting,
especially after an X-ray revealed a bone chip in her sore ankle.
After the chip was removed by arthroscopic surgery Nov. 1, Atler
sought Karolyi's advice and moved into a Plano apartment with her
mother. Ted Atler, an electrical technician for the U.S. Postal
Service, and brother Teddy, 20, remained in Valencia.
</P>
<P>
   Atler said she immediately felt at home when she arrived Nov.
13. She liked Plano so well, she said, that not even another bone
chip, discovered in a follow-up exam in Dallas that week, could
dash her hopes. She had surgery to remove the second chip Nov. 30.
She wore a brace on her foot for six weeks, and she recently
started working out on all four events again.
</P>
<P>
   ``\RThe injury\S has actually helped me a lot, in a way, because
I want to do gymnastics so bad now,'' she said. ``And I've worked
out on bars so much that I've learned all of these new skills.
\RLiukin is\S going to put in a lot more turns and stuff, which is
what I've always wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Liukin, for his part, said he has no complaints about his new
pupil.
</P>
<P>
   ``She helps me a lot, actually. She listens and says yes all the
time, and the other kids see that,'' he said. ``She has the
discipline. It kind of proves to them that this is the way to be a
champion.''
</P>
<P>
   Liukin said Atler could make her 2000 debut at the American
Classic in Reno, Nev., next month, but might compete in only one
event. Her first major all-around competition will likely be the
Pacific Alliance Championships in April in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   Atler said she thinks she'll be ready for the biggest test,
which should come in the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I worry about is if \Rthe recovery\S is going
to take a long time, but my ankle's getting better every day,'' she
said. ``Other than that, I don't have many worries because I know
that when I'm happy I do really well.''  &LR; tagtop:Heidi Pederson
(817) 685-3872  &LR; tagbottom:hpederson &LR; star-telegram.com
</P>
<P>
   &LR; subheds:The Atler file  &LR; agatea: Birthdate: Feb. 17, 1982
</P>
<P>
   Residence: Plano
</P>
<P>
   Year in school: 12th
</P>
<P>
   School: Home-schooled
</P>
<P>
   Began gymnastics: 1987
</P>
<P>
   Years on national team: 6
</P>
