<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS' BUYER FANCIES BIRD OR THOMAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The mere fact that Mark Cuban picked up the phone a couple of
weeks ago and called Michael Jordan's people about his availability
sends a strong signal that the Mavericks' new owner is planning to
make a big splash in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine Jordan, if you will, as part-owner and president of
basketball operations of the Mavericks. Had Cuban purchased the
team's controlling interest in November, say, that notion might
have come to fruition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had I done something earlier, yeah, I would have talked to him
earlier,'' Cuban said. ``Maybe there would have been a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have explored all options. Woulda, coulda, shoulda.''
</P>
<P>
   Sources said Cuban will pursue Isiah Thomas or Larry Bird to do
for the Mavericks what Jordan is doing for the Washington Wizards.
</P>
<P>
   Bird, an Indiana native, has said this is his final season as
coach of the Indiana Pacers. Thomas, who played some pickup
basketball games against Cuban at Indiana University, did a
marvelous job turning the Toronto Raptors into a respectable
franchise when he was vice president of basketball operations and
general manager.
</P>
<P>
   To the possibility of Bird or Thomas joining the Mavericks,
Cuban would only say: ``I will explore all options, and it will be
fun doing so.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan took over a Wizards team Wednesday that has
characteristics similar to the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   The Wizards haven't won a playoff game since 1988; the Mavericks
haven't won a playoff game since 1988. The Wizards only have been
to the playoffs once in the past 11 seasons; the Mavericks only
have been to the playoffs once in the past 11 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a stretch to think that Jordan wouldn't have taken a
strong look at what Cuban had to offer if Ross Perot Jr. had sold
this team to Cuban earlier. Sources said Cuban wanted Jordan so
much he would have offered him anything, because he knows the
worldwide respect and publicity the downtrodden Mavericks would
have received.
</P>
<P>
   More than 400 media members showed up at MCI Center in
Washington last week to see Jordan tell the world he's back in the
NBA. Just think, that scene could have taken place at Reunion
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been great to get Jordan,'' Mavericks forward
Cedric Ceballos said. ``He's a good friend and a great player, and
a tremendous individual.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been great to have him a part of this team. Hey,
\RJordan\S can always sell his share in the Wizards and join us.''
 &LR; subheds:SPOTLIGHT ON ... Heir apparent guarded about teaming with
Air Jordan
Detroit Pistons All-Star forward Grant Hill has been called the
second-coming of Michael Jordan. Now, he's knocking down persistent
rumors that he will be joining Jordan in Washington when he becomes
a free agent July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, who left yesterday's game against the Chicago Bulls after
falling hard on his tailbone, is from Reston, Va., which is close
to Washington, D.C. Jordan is now part-owner and president of
basketball operations for the Washington Wizards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what \RJordan's\S role is or anything like
that,'' Hill said. ``I don't know what he's doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't thought, not one bit, about \Rgoing back to the
Washington area\S. I like coming home and playing against the team
I grew up watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, Hill added with a chuckle: ``I'd probably see too much of
my parents, and I don't know if that's good or bad.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not good for Pistons coach Alvin Gentry that he has to
constantly hear of the places Hill will play next season. So Gentry
resorted to sarcasm when asked about Hill's Wizards connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course he'd want to come back \Rto Washington\S,'' Gentry
said. ``Why wouldn't he?''
 &LR; subheds:AROUND THE EAST  &LR; agatea:Now that Jamal Mashburn finally is
having a breakout season for Miami, Heat coach Pat Riley believes
it's time to trade him.
</P>
<P>
   Go figure, but that's life in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Riley criticized Mashburn before Tuesday's home loss to lowly
Chicago and now is reportedly trying to trade him to Philadelphia
for guard Larry Hughes and forward Billy Owens.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Nets forward Jamie Feick, who went into yesterday's
game against the Mavericks fifth in the NBA in rebounds with 11.7
per game, has found himself in the doghouse of coach Don Casey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to say,'' Feick said. ``I have not had a
conversation with \RCasey\S. I don't know what is going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Feick was upset he was pulled early from Monday's game against
Philadelphia after he tossed up a pair of bad shots. Feick wound up
with only four rebounds in 23 minutes against the Philadelphia
76ers.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later against New York, Feick played only eight minutes
and got one rebound _ and he never left the bench in the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's game against Detroit, Feick regained Casey's good
graces. He started the game and collected 13 of his career-high 25
rebounds in the first quarter of the 122-120 victory against the
Pistons.
</P>
<P>
   Heat point guard Tim Hardaway returned to action Friday for the
first time after missing 26 games with a jammed right knee.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte Hornets guard David Wesley might be charged for his
part in the death of teammate Bobby Phills, according to Charlotte,
N.C., police.
</P>
<P>
   Wesley and Phills were racing _ police said speeds exceeded 100
mph _ when Phills lost control of his Porsche and died at the
scene.
 &LR; subheds:AROUND THE WEST  &LR; agatea:The Portland Trail Blazers are
concerned they can't depend on forward Rasheed Wallace to be on the
court in crunch time.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace recently got ejected from consecutive games against
Phoenix and the Mavericks and has received 80 technical fouls in
226 regular season games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he understands that it's hurting our team, and I don't
think he wants to hurt our team,'' Blazers coach Mike Dunleavy
said. ``The thing is, it's to the point now where he has to be
careful, because other teams will try to bait him if they know they
can get to him like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be like in the old days, when coaches would send in
some stiff to try to rile a guy and get him ejected.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix guard Penny Hardaway has started light practices and
plans to play during the Suns' East Coast trip that begins Jan. 25
against the Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway, who has missed 21 games with a foot injury, is likely
to play when the Suns face his old Orlando Magic team at the
Orlando Arena on Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just Orlando,'' Hardaway said. ``Hopefully, I'll be
playing before Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing is the doctors have told me when I go out
there, I'm going to have some side effects. There's going to be
some pain, and I may be hobbling sometimes. It's just a matter of
how much pain can you take.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle had won seven consecutive games before losing Friday to
Boston. That winning stretch included a victory in Los Angeles
against the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota, which suffered an embarrassing home loss to the
Mavericks on Dec. 4, apparently has gotten its act together. The
Timberwolves have won eight of their past nine road games and are
within 3 1/2 games of first-place Utah in the Midwest Division.
</P>
</TEXT>
