<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S GOOD PRIME TIME WON'T BECOME A RERUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is time to say goodbye to Deion Sanders, and wasn't it a
hoot?
</P>
<P>
   All those punt returns. And all those lizard-green outfits.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived under a one-word anthem: ``both.'' And he leaves
wanting to do neither, neither play offense nor defense.
</P>
<P>
   Not for the Cowboys, in any case. Not at the salary that Owner
Jones is prepared to offer, which won't be in the same tax bracket
as the $12.7-million salary cap figure that his contract said.
</P>
<P>
   Deion Sanders, Count Do-Rag _ worth $12.7 million?
</P>
<P>
   Even in his wackier, Owner Jethro-worst days, Jones wouldn't try
to claim that. It simply makes good business sense to void Sanders'
contract and to let him go. Let him try to make the Cincinnati
Reds. Let him find another NFL locker room to preen in. Let him
find another owner who is enchanted by his Prime Time charms.
</P>
<P>
   Let him find another city to beguile, another church to preach
from, another newspaper (wince) to write a weekly column for.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, he can still play football. When he sheds the self-promotion
flora and fauna and tries to blend in with the team, Sanders can be
a defensive presence to reckon with.
</P>
<P>
   But at what price? Owner Jones paid him $12.99 million up-front
in 1995 to jump to the Cowboys. He has since made it an art form to
collect signing bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   Bonuses for jumping from the San Francisco 49ers. Bonuses from
rewording his contract. Bonuses from temporarily giving up
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   My numbers might be a little off, but Owner Jones can correct me
if I'm wrong. I calculate the final tab on Deion to be in the
neighborhood of $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   For one Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Was it worth it? Did you enjoy that one Super Bowl, Owner Jones?
</P>
<P>
   When you consider the retooling job that Jones is now strapped
with, the answer is more complicated than a simple no.
</P>
<P>
   No cornerback, no one defensive player, is worth even $10
million a year. Not as long as there is an NFL salary cap. The
impact that Sanders' disproportionate paycheck had on the Cowboys'
depth was best measured this past season _ an 8-9 season _ when
injuries forced strange faces into odd, nickel-defense places.
</P>
<P>
   Please don't quote that line about Sanders being ``the best
cover cornerback to ever play the game.'' It's become trite.
Without a supporting cast, Sanders made minimal impact on the
Cowboys' won-loss record.
</P>
<P>
   Another trite Deionism that needs to be put to rest is that
``he's great in the locker room.'' And when a team is winning,
maybe Sanders is.
</P>
<P>
   But when a team is winning, everybody whistles to work like the
Seven Dwarfs. When the worm turned at the end of this disappointing
season, Sanders was passing blame and trying to stab backs with the
best of them. Remember when he left the 49ers and then trash-talked
about Jerry Rice?
</P>
<P>
   Granted, he was fun for awhile. Count Do-Rag was Owner Jones'
rich toy, an All-Pro with a cartoon personality. A Nike darling.
</P>
<P>
   But desperate times call for desperate assessments, and by any
accounting, Sanders' tenure with the Cowboys was an expensive
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys fans will always wonder what impact his $40 million,
distributed more wisely, could have had on Chan Gailey's two teams.
</P>
<P>
   His days here are numbered and, judging by his baseball
announcement, he knows that. His renegotiated contract was meant to
be voided, or Jones would have been on the hook for $10.5 million
in base salary in the 2000 season and $13 million in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Under the rules, Jones has to time it properly, in order to both
release Sanders and to be able to spread his remaining signing
bonus over another season. The target date is June 2. If he is let
loose on that date, Sanders would count $2.2 million against the
cap and $3.2 million in 2001. If he is released this week, he would
count for $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   But that's just the financial loose ends. Psychologically, the
parting has already begun to occur. You could tell it in Sanders'
voice as the season gurgled down the drain.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it wasn't about the nightclub that he owned, or the
clothes that he wore. It wasn't about his newfound religion, or
even about last week's news that he wants to use his baseball
career as leverage.
</P>
<P>
   No, it was about Deion Sanders, who could both amaze and amuse.
And for all his antics and theatrics, helped bring the Cowboys one
Super Bowl in five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many Prime Time acts, his had become tiresome.
</P>
<P>
   And it's time to say goodbye.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
