<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-MORROW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' MORROW MATURING A SEASON EARLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Simon Gonzalez 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ According to the Stars' master plan, Brenden
Morrow was supposed to be playing for the Michigan K-Wings, honing
his skills in hockey's minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scouting staff and management pretty much made me feel
that I'd play the season in Kalamazoo and then I'd get my chance
next year,'' said Morrow, the team's first-round draft pick in the
1997 draft.
</P>
<P>
   The master plan, though, is out for the season. It's on the
shelf after suffering concussions, broken ankles, chest contusions,
bruised ribs, separated shoulders and strained groins.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries to virtually every forward forced the Stars to bring
Morrow off the farm prematurely. Instead of clashing with
youngsters in the International Hockey League, he'll be playing in
his 30th NHL game tonight in Chicago. Instead of gaining experience
in Kalamazoo, the 21-year-old rookie will be playing alongside Mike
Modano on the Stars' first line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't make that big of a deal of it,'' Morrow said. ``I
realize injuries have forced them to make these decisions, and if
there weren't so many injuries I wouldn't be on the first line. I
just look at it as an opportunity to get some ice time, and try to
make the best of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrow indeed is making the best of it. He has 10 points on five
goals and five assists in 29 games. More importantly, he plays the
high-energy, hard-nosed grinding and checking game that coach Ken
Hitchcock's defense-first system demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you like about Morrow is that there's not very many games
that Brenden doesn't show up and play hard,'' Hitchcock said. ``He
plays physical, he's got good speed, and he's got sneaky-good
skill. The skill that he plays with kind of grows on you after a
while. The way our team plays, he's a very effective player.''
</P>
<P>
   He was especially effective playing on the first line with
Modano and Blake Sloan in Los Angeles on Thursday. Each player
scored an even-strength goal in the Stars' 5-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``They play real simple and basic,'' Modano said. ``They don't
try to do anything outside their realm as players. They skate well,
they play hard along the boards. That's where the game is played
nowadays. There's not a lot of open ice, but when it does come
they're able to play that style too because they've got the
speed.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of game that made Morrow a standout in junior
hockey and a first-round draft pick. At 5-foot-11 and 210 pounds,
he can play physically.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a pretty big physical force,'' Sloan said. ``It helps
create room for other people on the ice. It gets the other team's
defensemen looking over their shoulders a little bit knowing that
he's out there, and that might give us that one extra step.''
</P>
<P>
   He also has the skills to put the puck in the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'll ever get 50 goals or not, but I've always
played the same style game, grinding it out in the corners, and
I've still ended up scoring quite a few goals,'' Morrow said.
``I'll probably be a two-way player who can add a little offense.''
</P>
<P>
   A great deal of Morrow's offense comes from directly in front of
the net. He posts up by the goal, seemingly impervious to the large
defensemen who beat on him trying to move him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind taking it,'' he said. ``Usually you get rewarded
when you're in front of the net. The puck will go in off your leg
or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Injuries brought Morrow to the Stars a year ahead of schedule.
But that attitude, combined with his skills and tenacity, could
have him in the NHL to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's earned the right to play here,'' Hitchcock said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
