<SLUG> BC-BKC-BOSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC CAN'T SHAKE ITS COLD SPELL 
</HEADLINE>
 COLLEGE-MIAMI-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The moment he stepped off the plane from frigid Boston
Friday evening and was greeted by South Florida's siren song _
bienvenidos a Miami _ and its tropical climate, Troy Bell came to
the same realization most Minnesota snowbirds do upon their winter
arrival at Miami International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew this was the place for me,'' said Boston College's
freshman guard from Minneapolis. ``I can't live in Minnesota and I
definitely can't live in Boston. But this place is beautiful . .
.'' Then he wondered aloud, ``Is this (the way it is) all year
round for them?''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that would have made this trip better for Bell
and his teammates was a victory in Saturday &UR;  &LR; night's Big East
matchup against the Miami Hurricanes. But the Eagles (9-8, 1-4)
remained frozen stiff by an abominable cold snap in conference road
games _ dropping their third straight this season and 16th in a row
overall _ in Saturday &UR;  &LR; night's 62-54 setback against the Hurricanes
(11-7, 4-2) before a crowd of 5,210 at American Airlines Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The game was scheduled to be at Miami Arena but was switched to
the Miami Heat's new state-of-the-art-deco building when a cold
water line was accidentally ruptured by a city work crew, leaving
Miami Arena without air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   Miami coach Leonard Hamilton, whose team got a career-high 24
points from senior center Mario Bland, indicated that school
officials opted to move the game because of the threat of injury to
players.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Eagles certainly could have put a chill in the place
with their frostbitten shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we really have to focus on ourselves and what it is
we have to do in order to be effective,'' said BC coach Al Skinner.
``We've got to get back to the basics and what our principles are
both offensively and defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   BC got 20 points from Bell, the only Eagle in double figures.
Bell shot 4 for 15 from the field, including 2 of 8 from 3-point
range, but made 10 of his 11 free throws. He has gone 15 for 58 in
BC's four-game skid, and Saturday &UR;  &LR; night had a bag of ice taped to
his shooting hand after the game. Bell aggravated a nagging injury
when he banged his right hand off Johnny Hemsley's knee with 5:16
to go.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of BC's starters combined for 16 points on 7-for-20
shooting. Xavier Singletary was held scoreless, going 0 for 5.
Overall, BC shot 30 percent (17 of 56) and committed 23 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   What bothered Skinner most, though, were the defensive lapses
his team suffered during crucial stretches of the game. ``If we do
the job defensively, then we're in the ballgame,'' he said. ``But
we were totally lost on defense.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Eagles fought back from a 12-point deficit with a 15-7
run in the last 4:29 of the first half to pull within 30-27 at
halftime, BC wound up committing several defensive gaffes that
enabled Miami to reel off 9 unanswered points.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my shots were right around the goal,'' said Bland, who
became the 23d player in Miami history to score 1,000 career points
when he hit a free throw with 13:23 to go. ``But sometimes I'd turn
around and say to myself, `What happened to my defender?' The guys
just did a good job of getting the ball to me, and you have to take
advantage of that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
