A3829 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     01-23 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'NEAL SHOULD HAVE BEEN IN FOR THE FINISH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Shaquille O'Neal led the Lakers in scoring,
rebounds, assists, blocked shots and minutes Saturday against
Portland. He did everything but sing the national anthem and sink
free throws.
</P>
<P>
   For 47 minutes the Lakers' center created a vision of what a
league MVP looks like. And in the final seconds, he rested. It
wasn't his call, it was God's, or the Lakers' version thereof.
</P>
<P>
   First-year coach Phil Jackson made O'Neal, who missed three of
four shots from the foul line, just another Staples Center
spectator in the final seconds of a game the Lakers would go on to
lose, 95-91.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of having a chance to be a savior, O'Neal was just
another disciple questioning the man he has put his career and
reputation in the hands of.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just a peon around here. I just do what they say,'' a glum
O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   In his frown were the first signs all season of betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Damon Stoudamire, the Trail Blazers' hardy guard, was
saying a prayer of thanks for small favors. ``Heck, if you're going
to take Shaq out for the last play, we're glad to see that,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In Stoudamire's glee were the first signs that maybe Jackson is
human, after all.
</P>
<P>
   All those years with the Bulls, ``everybody thinks Phil was just
sitting there,'' said Lakers veteran guard Ron Harper, who played
under Jackson for five seasons in Chicago. ``Don't believe that.
Michael Jordan may have scored a lot. Phil had a hand in that,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   It's more impressive than an O'Neal no-look pass, more
intimidating than O'Neal rising in the paint to block a shot: In
less time than it took for the NBA and its players to agree on a
new collective bargaining agreement, Jackson has fashioned a team
ideology out of a roomful of ids.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Bill Bradley wanted Jackson's fingerprints on his
presidential campaign. Halfway through the NBA's 2000 primaries,
Jackson has the attention not only of his Lakers but of the rest of
the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's looking like he's back coaching Chicago again,''
Stoudamire said. ``He barks a command every now and then and then
goes and sits down.''
</P>
<P>
   Now if Jackson could just get the Lakers to routinely obey him.
They slipped into their old ways in the second half, wilting like a
piece of plastic exposed to extreme heat. The Trail Blazers' turned
up the intensity and the Lakers melted.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal had no rebounds in the third quarter after pulling down
14 in the first half. He had four points in his final 23 minutes.
To be fair, he must have felt less like the toast of the league
than a cork bobbing in a rough sea, what with the continuous waves
of players Portland sent at him.
</P>
<P>
   He was swimming in Trail Blazers jerseys. Brian Grant, Arvydas
Sabonis, Scottie Pippen and Rasheed Wallace took turns pulling at
him like an undertow. It was the kind of game that demanded that
Kobe Bryant or Glen Rice or Harper or somebody, for goodness sakes,
be the lifeline that towed O'Neal and the Lakers to the shores of
victory.
</P>
<P>
   But Bryant was weighed down by the four fouls he picked up in
the first three quarters, the last of them a piddling one with less
than two seconds remaining in the third. He would end up fouling
out before the Lakers' final, climactic possession.
</P>
<P>
   And Rice looked like he was fighting against the tide; he missed
all three shots he tried in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Fox was the closest thing the Lakers had to a go-to guy
down the stretch. So short of sending O'Neal in for the final 13.6
seconds and crossing his fingers and holding his breath, there
wasn't much Jackson could do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil's got (the Lakers) playing great defense, they're playing
well together and he's got them playing hard on both ends of the
court,'' said Pippen, who played his usual stellar game defensively
and also contributed 15 points. ``He's had a great impact on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not much Phil could do (Saturday). He couldn't go out
and score for them or defend.''
</P>
<P>
   The only things he could have done were play Travis Knight a few
more minutes in the first half and leave O'Neal in at the end. The
latter was a risk Jackson should have taken. O'Neal isn't going to
become a better foul shooter in clutch situations in April and May
by sitting on the bench in the final seconds of a close game in
January.
</P>
<P>
   The way he has played to this point, O'Neal had earned the
chance to surprise us.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-00 0250EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
