<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORABLE NIGHT FOR USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ No matter what else happens this season, USC won't
be able to top what happened Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans, supposedly reeling with two significant players
sidelined with fractures, stunned No. 2-ranked Arizona, 80-72, at
the Sports Arena in a battle between the Pacific-10 Conference's
unbeaten teams before 9,105 fans.
</P>
<P>
   USC hit eight straight free throws in the final minute to hold
off the Wildcats, and the crowd rushed the floor at the buzzer to
celebrate the victory, which gave the Trojans sole possession of
first place in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   USC won without forward Sam Clancy (fractured foot) or forward
Jarvis Turner (fractured ankle) while Arizona was without forward
Richard Jefferson (fractured foot). All three gathered on the floor
on crutches before the game.
</P>
<P>
   USC got career performances from forward Brian Scalabrine and
David Bluthenthal. Scalabrine had a career-high 27 points while
Bluthenthal had a career-high 26.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps inspired by the absence of Clancy or Turner, USC came
out and played its most inspired game of the season. They even did
it by playing such little-used reserves as freshmen Kostas
Charissis, Nate Hair and Malachi Thurston.
</P>
<P>
   They held the lead because the core players remained hot,
especially Scalabrine.
</P>
<P>
   He had 15 points in the first half and quickly hit two shots to
open the second half. He had 23 points with 14:30 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Bluthenthal also made up for Clancy's absence, scoring 18 points
in the first 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans were almost a two-man team offensively in that span,
because starters Brandon Granville and Jeff Trepagnier were both
having subpar performances.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans (12-5, 5-0) were clinging to a 65-59 lead with 3:23
left, despite using an unlikely mix of veterans, freshmen and
walk-ons.
</P>
<P>
   But USC had no answer for 7-foot-1 center Loren Woods, who
scored 21 points, point guard Jason Gardner (25) and former Grant
High star Gilbert Arenas, who had 16.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona (16-3, 5-1) dominated under the basket, outrebounding
the Trojans, 23-12 in the first half, including nine offensive
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, the Trojans were shutting down forward Michael
Wright, who scored only one point in the first half. He entered the
contest as Arizo na's second-leading scorer (14.8 points per game).
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans, already facing a player shortage, appeared in deep
trouble when point guard Brandon Granville picked up his third foul
with 10:27 left in the first half. But Bibby did not substitute,
and Granville managed to play the rest of the half without getting
his fourth foul.
</P>
<P>
   Charissis played 11 minutes in the half, more than his combined
total in USC's first four Pac-10 games and no points, no rebounds
and two steals.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams used just seven players in the half.
</P>
<P>
   USC's depth was so thin that Trojans coach Henry Bibby was
reduced to inserting 6-5 walk-on Abdullah Elmagbari in the second
half, after Bluthenthal got his fourth foul with 10:16 left.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-00 0316EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
