<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-HORNETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORNETS PUT END TO CELTICS' STREAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ Life without Paul Pierce wasn't pretty the
last time around. It was just as bad Saturday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce went down early with a hamstring injury and the Celtics'
four-game winning streak went the same way. In a nearly empty
Charlotte Coliseum _ a liberal estimate would be 4,000 _ the
undermanned Celtics dropped a 110-96 decision to the Hornets.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Pitino talked afterward about his short-tempered players
having the ``diplomacy of Stalin'' with the referees, as Antoine
Walker (5 of 15, 11 points) and Kenny Anderson (4 of 15) each did
their Rasheed Wallace imitations and got technicals. But it was the
injury to Pierce that really hurt, given the Celtics already were
shorthanded with Calbert Cheaney (family situation) and Eric
Williams (knee) already out.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce said he strained his left hamstring diving for a loose
ball going out of bounds in the first quarter. He played only 11
minutes and sat on the bench the rest of the game with his leg
taped. This was the same building in which he badly sprained his
ankle last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a curse here for me,'' Pierce said. ``I come to
Charlotte and I get hurt. It bothered me, so I couldn't finish the
game. This has never happened to me before, so we'll see. If I was
a doctor, I'd tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino wasn't much more revealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what his status will be,'' said Pitino. ``We'll
watch over the next few days.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach, however, was a tad upset with his short-fused
players. The Hornets attempted 37 free throws to the Celtics' 13.
The Celtics were called for 30 fouls to Charlotte's 19. Those
numbers bear out season-long trends: The Hornets lead the league in
free throw attempts while the Celtics commit the third most fouls
in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players have got the diplomacy of Stalin,'' said Pitino.
``They have no idea how to get calls. They're just stupid with
officials. Our players have no diplomacy whatsoever. It's like the
cold war with them. They don't understand it. They try to win the
verbal war with referees, they're going to come out and lose every
time. And they still haven't figured it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker, who has four technicals in the last five games, said he
found it hard to believe he never got to the line. That has
happened six times this season. ``It's frustrating,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Dana Barros, ``We were definitely frustrated, but you have
to keep your frustrations to yourself. The refs are human, too. We
can't afford to get that kind of reputation as a team. Once you get
that label, it's tough to lose it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the referees didn't let Charlotte shoot 52 percent or
collect 31 assists. Boston had trouble all night with Derrick
Coleman, who beat them up inside and outside with 24 points, 11
rebounds, and 3 blocks. Six Hornets were in double figures and
there was enviable shot distribution among those six.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made extra passes and got a lot of good, open looks,'' said
Eddie Jones, who had 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics got 18 points and 11 rebounds from Vitaly Potapenko
and 16 points off the bench from Danny Fortson. It easily was
Fortson's best outing, but, as he put it, ``It don't mean anything.
You might as well erase it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets led by 9 after one, by 15 at the half, and by 12
going into the fourth. The Celtics never mustered the necessary
defensive stand to make up any significant ground. In the second
half, they trailed by at least 10 for 23 of the 24 minutes. They
got as close as 8.
</P>
<P>
   They had trouble matching up against the bigger Hornets, made
evident by 16 points from old nemesis Brad Miller. Pitino had no
choice but to go small, admitting, ``It's not a pretty sight.'' He
had Doug Overton playing small forward at one point. Coleman (8 of
11 from the field) killed them down the stretch. He scored 8
straight points to offset a pair of Fortson hoops when the Celtics
were looking like they might do something.
</P>
<P>
   After a Fortson layup made it 95-87, Coleman stepped out and
drained a trey.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really killed us,'' said Walker.
</P>
<P>
   After a Fortson dunk (off a Walker miss), Coleman bulled his way
in for a 3-point play. That made it 101-89 with 3:48 left and
finished off the Celtics for good. At that point, even a flight to
Miami in a snowstorm looked to be comforting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
