<HEADLINE>
ATTN. EDITORS:  

</HEADLINE>
  
 For Immediate Release
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ``Seldom courted, never fully avoided, adversity is an
advantage. At least in politics, and probably in life, too.'' With
those words, Boston Globe Washington Bureau chief David M. Shribman
introduces an overview of this year's presidential primary
candidates. The profiles, by Globe staff writers working the
campaign beat, present the candidates against the lifetime of
challenges they encountered on the way to the race for the nation's
highest elected office.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARY-ADVERSITY (Undated) _ Turning points. Dancers have them.
So do skiers, cars, and screenplays. But politicians have them
also. And oftentimes a political figure's turning point can become
America's turning point, too. By David M. Shribman. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARY-GORE (Undated) _ He was a young newspaper reporter on
the lookout for his next big story, when Al Gore got the tip that
would forever change his life. By Ann Scales and Susan Milligan. (2
takes)
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARY-BRADLEY (New York) -- As Bill Bradley enters a crucial
phase of his quest for the Democratic presidential nomination, the
story of how he confronted _ and overcame _ his greatest failure
provides a window on both his character and the quirks of
circumstance that helped shape his life. By Bob Hohler. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARY-BUSH (Washington) _ The parable of the prodigal son is a
big part of Bush lore. It started with George W. Bush's
oft-repeated admission that ``when I was young and irresponsible, I
sometimes behaved young and irresponsibly. By Mary Leonard. (2
takes)
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARY-MCCAIN (Washington) _ John McCain is 63 now, and his
father and grandfather are long dead. But his story must begin with
them, for it is hard to overestimate the impact that their legacy
had on his life. By John A. Farrell. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARY-FORBES (Undated) -- Steve Forbes went from being a
passionately private multimillionaire, a man who laughed off talk
of running for president, into a politically energized campaigner,
convinced that he was the savior of the Republican Party. By
Michael Kranish. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARY-KEYES (Undated) _ Ordinarily, Alan Keyes avoids even
such veiled references to his race, though he has spoken of it
sometimes, particularly when he is explaining what he sees as the
lack of respect given his candidacy. By Yvonne Abraham. 850 words.
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARY-BAUER (Undated) _ The most important night of Gary
Bauer's life began in less than ordinary fashion, as most nights
did for him back in 1964. By Yvonne Abraham. 770 words.
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARY-HATCH (Undated) _ Orrin Hatch is profoundly
uncomfortable answering questions about his life outside his
23-year Senate career, handing over details of his childhood and
his family as if each one were a treasure. By Yvonne Abraham. 800
words.
</P>
<P>
   For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  All stories will bear the BOS
designator and move under the  &UR; Politics (p)  &LR; category code.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
