<P>
   TV-MALCOLM-SITCOM (Los Angeles) _ Out of nowhere _ and just as
people were predicting the death of the sitcom genre _ a new Fox
family comedy, ``Malcolm in the Middle,'' has sailed to the ratings
stratosphere, equaling ``Frasier.'' What impact will this have on
prime time? By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   TIMEWARNER-EMI (London) _ Time Warner plans to announce on
Monday that it will acquire EMI Recorded Music for about $1
billion, in a deal that would create the world's largest music
company. The acquisition would expand Time Warner's music catalog
as the company pursues its merger with America Online _ a merger in
which online distribution of music is expected to be the first big
market opportunity. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   TRANSMETA (San Francisco) _ The story behind TransMeta, the
pedigreed Silicon Valley chip designer that had been working behind
a veil of secrecy until last week, when it finally told the world
what it has been working on.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The Market Place column: The
Nasdaq composite index last week had its best performance ever,
compared with the Dow Jones industrial average. And high-flying
tech stocks were the reason. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-INTERTAINER (Los Angeles) _ In another step toward its
effort to extend its reach from the personal computer to the
television set, Microsoft Corp. is investing $56 million in
Intertainer Inc., a privately held company that provides a
video-on-demand service, executives of the company said. By Andrew
Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   AUTODEALER-ECOMMERCE (Orlando, Fla.) _ News from the auto
dealer's conference, where e-commerce is the preoccupation. By
Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   ECOMMERCE-COLUMN (Undated) _ In the world of
business-to-business Internet commerce, it has become difficult to
keep up with the rapid-fire creation of so-called e-marketplaces _
the darlings du jour of the investment community. The vast lineup
of newcomers to this e-commerce arena speaks to the riches they see
awaiting any company that can dominate a given business-to-business
sector. Internet marketplaces are part of a business-to-business
e-commerce industry that is expected by 2003 to reach $1.3 billion
in annual revenue _ more than 10 times the projected size of the
business-to-consumer market. But capturing that cash will prove
difficult, analysts said, and not just because of the growing
number of competitors in every category. By Bob Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   SUPERBOWL-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ The hoopla and hyperbole
surrounding the costly commercials that will run on Jan. 30 during
Super Bowl XXXIV has been intensified by the dozen or more dot-coms
scheduled to appear for the first time. And the noise is generating
a bit of a backlash centered on ``anti-advertising'': promotions,
public relations campaigns, sweepstakes and other efforts off the
gridiron to reach consumers. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   BIOTECH-CLONES (Undated) _ Britain last week became the first
country in the world to grant a patent covering cloned early-stage
human embryos, a move biotechnology critics say will ignite new
controversy even though the Geron Corp., the company licensed to
use the patent, has no intention of creating cloned humans. By
Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
