<P>
   &UR; FOR MONDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Monday, Jan. 24:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS (Jerusalem) _ While Israel and the
Palestinians will intensify negotiations over the next few weeks,
it is unlikely that they will reach a framework agreement by the
goal of mid-February, Israel's senior negotiator said Sunday. By
Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-WEIZMAN (Jerusalem) _ Israeli President Ezer Weizman said
late Sunday he would stay at his post in spite of a police
investigation into suspected tax fraud and corruption. (Summary
from wire.) By William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-POLITICS (Undated) _ With less than four weeks remaining
before Iran's 38-million voters elect a new Parliament, the
conservative Muslim clerics who have held the country in a rigid
political grip since 1979 have moved to shore up their power. By
John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   GENETIC-ENGINEERING-TRADE (Undated) _ Nearly a year after the
United States blocked a proposed global treaty to regulate trade in
genetically modified products, delegates from more than 130 nations
will resume negotiations Monday in Montreal. After months of
international concern about bioengineered food, Washington will be
on the defensive. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Grozny, Russia) _ Russian troops have reached
Grozny, but it is clear that they are not of the verge of victory.
By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-U.S. (Undated) _ When Richard C. Holbrooke took over as
Security Council president for January, he declared it the month of
Africa. But council members have been getting more than an
education on important African issues, from an AIDS epidemic to
multiple civil wars. They have also been absorbing some lessons in
U.S. politics, election-year style. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN-BOMB-PROTEST (Madrid, Spain) _ An estimated 1.1 million
people marched through downtown Madrid on Sunday to protest a
car-bomb attack seen as a resurgence of Basque separatists'
32-year-old campaign of violence. By Al Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-U.S. (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ The State Department is
backing the Serbian opposition. At the same time, Voice of America
and Radio Free Europe broadcasts have been cut back for lack of
funding. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-CULT (Tokyo) _ By changing its name and denouncing its
spiritual leader last week, the religious sect that killed 12
people in a nerve gas attack in the Tokyo subways in 1995 tried to
convince Japanese society that it was no longer a threat. But the
name change from Aum Shinrikyo to Aleph, which is the first letter
of the Hebrew alphabet and signifies renewal for many Japanese,
appears to have raised more fears than it calmed. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-KOHL (Berlin) _ A report that Kohl will tell all about
secret donors turns out to be a hoax. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   ROME-HOMELESS (Rome) _ Eight homeless people have died on the
streets of Rome since New Year's Eve, the start of the Vatican's
2,000 Jubilee, including a 60-year old woman who died near St.
Peter's basilica. Those deaths have caused shock and soul-searching
in a usually balmy capital where homelessness mostly used to seem
like a preoccupation of larger, harsher cities like New York or
Moscow. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GUARD (Austin, Texas) _ Early next month, nearly 800
men and women of the 49th Armored Division will board transport
planes and fly to Bosnia. Ultimately, they will take command of the
American sector in NATO's multinational operation there. The
Pentagon has deployed Guard and Reserve units overseas before; more
than 265,000 were called up to support the Persian Gulf war in
1990. But the 49th's mission is something new. Not since the Korean
War has a National Guard division commanded an overseas operation.
By Steven Lee Myers. (First article in a continuing series.)
</P>
<P>
   USC-ENTERTAINMENT-STUDIES (Los Angeles) _ Here in the city where
``entertainment'' means everything from a televised freeway chase
to a multimillion-dollar movie, the University of Southern
California is embarking on an ambitious inter-disciplinary effort
to study entertainment as a defining concept of 21st century life,
in fields from law to architecture, with the dual goal of prompting
intellectual debate and training the next generation of media
moguls. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHEAST-ICE-STORM (Atlanta) _ A storm swept through parts of
the mid Atlantic and Southeast states with rain, ice and snow early
Sunday, glazing highways and knocking out power to more than
300,000 customers in Georgia, about 270,000 of them in the Atlanta
metropolitan area. By David Firestone and Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Miami) _ The Cuban American National Foundation
(CANF) on Sunday offered to fly the two grandmothers of Elian
Gonzalez, the Cuban boy rescued from Florida waters in November, to
Miami to visit him and his relatives there, according to the wires.
The organization, which represents the large Cuban exile community
in Miami, said a private plane was being prepared to take them to
South Florida to visit Elian. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   AFTERSCHOOL-PROGRAMS (Undated) _ The explosion in after-school
programs _ federal funding alone has ballooned from $1 million in
1997 to $454 million this year _ represents nothing less than a
re-imagining of the school day for the first time in generations,
as educators and policymakers seek to respond to the realities of
working families and what may be missing from the classroom. By
Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA-SURVEY (Undated) _ This year's class of first-year college
students, having survived the most competitive higher-education
admissions process ever and saddled with increased family and
financial responsibilities, entered school more stressed out than
any in a generation, according to a national survey by researchers
at the University of California at Los Angeles. By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NOMINATION-REFORM (Chicago) _ Republican and Democratic Party
officials are already exploring ways to change a nominating system
that critics say has become too chaotic, too fast for informed
decision-making and, in some fundamental ways, undemocratic.
``Frankly, an awful lot of people feel they have no effective voice
in the selection process,'' said William Brock, the former senator
and Republican National Committee chairman. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-MEDIA (Des Moines, Iowa) _ For the past few days, Des
Moines has been the media capital of the world. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-ABORTION (Des Moines, Iowa) _ For George W. Bush, the
politics of abortion can be a minefield, and he knows it. By Frank
Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   IOWA-CAUCUS (Des Moines, Iowa) _ A primer on the process. By B.
Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   IOWA-RELIGIOUS-RIGHT (Des Moines, Iowa) _ It may not be the
overwhelming force it once was, but the religious right is still
breathing fire in Iowa. By Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SPEECHWRITER (Washington) _ J. Terry Edmonds is the
keeper of the disc. With just days to go before President Clinton
delivers the final State of Union speech of his presidency, there
is a mad scramble underway among aides and outsiders to insert a
paragraph, or just a sentence, or even a fleeting phrase, into the
final text. As the president's chief speechwriter, Edmonds is the
guardian of the computer disc containing the speech's latest draft,
and the coordinator of the policy proposals, accolades, reflections
and humorous asides that will pop up Thursday night on Clinton's
teleprompter. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Undated) _ Commentary; details TK. By William
Safire.
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN (Undated) _ Commentary; details TK. By Bob
Herbert.
</P>
