</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASDAQ-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: TECHNOLOGY STOCKS IN THE DOW VS. NASDAQ 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Graphic  is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are blue days for blue chip owners, but they're great days
if your money is in small technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Last week was a bad one for the Dow Jones industrial average,
the index that has long been identified with blue chip stocks.
</P>
<P>
   But the technology-saturated Nasdaq composite index had its best
week ever relative to the Dow. The Nasdaq rose 4.2 percent last
week to yet another closing high, with gains in every trading
session, while the Dow fell 4 percent as it declined each day.
</P>
<P>
   That outperformance _ with the Nasdaq doing 8.2 percentage
points better than the Dow _ far exceeded the Nasdaq's previous
record for outperformance over a week. That margin, 4.8 percentage
points, was set in the week ended Nov. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's divergence reflects continued speculation in small
technology stocks at a time when rising interest rates have hurt
many stocks _ including the bigger, bluer-chip technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Intel and Microsoft, the Nasdaq-listed technology
issues that were added to the Dow's 30 component stocks last year,
were among the 23 Dow stocks that lost ground last week. And the
other two most-active Nasdaq stocks last week, MCI WorldCom and
Dell Computer, also lost ground. Together, those four stocks
account for 20 percent of the Nasdaq composite index, but their
decline did not stop that index from having a strong week.
</P>
<P>
   The latest speculation in small technology stocks extends beyond
Internet issues, but it is concentrated on companies that are often
small and unprofitable.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing new in the Nasdaq's soaring, of course; it has
doubled over the past 13 months. But the fact that smaller stocks
are leading the way is a bit of a change.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2,000 _ an index that includes the stocks that rank
from 1,001 to 3,000 in market capitalization in the United States
and is the most widely followed index of small stocks _ rose 5.2
percent last week, better than the Nasdaq, which is dominated by
large technology stocks. Compare that to 1999, when the Nasdaq
composite rose more than 80 percent for the year, while the Russell
was up less than 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, huge margins of outperformance by Nasdaq over the
Dow have usually _ but not always _ come at a time when the
momentum of the Nasdaq composite was likely to continue. As
calculated by Bloomberg Financial Markets and going back to the
Nasdaq's creation in 1971, of the 10 previous cases when the Nasdaq
composite outperformed the Dow by at least four percentage points
during a week, on eight occasions the Nasdaq composite outperformed
the Dow over the subsequent four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more important, the Nasdaq composite registered gains in
seven of those eight cases.
</P>
<P>
   The most notable exception came slightly less than a year ago.
In the week ended Jan. 29, 1999, the Nasdaq leaped 7.1 percent,
vastly outperforming the Dow, which gained 2.6 percent. Over the
next four weeks, though, the Dow slipped only a bit while the
Nasdaq fell 8.1 percent. Technology stocks, which had led the move
up, also led the move down.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the most recent big outperformance for the
Nasdaq over the Dow, prior to last week _ the week of Nov. 5, noted
above, when the Nasdaq rose 4.6 percent and the Dow slipped a bit _
served as a signal that the current Nasdaq surge was under way. It
was the third week in a row that the Nasdaq rose at least 3
percent, and it did not have a week with a gain of less than 2
percent for the rest of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   A drop of 4.6 percent occurred in the first week of this year,
but the Nasdaq has more than made up for that decline by rising
more than 4 percent in each of the two subsequent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   All told, since Oct. 15 _ a period of 14 weeks _ the Nasdaq
composite has risen 55 percent, while the Dow has gained 12 percent
and the Russell 2,000 is up 29 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
