u f BC-PATENTS-COLUMN-NYT     01-23 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNING THE FAMILY CAR INTO THE FAMILY SNOWPLOW
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By SABRA CHARTRAND   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Snow fell on much of the Northeast last week, sending homeowners
and merchants outside to clear off sidewalks and cars. Municipal
plows took care of most town and city streets, but private
residents once again were stuck shoveling the drifts with those
bulky shovels. Anyone with a long driveway or large parking area
surely dreads that cold, back-wrenching labor.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Nugent looked around his home for a tool that might make
clearing snow easier, and realized the most powerful engine he
owned was idle during snowplowing: his car. Working with a used
lawn-tractor plow blade bought at a charity bazaar and two plow
arms that were made for him, Nugent designed a snow plow blade that
can turn a mid-size car into a plow.
</P>
<P>
   His blade is half as tall and half as wide as standard plows,
attaches to the front end of a car, and can be folded up and stored
like a bicycle. His model weighs about 40 pounds, and he says it
easily attaches and detaches to a car chassis.
</P>
<P>
   But Nugent admits previous designs for homeowner plows have been
unpopular because Americans are reluctant to view their cars as
workhorses.
</P>
<P>
   ``U.S. consumers learn from childhood to think of cars as status
badge, rocket ship, music room, anything but work tool,'' he wrote
in his patent. ``Owners felt little demand for a plow to mount on
the family car because they instinctively recoiled from heavy
hardware suggesting body damage.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he said, there is a limited time in winter when most car
owners might regret that attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``In most parts of the world where snow accumulates, the
homeowner's need for plowing ranges from near zero to merely a few
hours per year,'' he wrote. ``Only in winter, only on storm days,
only during or after storms of a certain accumulated snow depth and
density, and even on those rare occasions, driveway plowing is only
required if you really need to drive out soon into a plowed
street.''
</P>
<P>
   But Nugent says he found that those who really need to drive
must use car snow plows modeled on industrial plows _ heavy, with
hydraulic lifts, which can be hard for a passenger car to handle on
slippery surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   Nugent, 73, of Wilton, Conn., designed a plow blade for his car
that is five millimeters thick, made of steel and can be attached
to the pre-existing tabs on the chassis, called ears, which are
normally used for tying a car down during shipping. Nugent
envisions a person attaching the blade in about three minutes and
says it can be done without damaging the car.
</P>
<P>
   The blade does not lift off the ground when the car is driving
in reverse. A person ``merely drives and drags,'' Nugent said. He
hopes to license his invention, which received patent 6,009,642.
</P>
<P>
   In-Flight Evacuation, Parachute Included
</P>
<P>
   How many people have ever wondered if they could bring their own
parachute on a commercial flight in case of emergency? Neil and
Cleveland Nance have won a patent for an in-flight evacuation
system that takes care of that concern, and adds a survival kit as
a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   The Nances have invented a system that would eject passengers
from a plane in peril during flight. In their design, passenger
seats rotate 180 degrees to face backward and then glide toward the
rear of the plane, where large doors open to allow the people in
their seats to be ejected. The patent does not address the issue of
cabin pressure in an airliner, which might change drastically if
large doors were opened during an emergency, depending on the
altitude.
</P>
<P>
   Just before being expelled, the bottom part of the seat would
detach and drop into the plane's cargo area. The passenger would
float into the air strapped to the backrest portion of the seat,
from which a parachute would emerge as the passenger leaves the
rear of the plane. In addition to housing the parachute, the
backrest also carries a survival kit with a first aid pouch,
floatation device and safety lights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The passengers will slowly descend to earth,'' the Nances
wrote in their patent. ``After landing, the survival kit will be
used until rescuers arrive.'' The system was given patent
5,979,829.
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the World Wide Web at www.uspto.gov or
may be ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the
Patent and Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
