<HEADLINE>
EARMARK STANLEY PARK SCHNITZEL FOR YOUR NEXT DINNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've heard and sympathized with the complaints from our
neighbors to the north:
</P>
<P>
   _The exchange rate between the U.S. and Canadian dollar has
limited the number of shopping excursions residents of Vancouver,
Moose Jaw and Kamloops can afford to make to Bellingham, Seattle or
Queets.
</P>
<P>
   _Terrorist threats frequently slow traffic across the border to
an escargot crawl.
</P>
<P>
   _And if disdain for Canadian coins were not bad enough among
U.S. shopkeepers, the bearers of said cash persist in calling their
dollar a ``looney.''
</P>
<P>
   But I didn't comprehend the magnitude of the problem before
spotting a recent clipping from a major Canadian newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ottawa _ Health Canada announced yesterday that it is widening
its investigation into puppy chews after 29 people across the
country suffered salmonella infection from dog treats made out of
pigs' ears.''
</P>
<P>
   Even during the depths of the Great Depression, or at the time
of sweeping Boeing layoffs or following the Great Seattle Fire, our
residents were never reduced to wrestling their dogs for pigs'
ears.
</P>
<P>
   Embarrassed Canadian authorities have attempted to mask the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Health Canada is telling Canadians to avoid handling the
pig's-ear treats with their hands, to wash their hands carefully
after giving the treats to their pets and to make sure that young
children and elderly people stay away from the products,'' the
newspaper article proclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   Nice try, Health Canada, but you're not fooling us.
</P>
<P>
   No where in the news reports does it mention an epidemic of
salmonella among cocker spaniels, Pekingese or great Danes.
Obviously, they are being shorted by their owners when the dog
treats are passed around.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Taco Bell chihuahua should be dispatched across the
northern border to issue an overdue command: ``OK, drop the pig's
ear!''
</P>
<P>
   But better times must be coming for our Canadian friends. When
that day dawns, they can return the dog chews to the rightful
owners and feast upon a vastly superior pork product.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Park Schnitzel
</P>
<P>
   6 thin-sliced, boneless pork chops
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 beaten egg
</P>
<P>
   Dry Italian bread crumbs (like Progresso)
</P>
<P>
   Olive or canola oil
</P>
<P>
   One by one, flatten the chops between two sheets of waxed paper.
I accomplish this with the dull end of a meat cleaver, but that may
be illegal in British Columbia. Whatever you use, whack the meat
until you have reduced the thickness by one-half, without tearing a
hole in the chop.
</P>
<P>
   Lay the chops out in a dish and sprinkle with 1 tablespoon of
lemon juice. Let sit for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Mix the beaten egg with the remaining half tablespoon of lemon
juice. Moisten both sides of the fillets in the egg mixture, then
coat with the bread crumbs, also on both sides. When you have
accomplished this, refrigerate the coated chops for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to eat, heat the oil in a large skillet and cook the
pork quickly on both sides, until the crust is crisp and golden
brown. Serve immediately to three guests, maybe with some fried
potatoes on the side.
</P>
<P>
   If the Taco Bell Chihuahua sends a CARE package to Canada, it
may include this casserole, which might be retitled:
</P>
<P>
   English Bay Enchiladas
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup diced onion
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cumin (divided)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt (divided)
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons chili powder (divided)
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup beef broth
</P>
<P>
   1 cup tomato sauce
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces small shrimp
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces surami (fake crab meat)
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup green onions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup chopped green chilies
</P>
<P>
   One cup minced celery
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 and one-half cups grated Cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 and one-half cups grated Monterey Jack cheese
</P>
<P>
   12 6-inch corn tortillas
</P>
<P>
   Toppings (see below)
</P>
<P>
   In a skillet heat the butter and oil. Add the onions, half
teaspoon cumin, half teaspoon salt and 3 teaspoons chili powder.
Cook 5 minutes over medium heat. Add the flour and cook another
minute, stirring with a wooden spoon. Add the chicken broth, beef
broth and tomato sauce and stir-cook until this muck thickens.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl combine the shrimp, shredded surami, green
onions, green chilies, celery, black pepper, half teaspoon cumin,
half teaspoon salt and 1 teaspoon of chili powder.
</P>
<P>
   Cover a greased, flat oven dish with a thin layer of the sauce.
Break the tortillas into large pieces and create a layer in the
oven dish. Top with one third of the shrimp mixture, more tortilla
pieces, one third of the shrimp, more tortillas, the last third of
the shrimp mixture, and a final layer of the tortillas.
</P>
<P>
   Over this whole mess pour the remaining sauce and top with the
grated Cheddar and jack cheeses.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in a 350-degree oven for 30 minutes, or until the dish is
bubbling. Remove from oven and DON'T DROP THAT ENCHILADA! Instead,
let this dish rest 5 minutes, then cut into 6 serving portions.
</P>
<P>
   If you want, you can pass around bowls of guacamole, sour cream,
sliced black olives and sliced jalapeno peppers and let your guests
choose their own toppings.
</P>
<P>
   But please, no pig's ears.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
