<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-23 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4019 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a BC-WHY-IOWA-SPI &LR;      01-23 1554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHY-IOWA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATES LOOKING FOR A HOME RUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ When he first ran for president in 1988, Al
Gore disdained the disproportionate influence of ``the small state
of Iowa'' in winnowing the field of White House contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Gore refused to put resources into organizing for the 2,142
precinct caucuses across Iowa. After early forays, he flew in just
once, picking Independence, Iowa, to explain why he was cutting
free of the state.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen years later, Gore is proclaiming his support for Monday
night's first-in-the-nation caucuses, and solidarity with Iowa's
family farmers, as he seeks to follow Bill Clinton into the Oval
Office.
</P>
<P>
   What is it about Iowa, which ranks 30th in population among the
50 states, a stable and somewhat old-fashioned place in a
fast-changing country, that causes national candidates to campaign
here for months? What gives it so much sway over how Americans
elect their president?
</P>
<P>
   In the Iowa-based movie ``Field of Dreams,'' the mantra was ``If
we build it, they will come,'' referring to a baseball field and
legendary players of the past.
</P>
<P>
   The new mantra is ``If we hold a caucus, they will come.'' Every
four years the candidates appear before bales of hay as if in a
batting cage. And if they can't get a home run _ the victory that
will propel an unknown politician onto the covers of Time and
Newsweek _ there is the scratch single of a third-place finish that
keeps a candidate in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa is the envy of other states in having an early, influential
voice in picking a president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is neither fair nor rational that a few select states
dictate the outcome of every presidential race,'' Sen. Slade
Gorton, R-Wash., said in October when introducing a bill to create
four regional primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa's caucuses first gained major notice in 1972, when after a
rules change they became the nation's first contest. That year,
long-shot liberal George McGovern beat expectations with a strong
second-place showing against Sen. Edmund Muskie, then the top-heavy
favorite for the Democratic nomination. McGovern went on to win the
nomination and lose in a landslide to Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, across Iowa, about 200,000 out of 1.76 million
registered voters will find their way to schools, churches, civic
buildings and homes for separate Republican and Democratic
caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans will hear talks for candidates and then vote their
preference by secret ballot. Democrats will have to publicly
declare their preference and master arcane rules of proportional
representation in electing precinct delegates.
</P>
<P>
   The caucuses have impacted the picking of presidents in several
important ways. These include:
</P>
<P>
   Retail politicking: Jimmy Carter's road to the White House began
at the home of Harry and Elaine Baxter, of Burlington, and other
guest rooms across Iowa. Caucus politics make candidates go after
voters in small groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to succeed, where you begin is in somebody's
living room,'' said ex-Sen. Bill Bradley, who has stumped the state
in an uphill race against Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Some candidates aren't willing to go through the ritual. Former
New York Gov. Mario Cuomo twice veered away from seeking the
presidency, with friends joking that he couldn't stand the thought
of trooping around farms in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Humbling the mighty: Favorites stumble in Iowa, a state that
refuses to be taken for granted. Ronald Reagan was upset by George
Bush in 1980 _ because Bush visited almost all of Iowa's 99
counties and Reagan didn't. Eight years later, as vice president,
Bush ran a distant third behind Bob Dole and Pat Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, D.C., pooh-bahs must adapt or expire. About 400
Iowans gathered in front of baseball bleachers in Ottumwa in 1988
to hear GOP candidates. Four of the candidates stood
self-importantly on the stage. Only the physically disabled Dole
climbed around the rickety bleachers to greet voters one on one.
</P>
<P>
   The Iowa caucuses have humiliated powerful senators.
Astronaut-turned-lawmaker John Glenn drew big crowds in 1984. He
ended up with just 3.5 percent of the Democrats' vote. Indian Sen.
Richard Lugar, touting his foreign policy expertise, was the choice
of just 2.5 percent of Iowa Republicans in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In this year's GOP race, veteran Utah senator Orrin Hatch is
going nowhere. He's not happy about it. ``I'm telling you I can
win, but I can't win if you Iowa students don't come out and vote
for me,' Hatch told aspiring chiropractors at Palmer College.
</P>
<P>
   Winnowing the field: Iowa can put a sometimes brutal end to
presidential aspirations, even before the first results are phoned
in to Des Moines on caucus night.
</P>
<P>
   The Iowa Republican Party, as a fund-raising device, conducts a
straw poll of candidates late in the summer before the caucuses.
Three GOP candidates who fared poorly _ Lamar Alexander, Dan Quayle
and Pat Buchanan _ have since dropped out of the contest. So has
Elizabeth Dole, who finished in third place.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm managed to tie Dole by packing the 1995 straw
poll with out-of-state supporters. In the actual caucuses, he
finished a dismal fifth and quit the race two days later.
</P>
<P>
   Still, candidates do recover from a loss in Iowa. Reagan came
back to overwhelm Bush in the New Hampshire primary, and was on his
way to the GOP nomination and the White House. Bush staged a
similar recovery in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Special constituencies: Farmers account for only about 100,000
of Iowa's 3 million people, but farming assumes almost mythic
importance at caucus time.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has staged 25 meetings with farmers and six farm visits
in an effort to prove that he cares about agriculture. Gore
imported a farmer from New Jersey, which Bradley represented in the
Senate for 18 years, to argue that he doesn't. Gore has talked
endlessly about working as a boy on his father's Tennessee farm,
and even demonstrated expertise in the field of bull semen.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates not only court the family farmer but tirelessly
pledge to defend Social Security and Medicare. Iowa has an aging
population: 16 percent of its citizens are 65 and older. The
American Association of Retired Persons has 360,000 members in
Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Christian conservatives are a major target for courtship by
Republican candidates. Iowa is home to sizeable anti-abortion and
home schooling movements.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the frustrations is that New Hampshire doesn't have a
large church community,'' said Gary Bauer, head of the Family
Research Council and a longshot GOP candidate.
</P>
<P>
   About 90,000 people are expected at the Republican caucuses. As
many as 35,000 will be activists in the pro-life and pro-family
movements. ``The conservatives will show up,'' said state Rep. Dave
Lord, a GOP legislator.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP front-runner, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, has come
courting and, in Lord's words: ``He has convinced some people but
not the majority of the Christian community.''
</P>
<P>
   With 97.9 percent of Iowa's work force employed, it is difficult
to get the state's residents fired up about the idea that America
is going to the dogs, a common theme in many election cycles.
</P>
<P>
   In Perry, northwest of Des Moines, the Iowa Beef Processors have
attracted out-of-state Hispanic workers at $8 an hour because
Iowans don't want to do the messy, dangerous work. More than 3,000
Bosnians have also settled in Iowa, largely to work in the
meatpacking industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is working,'' said Lord, who owns a car wash in
Perry. ``My nephew is trying to hire people; he can't, unless he
hires people away from other businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hawkeye State is, in some ways, not exactly reflective of
America. In an increasingly multiethnic America, its population is
more than 96 percent white.
</P>
<P>
   It is prosperous with unemployment at half the national average.
Des Moines is one of the major insurance industry centers of the
world. Agribusiness and manufacturing fuel an increasingly
diversified economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people have had to get out of farming. Fortunately, the
rest of the economy in Iowa is so good that they easily get jobs,''
said Dave Topel, dean of the college of agriculture at Iowa State
University.
</P>
<P>
   But Iowa faces problems. Its population is stagnant. Despite
high employment, median household income trails $3,000 behind the
national average. Opportunity-seeking young families leave the
state, often for the Pacific Northwest. For the first time in its
history, Iowa has more people over the age of 74 than under 5.
</P>
<P>
   One of the state's major employers _ the appliance maker Maytag
_ just announced that it may move corporate headquarters out of
Newton. In Maytag's words, the move is being considered so it can
``continue to attract the most-qualified personnel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need more Iowans, we need younger Iowans, we need
better-paid Iowans,'' Gov. Tom Vilsack said in his recent
state-of-the-state speech.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa is a far different chunk of America than the
technology-driven Northwest, or the increasingly multiethnic
California, or the fast-growing cities of the South and Sunbelt.
</P>
<P>
   But it is first. And Monday night, Iowans get first crack at
picking the first American president to be elected in the 21st
century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
