u i BC-US-CITIZENSHIP-$ADV24     01-23 0295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-CITIZENSHIP-$ADV24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOW CONGRESS GRANTS CITIZENSHIP
 &HT;    With US-ELIAN-$ADV24.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    For Use Mon., Jan. 24 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUE SCHULTZ 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This week, the U.S. Congress is expected to
consider a private bill waiving requirements for citizenship, or
granting permanent residency to 6-year-old Cuban rafter Elian
Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   In 1875, the U.S. Supreme Court declared immigration and
citizenship federal issues and Congress, in 1891, established a
federal agency to deal with them. But, citizenship has become as
much a legislative as bureaucratic issue. According to the
Immigration and Naturalization Service, between 1992 to 1997,
Congress granted citizenship to almost 30 immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   As for the process, little is written in stone. The Congress can
bypass many of the usual steps for passing a bill, and a senator
can filibuster ad nauseam to stop it. The usual steps are:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The private bill for citizenship is introduced in both the
House and in the Senate;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  It is then sent to committees and subcommittees in both
chambers;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The committees review the bills, make changes and send it back
to the floors for debate;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If the bills in both chambers are passed, then it goes to a
conference committee of representatives and senators to make final
changes and again must be approved by Congress;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If approved it is then sent to the president for his
signature.
</P>
<P>
   The most common waivers set aside the oath of office
requirements for children or immigrants with disabilities, or
exempt residency requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
