<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-23 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4028 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TIMEWARNER-AOL-MEDIA-     01-23 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMEWARNER-AOL-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME AND FORTUNE PLAY CATCH-UP ON AOL DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was around cocktail hour on the Sunday night before Time
Warner and America Online announced the big deal that Norman
Pearlstine, the editor in chief of Time Inc., heard the news.
</P>
<P>
   Pearlstine said he was first surprised, and then daunted by the
frustrating task of covering the news after he had just put all of
his magazines to bed. ``Fortune had closed 48 hours earlier and
Time had closed 24 hours earlier,'' he said last week. ``We were
left playing catch-up.''
</P>
<P>
   Catching up was only part of the problem. The coverage of the
deal by Time and Fortune would be the first test of how the
enormous new company would cover itself in its own pages. In the
end, Time and Fortune covered the deal _ a barely adolescent
new-media giant swallowing up their old-media parent company _ much
as in the punch line to that old joke about canoodling porcupines:
very carefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a a balancing act when you cover yourself,''
Pearlstine said. ``There's no perfect way around it. There's
conflict. There's potential for conflict. What did you know as a
journalist and what did you know as a business partner? In the end,
you just sit down and write in a way that does not violate
corporate confidences.''
</P>
<P>
   The crew of news weeklies mostly hewed to the AOL-as-winner
line, and emphasized AOL's chairman, Stephen Case, over Time
Warner's chairman, Gerald Levin.
</P>
<P>
   Newsweek, weighing in with 25 pages of coverage (compared with
Time's 15 pages), styled Case as a latter-day Charles Foster Kane,
a media titan for the next century. Its coverage included a solidly
skeptical essay about both companies' stock prices by the economic
correspondent Allan Sloan.
</P>
<P>
   In 10 pages of coverage, Business Week posed America Online as
the clear winner in the deal, and also criticized AOL stock as
volatile. Business Week used a mock magazine design brandishing the
letters AOL in the typeface of Time magazine's logo. U.S. News &AMP;
World Report and Newsweek, which is owned by Washington Post Co.,
both ran long profiles of Case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Levin is a smart guy and a good businessman,'' Mark Whitaker,
the editor of Newsweek, said. ``But his is the story of a skilled
corporate insider. Compare that to the former Pizza Hut salesman
who by his early 40s has taken a start-up company in 10 years to be
so powerful that it can buy the biggest media and entertainment
company in the world. That's a better profile for our readers,
frankly.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Time magazine featured Levin along with Case on its cover
and paired the two in a dual profile. Entertainment Weekly, another
publication of Time Inc., featured a caricature of Case as a macho
groom, Levin as a bride in drag and Ted Turner as a leering
bridesmaid. On its cover this week, Fortune features Bill Gates and
Case, in two separate stories for the issue that arrives on
newsstands Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Time's cover article, by Daniel Okrent _ who had been involved
in previous Time Inc. Internet forays and knew most of the players
in the deal on a first-name basis _ was an insider's account of the
deal, and was tough about the company's sorry performance in
developing an Internet strategy.
</P>
<P>
   In the dual profile, while largely praising Levin, Time also
pointed out his ``half a dozen spectacularly costly crashes,'' like
the now-defunct TV-Cable Week. And two columns, by Michael Kinsley
and Victor Navasky, examined the pros and cons of media
concentration, respectively. Newsweek went with just one view on
this subject, a critical one, by Jonathan Alter.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Shepard, the editor in chief of Business Week, which is
owned by McGraw-Hill, said that although he felt there was some
added pressure to feature Levin on the Time cover, Time's coverage
was fair. ``Look, they used the word `dinosaur' to refer to Time
Warner, so I don't think they can be accused of going easy on
themselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no lack of hand-wringing during the reporting
process. One Time staff member sent an e-mail to colleagues warning
them that the company's management would probably prefer the deal
to be referred to in print as a merger, not an acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no pressure from Time Warner to refer to it as one
thing or another,'' Pearlstine said. ``But if I said, `Look, here
are the arguments for why it's a merger, not a purchase,' there is
a risk that someone thinks I am laying down an edict.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortune's coverage painted AOL as the dominant partner in the
deal. It began with a two-page editor's note defending the ability
of Time Inc. magazines to report on the new landscape, pointing out
such recent examples as Sports Illustrated's interview with John
Rocker, the Atlanta Braves player, in which the pitcher painted
himself as a xenophobe; the Braves are owned by Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Carol J. Loomis wrote an article critical of the new company's
ability to earn any money for investors, saying that the market
capitalization on AOL Time Warner would have to reach $2.4 trillion
(from her estimate for the company currently, which is $290
billion) to give an annual return of 15 percent. She compared the
task to ``pushing a boulder up an Alp.''
</P>
<P>
   John Huey, Fortune's managing editor, said: ``I think we have
the hardest time covering it. Those two companies operate at the
white-hot center of what we care about as a magazine.'' But, he
added, more concern went into the reporting for a positive story
about Time Warner that the magazine ran in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Huey said he heard mention of the deal as he was flying from his
home in Georgia to work in New York that Monday morning. ``I
overheard two people on the airplane and they had heard it on the
radio,'' he said. ``So that's how plugged in I am.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-00 1706EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000123.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-23 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4029 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CARS-INTERNET-SALES-N     01-23 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-INTERNET-SALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTOBYTEL PLANS TO SELL CARS DIRECTLY OVER THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Autobytel.com, the Internet car-buying service,
plans to announce on Monday that it will act as a car broker by
selling cars directly over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement at the annual convention of car dealers here
comes on the heels of Friday's news that Amazon.com would get into
the online car-selling business by taking a 5 percent stake in
Greenlight.com, and is part of a broader scramble by Internet
companies to get into the mundane business of selling cars and car
parts.
</P>
<P>
   These Internet services are now handling virtually the entire
process of buying a car, from supplying detailed information about
available models and options to delivering the car to the
customer's doorstep. While the cars still come from dealerships'
lots, the Internet companies say that many of their customers do
not want anything to do with dealers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a large group of consumers out there that want a
dealerless transaction,'' said Mark W. Lorimer, chief executive of
Autobytel.com, which now refers about 45,000 customers a month to
dealers who sell them cars, and accounts for almost half of all
online car sales referrals. In the coming months, the company will
roll out its direct sales offerings nationwide, imitating smaller
direct Internet sellers like CarsDirect.com.
</P>
<P>
   Customers will also be able to go to Autobytel's Web site to
view a list of dealers' offerings, each with a set price. After
finding a car to buy, customers can finance it online and have the
new car dropped off at their homes. But the paperwork will show the
seller is a local car dealer. ``From the dealers' perspective,
we're outsourcing the closing for them at fixed costs'' ranging
from $150 to $300, said Lorimer.
</P>
<P>
   Other big dot-coms are moving toward click-and-buy car sales.
``We do know we have to evolve into the direct model,'' said
Lindsay A. Sparks, chief executive of Microsoft's CarPoint, which
currently refers car shoppers to local dealers to conclude deals.
Still, he predicted that in the near term, ``direct selling will
still be a small percentage of the overall consumer buying
experience,'' and that in the long term, there will be a wave of
consolidation in the Internet-selling arena.
</P>
<P>
   Dot-com companies have been offering a range of services for
dealers at the National Automobile Dealers Association convention
here _ not just those that allow buyers to steer clear of car
dealerships.
</P>
<P>
   High Technology Solutions Inc. is expected to announce Monday
that its Virtual Dealership software, designed to help dealers sell
more bug deflectors, ski racks, head lamps and running boards, will
soon be found in Ford dealers nationwide. Kiosks, which High
Technology Solutions places in dealerships, allow customers to
configure a car with an assortment of accessories. Accessories are
a $20 billion market, said Allan J. Camaisa, chairman and chief
executive of High Technology, and dot-coms are trying to bridge a
``digital divide between the dealers,'' automakers and the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The Cobalt Group, a Seattle-based company that got its start by
building Web sites for thousands of car dealers, is promoting its
MotorPlace.com, a network that lets dealers use the Internet to
trade new and used cars and replacement parts. Last week, Cobalt
announced a partnership with the auto-dealer trade group, which
represents 19,500 of the nation's 22,400 car dealerships.
</P>
<P>
   And CarStation.com is attempting to remake the collision repair
business, which ``has been mostly a phone and fax business'' until
now, Charles L. Moore, CarStation.com's president and founder,
said.
</P>
<P>
   Technology companies have begun to focus on car dealers for
several reasons: existing inefficiencies in the car-selling system;
the belief that car buyers hate going into car dealerships, and the
size of the overall industry. ``There's a massive opportunity
that's sitting there,'' said Sparks of CarPoint. ``It's a $1.3
trillion business.''
</P>
<P>
   Dealers have about $6 billion in auto parts sitting on shelves
nationwide, all waiting for just the right fender-bender.
Currently, said John W.P. Holt, co-chief executive of the Cobalt
Group, ``we can trade pork bellies but we can't trade parts.''
Holt's plan is to put parts inventories online so that a dealer in
need of a replacement muffler can quickly find one at another
dealership.
</P>
<P>
   Stoneage.com announced that it would use the Internet to
advertise old-fashioned ``tent sales'' of used cars, filling fields
with used-car inventory from a handful of local dealers in various
markets on designated weekends, its chief executive, Mark J.
Campbell, said.
</P>
<P>
   But some industry strategists are skeptical of these efforts,
particularly of the prospects of companies trying to sell cars over
the Internet. ``I don't know where the legs are on this online
buying service,'' said Mark R. Rikess, president of the Rikess
Group in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   And Lloyd G. Waterhouse, president of Reynolds &AMP; Reynolds, which
specializes in designing computer systems for auto retailing, said:
``Most of the dot-coms are really adding a veneer to an already
inefficient system. The category is already tremendously
overcrowded.''
</P>
<P>
   Car dealers are often willing to work with the Internet
companies as long as the online concerns do not bypass them to sell
cars.
</P>
<P>
   James A. Willingham, chairman of the National Automobile Dealers
Association, told dealers Saturday that the Internet is no
substitute for car dealers. ``It is a lot different than buying a
book or a VCR over the Internet,'' said Willingham, who has been a
Buick dealer in California for nearly 40 years. ``We are talking
about a titled piece of property and an average sales transaction
cost of $25,000.''
</P>
<P>
   But 75 percent of car dealers have their own Web sites, and many
have already signed up with companies like Priceline.com or
Autobytel.com that generate Internet sales leads.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is really something that every car dealer has to
be a part of,'' Bill Knauz, who runs Karl Knauz Motors in Lake
Bluff, Ill., said. Still, he also believes the Internet alone will
not sell any cars. ``That is really kind of a fallacy _ no matter
how much you can look at that boob tube,'' he said, ``it doesn't
allow you to put your hands on a car.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
