</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEBRUARY GOAL NOT REALISTIC IN TALKS WITH PALESTINIANS, ISRAELI
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israel and the Palestinians will intensify their
peace negotiations over the next few weeks, but it is growing
increasingly unlikely that they will reach a framework agreement by
the goal of mid-February, Israel's senior negotiator said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have to be realistic, it is difficult to reach this
date,'' Oded Eran, the negotiator, said in a breakfast meeting
Sunday morning with foreign journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Eran was acknowledging publicly what Israeli, Palestinian and
U.S. officials have been saying privately for weeks, and the way he
talked made it seem that he assumes the deadline will not be met.
This represents a real deflation of the hope of rapid progress that
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak voiced last fall.
</P>
<P>
   But Eran said he still believed that a full permanent peace
accord could be forged by September. That is the final deadline set
in the most recent interim peace accord, and the date by which
Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, has said he would make a
unilateral declaration of statehood if the talks were not
completed.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials announced on Saturday that Arafat, Barak
and President Clinton would meet next weekend in Davos,
Switzerland, at the worldwide economic meeting. Senior Israeli and
U.S. officials said the meeting was not confirmed. It would be the
first three-way meeting since the leaders got together in Oslo,
Norway, in November.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is not prepared to invite the parties to the
Washington area for the Camp David-style summit meeting that was
proposed in Oslo as a possibility for February, U.S. officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis and the Palestinians are too far apart on every
issue before them _ borders, Jewish settlements in the West Bank,
Jerusalem, refugees, security and water. There are no working
papers on any issue, a U.S. official said.
</P>
<P>
   All the same, the working presumption is that both the Israelis
and the Palestinians will use the Feb. 13 deadline as a catalyst to
redouble their efforts in the next 20 days. And it is possible that
American peace envoys will travel to the region to oversee
intensified talks, a U.S. official said _ but probably only if the
Israeli-Syrian negotiations, which were suspended last week, are
not reactivated.
</P>
<P>
   Eran said he felt that the Israeli-Palestinian talks were taking
place in the shadow of the Israeli-Syrian negotiations, which
inevitably divided the peacemaking attention of Barak and the U.S.
peace team. He said he had to fight Barak's attempts to raid his
negotiating teams to assemble committees to meet with the Syrians.
</P>
<P>
   Eran, who was Israel's ambassador to Jordan before he was
assigned to oversee the peace negotiations, said there was
``nothing sacred'' in the original Feb. 13 deadline for the
broad-brush framework agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is, can we bridge the gaps?'' he said. ``Now we are
on the 23rd of January. We have three weeks to ready an agreement,
if we stick to the original plan. If I have to be realistic, it is
difficult to reach this date. But we can reach the two accords,''
the framework and the comprehensive agreements, ``in the eight
months until September.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked, Eran said he was not concerned about Palestinian
unrest if the February deadline was not met. He said that Arafat
had never been keen about Barak's idea of aiming for a framework
agreement halfway through the final status negotiations. Arafat's
eyes, he said, have always been trained on the full final accord.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Palestinian official agreed that Arafat did not put too
much stock in the framework idea. But, he said, if the deadline was
broken, many Palestinians would see it as ``another Israeli promise
broken.''
</P>
<P>
   Eran himself said he could not imagine that a framework accord
would have any meaning unless it contained very specific details
about the division of territory, including the fate of Jerusalem
and the Jewish settlements in the West Bank.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In addition to overseeing the final peace talks, Eran is charged
with negotiating the plans for carrying out the most recent interim
agreement, signed in Sharm el-Sheik, Egypt, last September. With
surprising frankness, he said that the interim issues took too much
time and distracted negotiators from the more important permanent
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see the Palestinian side,'' he said. ``What if there is
no final status agreement? But if there is no final status, both
sides are looking at larger problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the unresolved interim issues are two more land transfers
and the opening of a northern safe passage route between Gaza and
the West Bank, to complement the southern route opened last fall.
</P>
<P>
   One land transfer _ involving 6.1 percent of the West Bank _ is
overdue, and Eran said that the Israelis would make a decision
about what land to return in the next couple of days. He said that
the Palestinians had submitted requests for territory that were
believed to contain a request for villages like Abu Dis, which
borders on Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Eran also said that Abu Dis, which some believe the Palestinians
are preparing to be the capital of their future state, would not be
included in the next Israeli transfer. Abu Dis is in an area under
Palestinian civilian control and Israeli military control, and it
presumably would be turned over to the Palestinians under a final
accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``It raises the whole conversation about Jerusalem prematurely
on the Israeli agenda, and I don't think it's useful from the
Palestinian point of view either,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eran said there was a ``growing understanding'' between the two
sides on the issues involved, and he characterized the talks as
frank. He said that the rhetorical posturing that is often the
public face of the negotiations _ the assertions that progress is
not being made or that starting positions cannot be altered _ did
not go on behind closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   Eran also said that one point of ``proximity'' was that both
sides agreed that an international agency ``or mechanism'' would
have to handle the Palestinian refugee issue, including
compensation. But there is no agreement on the more fundamental
question of whether Palestinian refugees have the right of return
to Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
