A4034 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-GERMANY-KOHL-NYT &LR;      01-23 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-KOHL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT THAT KOHL WOULD TELL DONORS' NAMES IS HOAX 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ The scandal surrounding secret payments to Germany's
Christian Democratic Union took a bizarre turn Sunday with a hoax
in which a statement was falsely issued in the name of former
Chancellor Helmut Kohl saying he would reveal the names of the
donors who gave him more than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Several German and international news agencies published the
statement before hastily retracting their dispatches when Eva
Christiansen, a spokeswoman for the Christian Democrats, announced
that it was false.
</P>
<P>
   The statement was supposedly sent by the Christian Democratic
Union's Bonn office. It said that Kohl was ready to provide the
names of the secret donors to a special committee of senior
politicians who would investigate whether favors had in fact been
bought but who would not initially publicly identify those
involved.
</P>
<P>
   One of the politicians was to be Johannes Rau, the German
president, and suspicions about the document began to emerge when a
spokeswoman for Rau said the president knew nothing of such a plan.
Later, Michael Roik, a spokesman for Kohl, said the statement was a
complete invention.
</P>
<P>
   Why the statement was issued, and by whom, remained a mystery.
But the confusion it provoked reflected the atmosphere of extreme
uncertainty that has taken hold of Germany as Kohl appears to toy
with the fate of his party.
</P>
<P>
   As long as the former chancellor continues to withhold the names
of those who made secret payments to his party during his time in
office, and continues to insist that his assurances of anonymity
are more important than the law, it seems inevitable that support
for the Christian Democrats will continue to crumble.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl has admitted taking over $1 million in secret payments, but
said he used the money solely for the good of the party and was
never bribed in the sense of selling a favor. He has refused to
comply with a law that says the source of any party donation of
over $10,500 must be revealed.
</P>
<P>
   His refusal has prompted the wildest speculation about the
identity of the donors. International Jewish groups, the French
government, arms dealers, real-estate magnates and others have been
mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   So has the possibility that the donors do not exist at all and
that the story is a cover for kickbacks for various business deals
that might have been illegally held in overseas bank accounts
during the 16 years that Kohl was chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   Among the transactions being investigated are a tank sale to
Saudi Arabia in 1991 and the sale of the East German Leuna refinery
to Elf Aquitaine of France in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Roik on Sunday described as ``pure character assassination'' a
report based on unnamed sources carried by French and German
television saying that former President Francois Mitterrand of
France had provided money for Kohl's party in connection with the
refinery sale in the interests of European political stability.
</P>
<P>
   A long-awaited audit by Ernst &AMP; Young, the accounting firm, of
Christian Democratic finances under Kohl, is due to be published on
Monday and is expected to provide more precise details on the
amount of money illegally obtained by the party.
</P>
</TEXT>
