<HEADER>
A4035 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-JACKSON-MUSIC-REVIEW-     01-23 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODERATION IN ALL THINGS, ESPECIALLY COUNTRY MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ANN POWERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Boy, y'all are lively here tonight,'' said Alan
Jackson to the whooping crowd at Irving Plaza on Wednesday. The
Manhattan club is hardly a sawdust-floor honky-tonk, but it is a
long way from the coliseums and Las Vegas showrooms this
42-year-old country star normally fills.
</P>
<P>
   His comments to the thrilled audience seemed genuine. But it was
also part of a mystique that has allowed Jackson to keep topping
the country charts.
</P>
<P>
   Since he emerged as part of the country renaissance of 1989,
Jackson has acted as Nashville's conscience, proving that
well-written traditional songs can still have wide appeal. While
Garth Brooks turned himself into an action figure, and Shania Twain
offered up her midriff, the laconic Jackson had hits like ``Don't
Rock the Jukebox'' and ``Gone Country,'' based in country's
fundamental language of heartache and hell raising.
</P>
<P>
   Moderation, a quality he amply demonstrated at Irving Plaza, has
allowed Jackson to stay on top. His fellow torch-bearers, Dwight
Yoakam and Randy Travis, have paid commercially for being too arty
or schmaltzy. Jackson, conversely, has made an art of being the
strong, silent type. He's injected wry humor into songs like
``She's Got the Rhythm (and I've Got the Blues),'' written with
Travis, and stood up for populism with ``Little Man.'' But he uses
a light touch on those familiar tropes, right down to the reserved
melodies that let him keep his moist bass-baritone vocals mellow.
</P>
<P>
   A long acoustic set in the middle of his show allowed Jackson to
tell stories linking his hits together. His shy monologues weren't
always audible above the fans' screams, but what did come through
was a tale of success that has come from knowing one's place and
being proud of it. He told of how he had hoped that one song would
be recorded by Whitney Houston, but that its humble lyrics about
domestic life didn't suit the glamorous soul queen; the good old
girl Faith Hill had a smash hit with it instead.
</P>
<P>
   This sense of artistic propriety was reflected throughout the
night as Jackson moved through his own songs and some covers from
his new album, ``Under the Influence'' (Arista Nashville), a
tribute to his honky-tonk forebears. ``Pop a Top,'' a 1967 hit for
Jim Ed Brown, extols the lowly pleasures of canned beer. ``The
Blues Man'' by Hank Williams Jr. showed a tender side of that
notorious party guy. Jackson's own 1996 hit, ``Everything I Love,''
ruefully listed the earthiest of vices: cigarettes, Jack Daniels
and coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Even as he maintained such orthodoxies, however, Jackson slipped
in a bit of rock 'n' roll spirit. Danny Groah's guitar riff during
``Don't Rock the Jukebox'' recalled the legendary genre-crosser
Gram Parsons. And the band played both ``Summertime Blues'' and
``Mercury Blues,'' rock hits for other artists. Within these
moments Jackson stayed cool, able to step outside his norm for a
moment because he clearly knew how to get back in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-00 1741EST &QL; 
