<HEADER>
A4040 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYT     01-23 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS FACES POTENTIAL `DO-LITTLE' YEAR  
 HELMS IN ENEMY TERRITORY  
 STATES GET DOMESTIC-TERRORISM SQUADS  
 TEEN MATERNITY: LOWER BUT STILL HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: The South)  (mk) 
 By CARL HULSE and SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As lawmakers return to the Capitol for a millennial
election-year session, the bar is being set low in terms of
anticipated accomplishments. With control of Congress at stake,
members of both parties predict the year will be notable more for
political posturing than productivity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't look for a lot,'' said Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La.,
who called it unrealistic to expect Congress to launch any
far-reaching legislative initiatives this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it will be a record-breaking year,'' agreed Rep.
Charles Canady, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   GOP leaders are playing the expectations game, laying out a
modest agenda centered on a plan to eliminate a major portion of
the national debt by 2015 and adopting a compromise patients' bill
of rights. Any success beyond those goals could then be celebrated
as icing on the cake.
</P>
<P>
   But the congressional agenda is not entirely under their
control. A nasty feud is developing over a decision by Republican
leaders in the House to bypass a Catholic candidate for chaplain,
sparking charges of religious bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   Votes on a China trade pact promise to be contentious, as could
an early debate over conferring citizenship on Elian Gonzalez, the
Cuban boy at the center of an international custody fight. And
congressional Democrats angling for campaign fodder will try to
thwart the GOP at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has his own priorities, unveiling a series of
costly health and education proposals in an effort to force
Republicans into going along or being seen as opposing popular
programs.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart believes they will ultimately
choose the former. `If you look at the issues that the president is
going to put forward, we're very confident that this will be a year
of legislative accomplishment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   SENATOR BITES BIG APPLE
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't have quite the historic weight of Nixon's trip to
China, but it's noteworthy just the same: Jesse Helms visited New
York.
</P>
<P>
   OK, the headlines focused on Helms' unprecedented address before
the U.N. Security Council, an interesting development given the
North Carolina senator's long-standing criticism of the United
Nations. He loosened up his audience by noting that the U.N.
linguists faced a daunting task.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope you have a translator here who can speak Southern,
someone who can translate words like `y'all' and `I do declare,'''
he said to laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Helms, a Republican, has not been shy about using New York City
as a convenient foil over the years in his various speeches about
the moral decay of America. Whether it's gay activists, performance
artists, union leaders or liberal politicians, Helms has talked
about some of the city's denizens with something less than
affection.
</P>
<P>
   Given his U.N. trip, could a visit to the television set of
David Letterman be next?
</P>
<P>
   PLANNING FOR THE WORST
</P>
<P>
   With the creation of 17 new rapid response teams to contend with
weapons of mass destruction used on U.S. soil, the Pentagon is
extending its line of defense against domestic terrorism to a
broader section of the South.
</P>
<P>
   Florida, Louisiana, South Carolina, Virginia, Kentucky and
Arkansas are among states getting the $2 million, 22-member squads
of specially trained, active-duty National Guard personnel. When
the first 10 teams were deployed last year, Georgia was the only
Southern state to serve as a base for one.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said the teams will be on call to help local
emergency workers identify the chemical, biological or nuclear
agent used in any attack and how to contend with it, not treat the
victims.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., said such preparation was warranted
considering ``there is no question that the threat of an attack on
American soil by terrorist, criminal, rogue or military groups is
very real.''
</P>
<P>
   Guard officials will select the communities that will host the
teams.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS HAVING KIDS
</P>
<P>
   Though teen birth rates are declining nationwide, Southern
states continue to record high levels of maternity among young
women ages 15 to 19.
</P>
<P>
   Exceeding the 1997 national average of 52 births per 1,000 teens
of that age were Mississippi at 74, Alabama and Georgia at 67,
Louisiana at 66, North and South Carolina at 61 and Florida at 58.
</P>
<P>
   All, however, recorded drops from previous levels.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the reductions stemmed from a lower proportion of
teens having sex and an increase in the use of contraception. The
rate of abortion also decreased.
</P>
<P>
   States with the lowest rates were Vermont at 27 births per 1,000
and New Hampshire at 29, according to Child Trends, the group that
compiled the report.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse and Sean Loughlin are in the Washington bureau of
the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-00 1752EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
