<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-23 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4041 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CLINTON-SPEECHWRITER-     01-23 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SPEECHWRITER-ART-635&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING THE WORDS OF THE PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Terry Edmonds is the keeper of the disk.
</P>
<P>
   With just days to go before President Clinton delivers the final
State of the Union speech of his presidency, there is a mad
scramble among aides and outsiders to insert a paragraph, or just a
sentence, or even a fleeting phrase, into the final text.
</P>
<P>
   As the president's chief speechwriter, Edmonds is the guardian
of the computer disk containing the speech's latest draft, and the
coordinator of the policy proposals, accolades, reflections and
humorous asides that will pop up on Thursday night on Clinton's
TelePrompTer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are being lobbied, assaulted, bombarded, beseeched from all
quarters _ from within the White House, from the agencies, even
from outside,'' Edmonds said. ``Some little old lady called up from
somewhere and said, `How can I get something in the State of the
Union?' We were like, `Wow, how did you get our number?'''
</P>
<P>
   This is to be Clinton's last State of the Union speech, and
unlike the previous two, which were delivered in moments of
political crisis, it comes at a time when political eyes are
shifting toward the election _ all part of the challenge for
Edmonds, who became director of speechwriting in August 1999,
overseeing a staff of five speechwriters handling domestic policy.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a touch of personal history at work here, too.
</P>
<P>
   As the only speechwriter in this White House who is
African-American _ and as far as administration officials know, the
first black person ever to fill the role _ he says he is ``aware of
the historic significance of what I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was amazing to me to discover I was the first
African-American speechwriter to work in the White House,'' he
said. ``I hope I'm not the last. But once you get in there and once
you are inundated by the pace and demands of the job, historic
significances take a back seat to immediate actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds, 49, moved from public relations work in 1993 to become
speechwriter for Donna Shalala, the secretary of the Department of
Health and Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   At first, he tried to mimic the cadences of the Rev. Martin
Luther King Jr. in Shalala's speeches. It was a less than perfect
fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I quickly learned that she was not Martin Luther King,''
Edmonds said. ``You really have to write to the style of the person
who you're writing for.''
</P>
<P>
   He moved to the White House in 1995 after drafting a
well-received sample speech for the president's advisers. From an
office in the Old Executive Office Building, Edmonds has relished
the chance to handle Clinton's speeches on race relations.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote Clinton's speech on the day of the Million Man March
and he wrote the stirring eulogy that Clinton delivered for former
Rep. Barbara Jordan of Texas. Edmonds spent much of last year with
Harvard professor Christopher Edley ghost-writing a book on race
that Clinton intends to publish.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds does not have to do any research to describe vividly the
many people left behind in this booming economy. He grew up in a
housing project in Baltimore. He never knew his father. He spent
time in a foster home. He arrived home one day to see the family's
possessions tossed out on the curb after an eviction. ``There were
some rough times as we were growing up,'' he says simply.
</P>
<P>
   To write a president's words well, one must believe in the
leader. Edmonds does. During the heat of impeachment, he wrote a
letter to Essence magazine sticking up for his embattled boss.
Edmonds, who has a college-age daughter, recounted how the
president called him in the hospital in 1998 when his wife,
Antoinette, had suffered a massive stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my family, when my country were in our darkest hours,
Bill Clinton was there for us,'' he wrote. ``I, for one, think that
counts for something.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Without any slight intended toward the president, Edmonds does
acknowledge that the times of awe-inspiring oratory from public
leaders may have passed. One cause, Edmonds said, is the sheer
number of speeches presidents give. Harry S. Truman gave 88
speeches in 1949. In 1997, according to data compiled by Edmonds,
Clinton gave 545 speeches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think that President Clinton, when he's on, can give a
great speech, but he has to speak so much on so many different
issues that don't lend themselves to high oratory,'' Edmonds said.
``Releasing the Thanksgiving Day turkey is not going to sound like
Martin Luther King.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds would not discuss any of the announcements Clinton will
make this week. But he did offer this much about the contents of
that disk. The speech will be long.
</P>
<P>
   But it will not be a farewell address. ``He is an activist
president and has vowed to be one until his last day,'' Edmonds
said.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds refuses to claim credit for any lines, describing the
process as a collaborative one that ultimately hinges on what
flashes through Clinton's mind at whatever podium he is standing
at.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton is very prone to veer from the written
script,'' Edmonds said. ``If you're sitting there waiting for him
to give you your words back, you may be waiting a very long time.
He almost invariably improvises. And I'm not proud to admit that he
usually makes the speeches better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
