<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Jan. 24, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, over a quarter-inch of ice glazed portions of
interior North Carolina as a low-pressure system crossed the
southeastern states.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, wintry precipitation will once again threaten
sections of the interior Southeast as another low forms along a
front off the Atlantic coast. The circulation around the low will
draw moisture inland, causing rain near the southeast seaboard.
Meanwhile, breezes from the northeast directing chilly air into the
interior Carolinas will set the stage for patchy freezing rain and
light snow to occur.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms will affect much of Florida on Monday
as a cold front crossing the peninsula lifts humid air. A few of
the showers will produce tropical downpours, especially during the
afternoon when a potent jet-stream disturbance passing overhead
augments the ascent of the humid air.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, chilly air gathering moisture upon crossing the Great
Lakes will cause narrow bands of snow to form in northern Michigan
and portions of upstate New York. A growing ice pack on Lake Erie,
however, will limit the intensity of snow downwind of its shores.
</P>
<P>
   A rich supply of Pacific moisture will continue to fuel numerous
showers along the West Coast. The heaviest rain will impact central
and northern California where, locally, rainfall totals could
exceed 3 inches. As the moist air impacts the interior mountains,
it will ascend and cool, bringing locally heavy snow to the
southern Cascades. Heavy snow will also fall along many of the
west-facing slopes of the northern Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: Arctic Sunrise
</P>
<P>
   At Barrow, Alaska, the relentless darkness of the arctic night
has ended. The sun rose at 1:13 p.m. Sunday, after having been
below the horizon since November 18. It set 53 minutes later. Now
the amount of possible sunshine increases at least nine minutes
each day. By May 10, the nation's northernmost town will be in
constant sunshine until late August. This arctic sunrise is the
beginning of a slow steady process that modifies bitter air masses.
As the rest of the United States reaches a midwinter ebb, the
brightening Barrow skies are the first true sign of spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-00 1755EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
