<HEADLINE>
NEWSWEEK DROPS AN EXCERPT OF GORE BOOK  
 MS. IS READY TO GIVE EX-GLOBE COLUMNIST ANOTHER CHANCE  
 DREAMWORKS LOOKS FOR NEXT SEASON'S HIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   An excerpt from a new biography of Al Gore was scheduled to run
in Newsweek in the issue dated Jan. 24, which arrived on newsstands
last week. But as the presidential primaries neared, the day before
closing the issue, Newsweek editors pulled the excerpt, which
featured new allegations of marijuana use by Gore 2 1/2 decades
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The book, ``Inventing Al Gore: A Biography,'' by William Turque,
a Newsweek political correspondent in Washington, is to be
published by Houghton Mifflin in March.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to postpone the article was made by Richard M.
Smith, the chairman and editor in chief of the magazine, which is
owned by the Washington Post Co., and Mark Whitaker, the magazine's
editor. Whitaker said that the postponement had nothing to do with
political schedules and that he would not comment on internal
editorial decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   The excerpt, which magazine staff members said Whitaker now
plans to run closer to the book's publication date in March,
includes more contextual material about the 1988 campaign, during
which Gore admitted some marijuana use.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Houghton Mifflin, Laurie Glaser, declined to
discuss the contents of the book. Newsweek has already run one
excerpt from Turque's book, in the Dec. 6 issue.
</P>
<P>
   A Gore campaign spokesman, Chris Lehane, said: ``As to the book,
the issue is old news in the sense that Al Gore raised the question
himself in 1987. He's been very clear that he has never used the
drug in question since entering public office.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Is Ready to Give Ex-Globe Columnist Another Chance
</P>
<P>
   If Mike Barnicle, the former Boston Globe columnist who admitted
recycling stories he heard from others without checking to make
sure that they were actually true, can get a job at a decent
newspaper like The New York Daily News, why shouldn't Patricia
Smith, his former colleague who admitted that she fabricated
characters and quotes, get a nice respectable job, too?
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Ms. magazine said Ms. Smith had joined the magazine
as a columnist. Her first column, called ``Fools in Love,'' will
appear in the February/March issue and concerns a visit to her
22-year-old son in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Ann Gillespie, the magazine's editor in chief, said that
she had long been an admirer of Ms. Smith's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The disclosure that she had fabricated information shocked me,
and saddened me at the time,'' Ms. Gillespie said. Then she read an
essay Ms. Smith wrote in the September 1999 issue of Essence
magazine. ``That piece made me sit up and say, `Wow, this is a
voice that needs to be back out there.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gillespie said Ms. Smith had served her time in the court of
public opinion. ``I don't know anybody who walks on water,'' Ms.
Gillespie said. ``We've all had something. But I don't think she
should have been banished to Coventry for the rest of her life.
She's a great writer.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. could use the help. The magazine _ which is now owned by
Liberty Media for Women, a group of roughly a dozen women that was
cobbled together by Gloria Steinem from her network of feminist
movers and shakers _ has seen its circulation drop from 540,000 in
1989 to about 220,000. The magazine's circulation is not audited.
</P>
<P>
   There is no advertising revenue because in 1990 the magazine
adopted a no-advertising policy, a plan taken up by Ms. Steinem for
its economic sense and because it assured editorial independence.
So the magazine depends on newsstand sales _ at $5.95 an issue _
and subscriptions for its revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gillespie said that she was ``delighted'' to have Ms. Smith
on staff and that she had no qualms about the writer's editorial
integrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't even occur to me that there would be any issue,''
she said. ``And by the way, we also do fact-checking, so _ duh _ I
don't think it can be a problem.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith did not respond to a request for an interview.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks Looks for Next Season's Hit
</P>
<P>
   It has been a rough television season for DreamWorks. First came
the cancellation of the studio's comedy ``It's Like You Know.''
Then, last week, Michael J. Fox announced his departure from the
studio's stalwart hit on ABC, ``Spin City,'' leaving the show with
a shaky future.
</P>
<P>
   Now DreamWorks heads into television's development season in
serious need of a new breakthrough hit. Fortunately, it had ramped
up its series development this season and has a number of projects
it hopes can bear some fast ratings fruit _ in one case, the studio
is counting on its biggest creative name, Steven Spielberg, to ride
to the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   Still, DreamWorks would clearly be at a disadvantage if it is
forced to go into a new season without an established hit. ``It's
always tough when your flagship show is affected,'' said Garth
Ancier, the president of NBC Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ABC executives said they will look closely at how the ``Spin
City'' creator, Gary David Goldberg, proposes keeping the show
running. But realistically, one ABC executive said, without Fox,
``Spin City'' may be considered as only equal to the crop of comedy
pilots the network looks at this spring. And Dan McDermott, who
heads the television division for DreamWorks, conceded: ``Everybody
kind of looked at it as Mike's show. I think you'd have to say its
future is questionable.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, one of the most popular stars in television, decided that
his battle with Parkinson's disease had become too much of a
challenge to continue weekly series work after this season. ``Spin
City,'' which would have been a certainty to go to a fifth season
and likely more, now may end its run at four.
</P>
<P>
   That will supply DreamWorks with 100 episodes, just enough for
an effective sale in syndication. The show has already been sold to
stations around the country for a price estimated at about $2
million an episode. But a sale of 100 episodes of ``Spin City''
will bring in about $100 million less than one of 150 episodes,
often the number that long-running hits reach.
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks has one other show on the air, and two ready to go,
all at NBC. The existing show, ``Freaks and Geeks,'' has been among
the season's most praised new series, but its ratings have been
modest at best. One upcoming show, ``The Others,'' is a drama with
supernatural overtones. Another is a new comedy from Goldberg,
``Battery Park.''
</P>
<P>
   The next big hope for DreamWorks is a series set for the fall on
NBC, ``Semper Fi,'' a big-budget drama about life in the Marine
Corps, to be produced by Spielberg.
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks also has a comedy for ABC, a co-production with the
Disney studio Touchstone. The unnamed project, a quirky, comic look
at police work, will star Dennis Leary and will be written by Peter
Tolan, who also wrote the film ``Analyze This.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always pressure in this job,'' McDermott said. ``I'd
like to have one more show headed toward syndication in the next
six to 12 months.''
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
