<DOCNO> NYT20000123.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-23 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4057 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE24-COX     01-23 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke belt-tightening foreseen
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A Wall Street analyst predicted Sunday that Coca-Cola
would announce this week $700 million in charges against earnings
to cover the cost of layoffs and underperforming investments in
Russia and India.
</P>
<P>
   Sanford Bernstein analyst Bill Pecoriello said about $150
million of that amount would be charged in this year's first
quarter for severance benefit costs associated with at least 2,000
job cuts around the globe. He believes about 600 of those cuts will
be in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The company had no comment. It is not planning to talk about
possible job cuts and fourth quarter earnings until Wednesday. But
Pecoriello and some other analysts spent the weekend crunching
numbers in anticipation of the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Pecoriello said the other $550 million in one-time charges
against earnings would come from reducing the value of
underperforming bottling assets in Russia and India, as well as
from smaller balance sheet items. Those charges will go against
last year's fourth-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this happens at Coke, it's because every company
occasionally needs a belt-tightening,'' said John Sicher, editor
and publisher of Beverage Digest. ``We saw it with IBM a few years
ago. Although difficult, trimming down is often the right
prescription for future health.''
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the one-time charges, representing about $300
million to $400 million, will be for the company's Russian
operations, where a devalued ruble and troubled economy have hurt
sales dramatically, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're clearly going to re-evaluate their investment in their
Russian bottling business,'' said Andrew Conway, an analyst with
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``The company will write down the value
of their investment because the future growth prospects are lower
than they originally thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Conway said case sales in Russia have dropped about 50 percent
compared with what they were 18 months ago. He estimated that the
company would reduce the value of its Russian assets by between
$300 million and $600 million.
</P>
<P>
   He also believes the severance costs from job cuts will
``easily'' amount to another $100 million to $200 million in
charges. He expects consolidation of sales and marketing offices in
parts of Europe and elsewhere, with some people in Atlanta being
sent abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts believe Coke's U.S. operation in Atlanta will
experience jobs cuts as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm interested in seeing where they cut people and why, and
its implications for future growth,'' Conway said. ``They need
people on the street to sell syrup. They need people in the field
to assess the demographic and market opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   The job cuts and writedowns indicate ``Coke is retrofitting the
business for the gradually improving global growth prospects,
instead of a period of powerful volume growth,'' Conway said.
</P>
<P>
   He and other analysts believe the company needs to communicate
clearly about its long-term growth prospects. In fact, several
analysts said they expect top company officials to fly to New York
late this week to talk with them.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the key decisions the company will announce this week
have been in the works for nearly a year, Conway said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Chairman M. Douglas Ivester initiated a ``complete
review of the entire global business system. ... Ivester started
this process about nine months ago. It just so happens (Doug) Daft
will carry it through.'' Daft, the company's current president,
will replace Ivester as chairman and chief executive officer in
April.
</P>
<P>
   That transition makes this a particularly good time for the
company to take restructuring charges. By announcing them now, Daft
could put the bad news behind him before he assumes the top spot in
April.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is cleanup time,'' said Manny Goldman, global beverage
analyst with Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
