<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-23 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4061 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NATIONAL-GUARD-SHORT-     01-23 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATIONAL-GUARD-SHORT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIZEN-SOLDIERS ARE INCREASINGLY CALLED TO SERVICE IN A DWINDLING
MILITARY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Va., Pa.)   (EDS: This is the abridged version of a special report that is the
first article in an occasional series on the National Guard. A
full-length version has moved as NATIONAL-GUARD)  
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Daniel L. Teafatiller, a rancher, sold all his
cattle, except his two prize bulls, which he asked his son-in-law
to look after while he is away. Patrick F. Martin, an account
manager for Microsoft, is trying not to think about the six-figure
stock bonus he will miss when he is gone. Ron De La Rosa, a lawyer
with his own practice down by the courthouse here, is scrambling to
try or settle as many cases as possible.
</P>
<P>
   De La Rosa and the others are citizen-soldiers, members of the
Texas National Guard who serve one weekend a month and two weeks
each summer _ unless a national crisis compels them to answer the
call to duty. That was always a possibility, they knew, but for
years, a remote one.
</P>
<P>
   Now the call has come. Only there is no war, no tornado, no riot
to quell. Instead, the Army has ordered them to set aside their
civilian lives, their jobs and their families to serve as
peacekeepers in a faraway place that few of them gave much thought
to a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   In February, about 700 men and women of the 49th Armored
Division _ the Lone Star Division _ are to board transport planes
and fly to Bosnia, not for a couple of weeks, but for nearly nine
months. On March 7, they will take command of the U.S. sector in
NATO's operation there, responsible for ensuring that Bosnia's
tenuous peace somehow endures.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has deployed guard and reserve units overseas
before; more than 265,000 guardsmen and reservists were called up
to support the Persian Gulf War in 1990 and 1991. But the 49th's
mission is something new. Not since the Korean War has a guard
division been put in charge of an overseas operation. And never
before has one commanded regular Army combat units.
</P>
<P>
   The 49th's deployment represents the culmination of a trend that
is transforming the nation's military, while roiling cities and
towns across America, with consequences that the Pentagon has only
now begun to assess.
</P>
<P>
   For De La Rosa, 42, a staff sergeant in the 49th's aviation
brigade, it has turned his life upside down.
</P>
<P>
   He is eager to serve _ ``I'll go wherever they need me,'' he
said _ but the deployment means leaving behind his elderly parents
and his small law office on San Antonio Street. He is the only
lawyer in his practice but hopes to keep it running, relying on his
office manager and wife, Olga, to hold on to clients.
</P>
<P>
   With overseas military operations proliferating and the armed
services having shrunk by a third since the Cold War, the Pentagon
has been forced to rely more heavily on the 870,000 men and women
in the Guard and Reserves to ease the strain. In the Army today,
guard and reserve soldiers actually outnumber those in the regular
force, 564,000 to 479,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply could not undertake a sustained operation anywhere
in the world without the Guard and Reserves,'' Secretary of Defense
William Cohen said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Already, in the first four years of the Bosnian operation, more
Army reservists have been activated than during the entire Vietnam
War, though never in a single group as large as the 49th's. At
Incirlik Air Base in Turkey, a third of the pilots and crew members
patrolling the ``no flight'' zone over northern Iraq have belonged
to the Air Guard or Air Force Reserves. Guard and reserve F-16
pilots have bombed Iraqi targets.
</P>
<P>
   And there is no end in sight. A recent Pentagon study predicted
the demand for guard and reserve deployments ``is likely to remain
high over the next 15 to 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Army has now designated guard units from Virginia and
Pennsylvania for rotations in Bosnia into 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The increased reliance on the reservists, however, has come at a
cost.
</P>
<P>
   It has meant more money for training, equipment and pay. Citing
the Army's dependency on them, Cohen last month postponed a planned
reduction of 25,000 guard and reserve positions, a 4 percent cut
that would have saved $900 million over the next five years,
according to Army officials.
</P>
<P>
   The greater demand has also raised questions about whether
part-time units are ready to take on missions important to the
nation's security.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the biggest impact _ and the one that most worries
Pentagon officials _ is here at home.
</P>
<P>
   Deployments have forced the nation's so-called weekend warriors
to juggle their civilian lives and military service. Long tours
mean disrupting families and putting careers or college on hold.
</P>
<P>
   Spc. Meghan A. Wood, an administrative clerk in the public
affairs office of the 49th, joined the Guard in 1998 to earn
tuition for the University of Texas. She was about to enter her
senior year last fall; her degree will now have to wait.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. John R. Fitzgerald, an intelligence officer, is going to
Bosnia as a newlywed. He and his wife, Naima Mery, first planned to
marry in November, but he had to go to a three-week mission
rehearsal exercise at Fort Polk, La. So they squeezed in a ceremony
at the St. Louis Catholic Church here last week.
</P>
<P>
   Staff Sgt. Mary E. Manley, who works for MCI-Worldcom's office
in Richardson, Texas, is going to miss a wedding altogether: her
25-year-old daughter's.
</P>
<P>
   Deployments have forced employers to scramble to fill vacancies
created when reservists leave, often at a cost. By law, an employer
cannot dismiss someone called to active duty, but many reservists
face subtle and not-so-subtle retribution, as well as lost wages
and missed opportunities for promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Conflicts over jobs are the leading reason reservists quit,
according to Pentagon surveys, followed by separation from their
families.
</P>
<P>
   ``The repercussions are more severe than people think,'' said
Jerry Mendez, a major in the 49th who is an insurance manager in
San Antonio. ``People are going to have to choose'' between
military service and family. ``Guess what they're going to chose.
That's why the Guard is losing quality people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
