<DOCNO> NYT20000123.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-23 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4071 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TIMEWARNER-EMI-675&AMP;AD     01-23 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMEWARNER-EMI-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME WARNER TO BUY CONTROL OF EMI'S MUSIC OPERATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK with ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time Warner Inc. plans to acquire control of the music business
of EMI Group and merge it with Warner Music, creating what could
become the world's largest record company, officials close to the
negotiations said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which is expected to be announced Monday in London,
would shrink the oligopoly of music companies that dominate the
world business from five to four. And coming two weeks after Time
Warner agreed to be acquired by America Online, the music merger
would create a force to be reckoned with in the fledgling business
of distributing music on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly underscores the premise of the AOL-Time Warner
merger and adds more sustenance to that deal,'' Jill S. Krutick, an
analyst with Salomon Smith Barney, said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The merged music company, to be known as Warner EMI Music, would
sell about one out of four records in the United States and also
have a vast international presence. EMI, whose roster of artists
includes the Rolling Stones, the Spice Girls and Robbie Williams,
has been strongest in Europe and some other international markets
like Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner's Warner Music, which has acts that include Madonna,
Eric Clapton and Jewel, has been strongest in the United States.
But its market share has plummeted in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner and EMI Group would each own 50 percent of Warner
EMI Music. But Time Warner would have a slight majority on the
board of directors and ultimate control. To gain this control, Time
Warner will pay EMI shareholders 1 pound per share, or about $1.65,
for a total payment of about $1.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   EMI Group would continue as a company with its own stock trading
on the London Stock Exchange. Its operations would consist of its
50 percent interest in the new joint record venture, plus some
other business that include a stake in the music retailer HMV.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Ames, the chief executive of Warner Music, would be chief
executive of the new venture, which is to be based in New York. Ken
Berry, who heads EMI Records, would be chief operating officer. EMI
Group's chairman, Eric Nicoli, and Time Warner's president, Richard
Parsons, would be co-chairmen, the people close to the transaction
said.
</P>
<P>
   Talks about the merger have been under way since August, well
before the recent announcement of the $165 billion merger of Time
Warner and America Online. One person close to the negotiations
said America Online was not told of the EMI talks until after
America Online and Time Warner had reached their basic merger
agreement. But Steve Case, the chairman of America Online, signed
off on the music deal, which would make even more musical content
available for AOL to distribute over the Internet, this person
said.
</P>
<P>
   Simply combining the current sales of Warner Music and EMI
Records, the new company would have revenue of about $8 billion a
year. That would surpass the roughly $6 billion a year in sales of
the current industry leader, Seagram Co.'s Universal Music Group,
which itself became the leader through the 1998 acquisition of
Polygram. But some operations might be cut after the Warner
Music-EMI merger, people close to the deal said Sunday, so it is
possible that Seagram would remain the largest music company.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Warner is now No. 4 in terms of newly
released current album sales, and EMI is No. 5. The combined
company would be just behind Universal Music in the American
market, with a share of about 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Layoffs and a realignment of record labels can probably be
expected within Warner Music and EMI. When Seagram bought Polygram,
for example, thousands of jobs were lost, some record labels were
eliminated and hundreds of artists found themselves suddenly
without record contracts as the company cut about $300 million in
annual costs.
</P>
<P>
   Warner EMI Music wants to cut $400 million in annual costs by
the third year after the merger, people close to the deal said. But
they said the realignment would be less tumultuous than in the case
of Seagram and Polygram.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Warner Music has seen its share of newly released album sales in
the United States shrink to 13.7 percent in 1999 from 20.9 percent
in 1996, dropping it from No. 1 to No. 4 in the rankings, according
to Soundscan, a monitoring firm. The company lost or removed many
experienced executives in the mid-1990s and has been criticized for
relying too much on aging stars like Eric Clapton, Phil Collins and
Madonna rather than developing new acts. Warner also has
historically relied on distributing American acts around the world,
but many overseas audiences are beginning to prefer homegrown acts.
</P>
<P>
   EMI, which has been rumored to be for sale for years, has been
recovering from troubles of its own, but its presence in markets
outside the United States could help bolster Warner there.
</P>
<P>
   Ames, who took over as head of Warner Music in August, began
talks with EMI almost immediately _ initially, about joint
manufacturing and distribution. Ames, a native of Trinidad, started
his career with EMI in 1975 and then spent 18 years at Polygram. He
is intimately familiar with the British music business and friends
with Berry, the head of EMI Records.
</P>
<P>
   The music industry is on the cusp of change as more people begin
to obtain music electronically over the Internet rather than on a
compact disk sold at a record store. Gerald Levin, the chairman and
chief executive of Time Warner, has said that music will be the
first entertainment business to benefit from the Internet. Music
companies will be able to sell their existing music in a new form,
which provides an incentive to increase a company's catalog.
</P>
<P>
   One executive close to the transaction said Sunday, ``You want
to bulk up in music, both in the catalog and new releases.'' The
merger, for instance, will reunite the complete catalog of Frank
Sinatra recordings, some of which are now held by EMI's Capitol
Records and some by Warner's Reprise label. EMI's catalog also
includes the Beatles.
</P>
<P>
   Further industry consolidation could be in store. Indeed,
Bertelsmann AG, the German conglomerate that owns one of the
biggest record companies, has been saying publicly that it is
interested in buying other record companies. But besides Seagram,
Warner-EMI and Bertelsmann, the only other giant is Sony Music,
which is owned by Sony Corp. and might not be for sale. ``This is
it for the big guys,'' said Jessica Reif Cohen, an analyst at
Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   People familiar with the Warner-EMI deal say they expect it to
get antitrust approval in the United States and Europe, citing the
approval of the Seagram acquisition of Polygram. But some analysts
said that with the number of companies becoming smaller, the
antitrust scrutiny could grow more intense. EMI and Warner are also
the two largest companies in music publishing, which means they own
the copyrights of songs and collect royalties when the songs are
played. The two companies own copyrights of nearly 2 million songs.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Dean Witter acted as an adviser for Time Warner
in the deal, people close to the situation said. EMI was advised by
Warburg Dillon Read and Goldman, Sachs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
