<SLUG> BC-EXP-TIMEWARNER-EMI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME WARNER TO BUY CONTROL OF EMI'S MUSIC OPERATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK with ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time Warner Inc. plans to acquire control of the music business
of EMI Group and merge it with Warner Music, creating what could
become the world's largest record company, officials close to the
negotiations said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which is expected to be announced Monday in London,
would shrink the oligopoly of music companies that dominate the
world business from five to four. And coming two weeks after Time
Warner agreed to be acquired by America Online, the music merger
would create a force to be reckoned with in the fledgling business
of distributing music on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly underscores the premise of the AOL-Time Warner
merger and adds more sustenance to that deal,'' Jill S. Krutick, an
analyst with Salomon Smith Barney, said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The merged music company, to be known as Warner EMI Music, would
sell about one out of four records in the United States and also
have a vast international presence. EMI, whose roster of artists
includes the Rolling Stones, the Spice Girls and Robbie Williams,
has been strongest in Europe and some other international markets
like Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner's Warner Music, which has acts that include Madonna,
Eric Clapton and Jewel, has been strongest in the United States.
But its market share has plummeted in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner and EMI Group would each own 50 percent of Warner
EMI Music. But Time Warner would have a slight majority on the
board of directors and ultimate control. To gain this control, Time
Warner will pay EMI shareholders 1 pound per share, or about $1.65,
for a total payment of about $1.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   EMI Group would continue as a company with its own stock trading
on the London Stock Exchange. Its operations would consist of its
50 percent interest in the new joint record venture, plus some
other business that include a stake in the music retailer HMV.
</P>
<P>
   Simply combining the current sales of Warner Music and EMI
Records, the new company would have revenue of about $8 billion a
year. That would surpass the roughly $6 billion a year in sales of
the current industry leader, Seagram Co.'s Universal Music Group,
which itself became the leader through the 1998 acquisition of
Polygram. But some operations might be cut after the Warner
Music-EMI merger, people close to the deal said Sunday, so it is
possible that Seagram would remain the largest music company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
