<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-23 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4081 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-FORBES-HNS &LR;      01-23 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-FORBES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH, FOBES HIT SAME TURF ON FINAL DAY BEFORE IOWA CAUCUSES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATERLOO, Iowa _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush and publishing scion
Steve Forbes stumped for votes in dueling rallies here Sunday just
one day before Iowa's caucuses, with Forbes aiming a last indirect
shot at Bush on abortion while Bush urged his supporters to ``bring
a friend or relative'' out to vote Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Both were fighting temperatures that barely rose out of single
digits. They also were competing with the afternoon telecast of the
NFC championship game, which campaign officials feared would
depress turnout Sunday. St. Louis Rams quarterback Kirk Warner
played college ball at the nearby University of Northern Iowa and
is a local favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Bush drew about 500 of his partisans, packed so
tightly in a middle school gymnasium that one woman fainted in the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing with Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, Bush appeared
confident of a big night Monday night. The Des Moines Register,
Iowa's most influential newspaper, endorsed Bush on the Republican
side and former Sen. Bill Bradley on the Democratic side.
</P>
<P>
   The final Register poll also showed Bush leading Forbes by 23
points, 43 percent to 20 percent. Radio commentator Alan Keyes,
conservative activist Gary Bauer and Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz. _
who is not campaigning in Iowa _ were tied for third with eight
percent each. Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, was fourth with one
percent, and 14 percent were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   The same poll showed Vice President Al Gore ahead of Bradley, 56
percent to
</P>
<P>
   28 percent, with 16 percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
   The Register editorial endorsing Bush said, ``There is something
about George W. Bush that draws people to him,'' and the
endorsement praised Bush for speaking ``with conviction of not
wanting to leave anyone behind in America.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech Sunday, Bush did not mention the abortion
controversy. Instead he kept his remarks generally light, telling
the crowd the government can shore up the Social Security and
Medicare systems while instituting a tax cut, and that he supports
free trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fearful people build walls; confident people tear them down,''
he said to light applause.
</P>
<P>
   He stopped speaking after a woman briefly fainted and was
escorted out of the gym by paramedics and security personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Bush joked that his ``hot air'' had overcome her, later telling
the crowd she was OK.
</P>
<P>
   He told Republicans in his corner to ``bring a friend or
relative to your caucus tomorrow night.'' It was the classic
front-runner's anti-complacency plug: Don't assume that being ahead
in the polls means it is OK to stay home.
</P>
<P>
   Bush started the day in Des Moines and last night was to address
a rally in Mason City, the place upon which composer Meredith
Wilson based his Broadway hit ``The Music Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Forbes spoke to a crowd of 300 at the town's
convention center. In a veiled reference to Bush, he attacked
``others who for political expediency may hesitate'' in opposing
abortion. He reiterated his support for a constitutional amendment
banning abortion, as well as his pledge that his running mate and
judicial nominees also would be required to oppose abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion has proven to be a wedge issue for Forbes and an
irritation for Bush. On the one hand, Bush wants to appeal to
mainstream Republicans who are either pro-choice or who put
abortion below economic issues and taxes in importance. On the
other hand, social conservatives in Iowa are a vocal element of the
Republican Party whom he can ill afford to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes has called Bush ``timid'' and a ``pretender'' on
abortion, and he has campaigned with veteran anti-abortion activist
Phyllis Schlafly. Bauer has made abortion the central focus of his
longshot campaign, appearing with Bobbi and Kenny McCaughey, the
Iowans who became parents of septuplets in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Bush told reporters that he too supports the
``human life'' amendment to the Constitution, which has been a
plank in the Republican platform since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen how much potency the abortion issue will
have in terms of Monday night's results. Two who attended the Bush
rally, Kim and Debra Reida of Waverly, said that although they
staunchly oppose abortion, they felt drawn to Bush on other issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the whole person we're looking at, not the one issue,''
said Debra Reida, 39.
</P>
<P>
   Bush describes himself as `pro-life'' but has argued for
exceptions including rape, incest and to protect the life of the
mother. In debates, Bush declined to say he would require his
running mate and federal judicial appointees to oppose abortion as
a condition for selection.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Reporter Name can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address reportername &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
