<DOCNO> NYT20000123.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-23 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4082 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-NOMINATION-REFORM-2TA     01-23 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOMINATION-REFORM-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTIES STUDYING WAYS TO IMPROVE PRESIDENTIAL NOMINATING SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ROBIN TONER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even before the voting begins in this year's
primaries and caucuses, Republican and Democratic Party officials
are exploring ways to change a presidential nominating system that
critics say has become too chaotic, too fast for informed decision
making and even, in some fundamental ways, undemocratic.
</P>
<P>
   It is part of the American political tradition to complain about
the system of nominating presidential candidates. But rarely is the
chorus as loud as it is this year _ or the talk of change so
serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking the whole issue of what happens beyond 2000 very
seriously,'' said Joe Andrew, national chairman of the Democratic
National Committee. ``What's different is that both parties have
blue-ribbon committees out there studying whether front-loading is
a problem and seeking testimony on what the solution might be.''
</P>
<P>
   William E. Brock, the former senator and Republican National
Committee chairman who is heading his party's Advisory Commission
on the Presidential Nominating Process, said in an interview last
week, ``There is a very considerable number of states that feel
they have no voice, and frankly an awful lot of people feel they
have no effective voice in the selection process.'' He added,
``What we're trying to address is that need _ if people don't feel
they have a voice, there's no need to participate, and if they
don't participate, the system isn't working as well as it should.''
</P>
<P>
   Some states are always left behind in the nominating season,
holding primaries or caucuses long after a candidate has locked up
the nomination. But never has the process been more front-loaded,
or compressed with a flurry of big states, seeking greater
influence, having moved their primaries forward.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a six-week burst of voting that begins on Monday
in Iowa and reaches a climax on March 7 with primaries and caucuses
in 16 states, including California and New York. By mid-March, some
analysts say, the race for the nomination could well be resolved in
one or even both parties. Nobody knows what this will mean for the
voters, who some polls suggest are only beginning to pay attention.
But both parties are clearly worried.
</P>
<P>
   In one measure of how fast this calendar has become in recent
years, by March 15, 1984, seven states had held primaries, said
Rhodes Cook, the author of ``Race for the Presidency''
(Congressional Quarterly Press, 1999). By the same point this year,
25 states will have held primaries, so clustered together that some
analysts say they may pass most voters in a blur.
</P>
<P>
   A recent preliminary report by Brock's commission notes: ``There
has been increasing concern that a front-loaded nomination system
that ends almost as soon as it begins raises barriers to all but
the best-connected and well-funded candidates. Perhaps more
importantly, it may not allow voters adequate time to consider the
quality of various candidates and their views on the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, when Democratic organizers pushed to create
the modern primary system after the tumultuous convention of 1968,
the question was how open the process should be _ how to get more
grass-roots involvement by voters in the choice of a nominee, which
had been largely the purview of elected officials and party
leaders. Now the question is more nuanced: whether a technically
open process can nevertheless force a result before most voters are
engaged.
</P>
<P>
   In the week before the first caucus, a poll by the Shorenstein
Center on the Press, Politics and Public Policy at Harvard
University found that two-thirds of the voters were paying ``only a
little'' or no attention to the campaign, and that 70 percent said
they had no favorite candidate.
</P>
<P>
   If the race is declared over before they tune in, some scholars
suggest, it could only further the voters' disaffection and the
decline in turnout.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people in Iowa and New Hampshire, especially New Hampshire
this time around, will have a remarkable level of engagement with
the candidates and probably, at least by American standards, a very
high turnout in the primary,'' said William G. Mayer, a political
scientist at Northeastern University in Boston who studies the
nominating process. ``And voters in a handful of subsequent states,
like South Carolina and Michigan on the Republican side, New York
and California on the Democratic side, will have a reasonable
opportunity to hear the candidates debate and some opportunity to
compare them and reach a choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is, the system will probably reach a conclusion at
a very early stage _ in my view, about mid-March _ and for everyone
after that, they're not likely to see a lot of the candidates, the
press is not likely to spend a lot of time covering the process,
and turnout will fall off the table,'' Mayer added.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, when Sen. Bob Dole locked up the Republican nomination
with a blitz of early primaries in March, about 8.5 percent of the
eligible voters turned out in Republican primaries, substantially
below the comparable turnout 30 years ago, according to Curtis
Gans, director of the Committee for the Study of the American
Electorate.
</P>
<P>
   Gans added that there was no clear evidence that the compressed
schedule decreased turnout, but that once a winner was declared,
turnout plummeted.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Officials in both parties said they hoped their hearings and
reviews _ aimed at producing recommendations for action at the
Republican Convention this summer, later for the Democratic
National Committee _ would help answer the question of what this
primary structure does, if anything, to diminish political
participation. Both sides are hoping for bipartisan discussions
and, perhaps, a bipartisan consensus.
</P>
<P>
   Still, figuring out a way to ensure that states comply with a
new primary structure will be hard.
</P>
<P>
   Among the ideas that scholars and politicians have been debating
are a rotating series of regional primaries, a national primary and
primaries organized by time zone. Brock said there was particular
interest in organizing primaries by state populations: small states
would go first, allowing candidates an opportunity to do
small-scale grass-roots politicking; the biggest states would go
last. The primary clusters could be separated by as much as a
month, meaning that each group would get a chance at a full-blown
campaign.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the parties' decisions will be affected by what
happens in the next few months. And there is always the chance that
voters will find a way to defy the predictions and make this race
more of a long march than now seems likely.
</P>
<P>
   Illinois, for example, will not hold its primary until March 21,
but Jack Tatooles, a Republican township committeeman and ardent
supporter of Sen. John McCain, was the very picture of the happy
warrior on a recent afternoon, collecting ballot petitions and
taking calls from volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about other states,'' said Tatooles, the
co-chairman of McCain's Illinois campaign. ``But I can tell you
things are alive and well here and beyond my wildest
expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Not far away, Rep. Luis V. Gutierrez, a Chicago Democrat who is
supporting former Sen. Bill Bradley's presidential bid, voiced
similar sentiments about his man, but admitted he was worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at the tail end,'' Gutierrez said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
