<SLUG> BC-IOWA-CAUCUS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Iowa caucuses keep candidates rallying for support
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ The first presidential campaign of the new
millennium officially begins tonight here in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Voters from across the Hawkeye State attend caucuses,
essentially public meetings at local precincts, to make their
choices for president in the Republican and Democratic parties.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than 10 percent of Iowa's 1.8 million registered voters
are expected to turn out amid cold temperatures that are predicted
to range from 10 degrees in the north to the mid-30s in the south.
There is a chance of snow in some parts of the state, which could
further dampen turnout.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats Bill Bradley and Al Gore and a Republican field of
five candidates plan to have a day of campaigning in a final effort
to turn their supporters out to the caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   The caucuses begin at 7 p.m. CST, leaving all the candidates
time to generate some last-minute enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   For the front-runners and their closest competitors, the caucus
results will be a chance to claim some type of victory and create
momentum and positive media coverage heading into next Tuesday's
New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all of the candidates have been trying to lower
expectations for their own performance, while upping the ante for
their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants do better than expected and they want their
opponent to do worse than expected,'' said Drake University
political scientist Art Sanders. ``You want two or three days of
good stories to get you on a roll into a New Hampshire.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Cook, author of the Cook Political Report, said Sunday
that 15 point margins of victory for either front-runner, Texas
Gov. George W. Bush or Gore, would be decisive wins in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say that someone who wins by 15 points didn't
win,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign here entered the home stretch with a new poll
published Sunday showing both Bush and Gore holding commanding
leads.
</P>
<P>
   The Des Moines Register, the state's largest and most
influential newspaper, found Bush leading his closest competitor,
publisher Steve Forbes, 43 percent to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.), who hasn't actively campaigned in
Iowa, was in a statistical tie for third place with the two
religious conservatives in the race, former diplomat Alan Keyes and
Family Research Council founder Gary Bauer.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes and McCain polled 8 percent, while Bauer polled 6 percent.
Sen. Orrin Hatch (R-Utah) placed last with 1 percent. The margin of
error was 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The percentages are essentially unchanged from a similar
newspaper poll taken two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's results could shrink the Republican field by at least
one. Hatch said he will reassess his campaign if he doesn't place
better than fourth.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, Gore led Bradley 56 percent to 28
percent in the Register poll. Bradley's support slipped five points
from a poll taken two weeks ago, when he trailed Gore 33 percent to
54 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The slip could be trouble for Bradley if it accurately reflects
Monday's results because Bradley set the 31 percent Sen. Edward
Kennedy (D-Mass.) got in the 1980 Iowa primary as the test of an
``insurgent campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Caucus polls tend to be unreliable because they can not
accurately foretell who will attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's 30 below zero, you don't have any idea who's going to
show up,'' said Iowa Gov. Tom Vilsack, a Democrat who has remained
neutral. ``It's all up for grabs.''
</P>
<P>
   The unpredictably of tonight's contest leaves room for a few
potential surprises.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, Keyes has been drawing large crowds of
supporters attracted to his strident anti-abortion stance.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who has spent millions of his personal fortune
campaigning in Iowa, also has been aggressively campaigning on his
anti-abortion message in an effort to keep his conservative base.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes plans to continue the strategy in more than two dozen
radio interviews scheduled for today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to continue to talk to voters about the importance
of the campaign for conservatives,'' said Forbes spokesman Greg
Mueller. ``That's who turns out in caucuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Mueller said Forbes merely had to out-perform his recent poll
numbers to be successful in Iowa and move on to New Hampshire,
where McCain and Bush are locked in a tight race for first place.
</P>
<P>
   Bush planned to hold a rally with Iowa and Texas state
legislators in downtown Des Moines today in his final bid to get
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're looking at a man who's campaigning as hard as I can to
turn out the vote in Iowa,'' Bush said Sunday on ABC's This Week
with Sam Donaldson and Cokie Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Gore planned to rally with supporters in Cedar Rapids,
Davenport, then Des Moines.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley plans to attend a rally in Ames with university
students, who are a crucial part of his outsider challenge to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
