<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-WEIZMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT FACES ACCUSATIONS WITH DEFIANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Striking a note of somber defiance, President Ezer
Weizman of Israel on Sunday night refused either to resign or to
step down temporarily while police pursue a criminal investigation
of his receipt of hundreds of thousands of dollars from a French
businessman and political supporter.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief nationally televised address from his official
residence, Weizman proclaimed that he ``committed no crime,
committed no sin, and took nothing illegally.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressure on Weizman to quit has intensified in recent days, with
calls for his resignation coming from former allies and every major
newspaper as well as from his longtime foes on the political right.
But his stubborn insistence on Sunday night that he should be
investigated and judged like ``any other citizen'' seemed
characteristic of a man who built a political career on impolitic
contrarianism.
</P>
<P>
   Looking weary but speaking firmly, the beleaguered 75-year-old
president said he would issue a statement about the facts of the
affair when the investigation is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no intention of resigning,'' he said, reading from a
prepared text.
</P>
<P>
   ``I repeat, I have no intention of resigning. A man whose
conscience is clean is not afraid and does not run away.''
</P>
<P>
   Several key figures in the current government, including Justice
Minister Yossi Beilin, have urged Weizman to step aside temporarily
until the police investigation is concluded. The president was
widely expected to announce on Sunday night that he was taking this
advice.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said he had concluded that ``a leave of absence is
not a solution'' for a sitting president, who would nonetheless
remain Israel's official head of state. ``There is no difference
between a president on leave and an incumbent president,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's office has said it hopes the
investigation can be finished in a matter of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Through spokesmen, Weizman has acknowledged that when he was in
other government posts, he received more than $200,000 in publicly
undeclared gifts from Edouard Saroussi, a French-born textile
magnate and Israeli resident who was a key contributor to Weizman's
political campaigns in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Published allegations contend that Weizman received $453,000
from Saroussi between 1988 and 1993 and that his alleged failure to
declare the income could be evidence of tax fraud or bribery.
</P>
<P>
   Weizman repeated on Sunday night his previous insistence that
his income statements from that period had been approved by
respected tax attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if I erred, I made a human error in innocence,'' he said,
in the only indirect admission of any possible wrongdoing on his
part.
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday night's address, few voices were raised in
Weizman's defense. ``I think that the president erred tonight,''
said Shaul Yahalom, the chairman of the National Religious Party.
``He ought to have taken a leave of absence.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the overall tone of commentary was one of empathy and
regret, mixed with head-shaking astonishment at the president's
seeming incomprehension of the wide consensus that he can no longer
perform the role of head of state.
</P>
<P>
   The presidency, conceived as a unifying and stabilizing
institution aloof from the partisan fray, has been occupied by
elder statesmen whose personal characters were considered above
reproach _ beginning with the president's uncle, the revered Chaim
Weizmann.
</P>
<P>
   And Ezer Weizman himself, though a more flamboyant figure than
his predecessors, was similarly seen as a selfless patriot, a
visionary air force commander who had devoted his life to his
country's defense rather than to personal enrichment.
</P>
<P>
   The accusations against Weizman were first made by a free-lance
journalist here, Yoav Yitzhak, who has called a series of news
conferences to publicize his charges.
</P>
<P>
   In an almost daily stream of elaborations and fresh allegations,
Yitzhak recently claimed that Weizman had also received funds in
1984 from another French millionaire in return for a pledge not to
join a coalition government then being formed under the leadership
of the right-wing Likud Party. Weizman's lawyers called these
latest allegations a ``fantasy.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Israel's presidency is largely a ceremonial position, the
president has the power to appoint judges and to grant pardons. He
is himself constitutionally protected against prosecution _ though
not against criminal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Beilin, the justice minister, acknowledging that he was not
``pleased'' by what the president said on Sunday night, called on
him ``to take into account the law enforcement and legal systems,
and to avoid clemency decisions and the appointment of judges in
the period in which the investigation is under way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
