<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-23 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4106 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-U.N.-U.S.-ASSESS-950&AMP;     01-23 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-U.S.-ASSESS-950&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: BIG GUNS AT THE U.N.: HOLBROOKE'S DAZZLING CAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds., skedded earlier as U.N.-U.S.)  
(js) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Richard Holbrooke took over as Security Council president
for January, he declared it the month of Africa. But council
members have been getting more than an education on important
African issues, from an AIDS epidemic to multiple civil wars. They
have also been absorbing some lessons in American politics,
election year style.
</P>
<P>
   First, Holbrooke turned over his gavel and the Security Council
spotlight to Vice President Al Gore, who many expect will name
Holbrooke his secretary of state if elected president in the fall.
Gore, opening a daylong debate on the AIDS crisis on Jan. 10,
demonstrated his informed interest in a burning international issue
and how he might project U.S. leadership in an international arena.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was the turn of Sen. Jesse Helms, the North Carolina
Republican who is chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee, which can make or break presidential appointments and
long delayed Holbrooke's own. Helms basked in the glow of two days
of attention as he lectured the council last Thursday, at
Holbrooke's invitation, on what he sees as the United Nations'
shortcomings, even warning that the United States might withdraw
from the organization. The next day, Helms held a Senate Foreign
Relations Committee hearing on the same theme in New York.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will occupy the
council president's chair for a star-studded debate on Africa's
biggest war, in the Congo. Half a dozen or more African presidents
will be in town, including the elusive Laurent Kabila, the Congo's
president.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen other Security Council members, and those who track U.
N. affairs, are watching all this with fascination, and some
ambivalence. For some, the spectacle of a staid chamber being
turned over to theatrical meetings for an extended period of time
is troubling.
</P>
<P>
   Edward C. Luck, author of ``Mixed Messages: American Politics
and International Organization 1919-1999,'' said that hijacking a
month's agenda ``is sort of abusing what the Security Council
does.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of American hubris that leads to a reaction
from other countries,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But diplomats who have taken part in these sessions say that the
mercurial Holbrooke, whatever his motives, has not only brought
some sizzle to the council but has also contributed immeasurably to
its understanding of significant facts of life. Both Helms'
hostility to the United Nations and Africa's unending wars fall in
that category, diplomats say.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Holbrooke's carefully orchestrated meetings and his
nonstop hospitality to influential members of Congress _ several a
week _ may have made the United Nations safe again for American
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, during the last U.S. presidential election, the
United Nations was anathema. Its secretary general, Boutros
Boutros-Ghali was the butt of jokes and lampoons by Republicans on
his unfamiliar foreign name. The Clinton administration quickly
reduced its public involvement in the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the beginning of a new chapter for America's
involvement and engagement in the affairs of the United Nations,''
said Sen. Joseph Biden of Delaware, the ranking Democrat on the
foreign relations committee. Helms agreed and, after a lavish
dinner with diplomats at the Metropolitan Club in New York on
Friday night, told those around him that he had met extraordinarily
interesting people, had learned a lot and hoped they did too. He
was wearing a blue-and-white U.N. cap.
</P>
<P>
   At the U.N. Association, an independent U.S. support and
research organization, Jeffrey Laurenti said that the last week
shows that ``even the most conservative senators can visit the U.N.
now without fear of being tainted with soft-headedness.'' This
pointed to ``a quiet sea change in how Washington's political class
views the United Nations,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be hard for any successor to Holbrooke to give the
U.N. this visibility and importance to Washington's movers and
shakers,'' Laurenti, the association's director of policy studies,
said. ``But his remarkable success to date at the United Nations
reflects the very real, if still fragile, American re-engagement
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Sen. John Warner, chairman of the Senate Armed Services
Committee, said Friday in a meeting with U.N. officials that Helms
and Biden were brave to be there. ``No one in the history of the
Senate ever got elected on supporting the United Nations,'' said
Warner, a Virginia Republican who also urged the United Nations to
make sure it runs its operations in Bosnia and Kosovo well before
plunging into yet more difficult tasks in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke brushed aside Warner's statement as political
posturing. ``For these senators to come to the U.N., that's the
point,'' he said in an interview Saturday. ``They make those
statements later to protect themselves with their constituents.''
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke has his critics, however. In particular, diplomats
were puzzled by the absence of a Democrat or an administration
official to rebut Helms at the same Security Council meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Council members who did not understand the political dynamics of
the event might have been left with a very bleak view of American
attitudes toward the organization, and a sense that foreign policy
is made in the Senate, not the State Department or the White House,
said one diplomat who attended the session.
</P>
<P>
   Biden made an effort to balance the portrayal of American
opinion at a closed-door lunch with diplomats, at which he was
outspoken in his disagreements with Helms.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Biden also told Secretary-General Kofi Annan and reporters that
he was not in favor of the benchmarks the Senate placed on payments
of debts to the United Nations, which make demands on the
organization no country has ever tried to impose.
</P>
<P>
   However, he acknowledged that he did not have the votes to do
that _ and then defended his decision to agree to those conditions
in a deal with Helms in order to have any money released.
</P>
<P>
   Biden took issue with Helms' assertion to the council that the
United States would withdraw from the United Nations if the
organization failed to meet its demands. ``It will never happen,''
Biden said. He also attacked what he called the ``nostalgia'' for
the anti-communist Reagan doctrine, which Helms had said did more
for democracy in the world than the United Nations. ``Thank God
it's dead,'' Biden said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
