<HEADLINE>
JACKSON WON'T SECOND-GUESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Plenty went wrong in the second half of the Los
Angeles Lakers' Saturday-night loss to the Portland Trail Blazers,
but coach Phil Jackson wasn't in a second-guessing mood Sunday.
Particularly when the subject was Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal was in the game for 47 minutes and looked tired and in
effective down the stretch. He also wasn't on the floor for the
crucial possession with 13.6 seconds left and the Lakers down by
two points.
</P>
<P>
   But, Jackson, noted, ``We had an ample opportunity to win that
game.''
</P>
<P>
   They did, but the Lakers wouldn't have needed to win on a
last-gasp effort had they protected a 10-point lead. That lead
disappeared when O'Neal, their best offensive weapon, struggled _ 2
for 8 in the second half, with two rebounds and no trips to the
foul line.
</P>
<P>
   Would Jackson rethink his reliance on O'Neal, who's now played
47 minutes in three of the past four games, with diminishing
returns?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see what that really has to do with anything but
playing,'' Jackson said. ``He got his blocks, he still was active
enough to block shots. He had five blocked shots the second half,
so obviously he still had a lot of energy. But somehow or other
things just weren't going, the ball wasn't bouncing for him. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``(In the third quarter) he had two point-blank shots, the ball
rolled off the basket. That makes a big difference. Some of that is
just bounces. Some of it's the fact that we were in (a defensive)
rotation to try and help ... and he wasn't in position to rebound.
He did look tired at the end of the game, but that's natural. He
should be tired at the end of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson also said he probably would have removed O'Neal for the
final play even if he hadn't been struggling from the line recently
(14 for 39 in the past four games). ``No, I like what we did,''
Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Without O'Neal or the fouled-out Kobe Bryant on the floor, and
with Glen Rice covered, Derek Fisher took the potential
game-winning shot and threw up an airball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't like the fact that Derek didn't hit iron,'' Jackson
said. ``We did everything to put ourselves in position to win. Shaq
shooting foul (shots) ... I don't know. Maybe going back to that
again and re-look at it, you're right.''
</P>
<P>
   Diversify: Jackson admitted the Blazers, led by his former
student, Scottie Pippen, used their familiarity with the Lakers'
offense to adroitly defend it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of things that Portland did to disrupt our
offense the second half. They kept dislocating our players so that
we couldn't make passes in our offense,'' he said. ``Pippen was in
the midst of what we were trying to do a lot of times.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Lakers are still running a simplified version of the
triangle offense, Jackson said they're not becoming predictable
``just not executing sharply enough.''
</P>
<P>
   If teams are learning the Lakers' tendencies over time, they
could be in trouble today at Utah. The Lakers are facing the Jazz
for the third time this season; both the Blazers and Seattle
SuperSonics beat the Lakers in their third meetings last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
