<SLUG> BC-NH-MCCAIN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McCAIN ACCEPTS LABEL OF `LIBERAL'  
(rk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ Is Sen. John McCain a ``liberal in Republican
clothing?''
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire for a final 10-day push to the nation's first
primary, McCain, an Arizona Republican, was confronted with that
question at one of the day's three town hall meetings. It echoed
the charges of some of his Republican rivals who have compared him
to Vice President Al Gore or suggested that his modest tax cut plan
is one that President Clinton could favor.
</P>
<P>
   At first McCain pointed to his bedrock conservative voting
record across 17 years in Congress, saying votes can be ``a better
barometer than someone's rhetoric.'' But soon he was making an
impassioned plea for his party to consider the plight of the poor
and the weak and refusing to disavow a political label that even
Democrats flee from.
</P>
<P>
   McCain called himself a disciple not just of Ronald Reagan and
Theodore Roosevelt, but Abraham Lincoln too. ``That means we do
care about those in our society who can't care for themselves,'' he
told a crowd packed into a school here. ``We do care about the
elderly. We do care about the poor. We do care about those
Americans with disabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said the gap between the haves and the have nots in
society ``is not healthy for America'' and described the Republican
Party as an ``inclusive party'' that recognizes anyone who shares a
philosophy of less government, less regulation, lower taxes, and
caring for the needy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess if you quote call me a liberal because of those
positions that I have, than I would gladly accept that label,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain had the state of New Hampshire to himself as the other
presidential contenders campaigned in Iowa, where the precinct
caucuses take place on Monday. The senator long ago wrote off Iowa
to focus on New Hampshire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
