<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AFC-MAIN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Titans solve Jaguars a third, final time
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ For three years, the Tennessee Titans were
the team nobody wanted. Now, they might just be destiny's team.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans, a seven-point underdog, used a quick 16-point
barrage in the third quarter to stun the Jaguars 33-14 in the AFC
Championship game Sunday at Jacksonville's Alltel Stadium. The
victory sends the Titans to Super Bowl XXXIV in the Georgia Dome
next Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt about it, we are a team of destiny,'' Tennessee
strong safety Blaine Bishop said. ``Now, the whole world knows
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee is only the sixth wild-card team to advance to the
Super Bowl since the NFL playoffs were expanded in 1978. It is the
team's first trip to the Super Bowl in the 40-year history of the
franchise and follows three consecutive 8-8 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a step behind Jacksonville all year,'' Tennessee coach
Jeff Fisher said. ``We just couldn't catch them. When people said,
`There's no way that you're going to win three times against the
same team,' we never batted an eye. When people said the Jaguars
were indeed looking forward to playing us again, nobody batted an
eye.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory also helped erase one of the most forgettable
episodes in NFL history, when the Oilers/Titans played before
half-empty stadiums and apathetic crowds in Houston, Memphis and
Vanderbilt Stadium in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about time,'' said owner Bud Adams, who founded the
franchise in Houston in 1960. ``I'm getting pretty old. I didn't
want to go to the Super Bowl in a wheelchair.''
</P>
<P>
   The defeat was a huge disappointment for Jacksonville, which had
the league's best regular-record (14-2) and seemed invincible in a
62-7 blowout of the Dolphins a week earlier.
</P>
<P>
   All three of Jacksonville's losses this season were to the
Titans. ``No way to explain it,'' Jaguars running back Fred Taylor
said. ``It just happened.
</P>
<P>
   Jaguars offensive tackle Leon Searcy said: ``It doesn't even
seem like it's real.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither does the Titans' wild ride through the postseason.
Playing in its first season in Adelphia Coliseum, Tennessee needed
an improbable kickoff return for a touchdown _ dubbed the
``Immaculate Deception'' _ to beat Buffalo 22-16 in the first
round.
</P>
<P>
   In the divisional playoffs, the Titans upset No. 2 seed
Indianapolis 19-16. The Titans were again seven-point underdogs
playing Jacksonville, the top seed in the AFC. But Tennessee
matched the Jaguars punch for punch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jaguars thought they were going to blow us out,'' Titans
defensive tackle Josh Evans said. ``But this was like a heavyweight
fight. We kept trading punches, but they didn't think ours were
coming.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars threw the first blow. On the Jaguars' opening drive,
quarterback Mark Brunell hit tight end Kyle Brady with a 7-yard
touchdown pass with 11:20 left in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee answered on its ensuing possession. After an
interception was nullified by pass interference, receiver Yancey
Thigpen scored on a 9-yard catch to tie the score at 7 with 9:51
left in the first.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville took a 14-7 lead in the second quarter on James
Stewart's 33-yard touchdown run with 4:36 left.
</P>
<P>
   But the Titans, after trailing 14-10 at halftime, took over with
a 16-point scoring outburst in about four minutes of the third
quarter. Quarterback Steve McNair scored on a 9-yard run to take a
17-14 lead with 9:24 left in the third.
</P>
<P>
   After Tennessee tight end Frank Wycheck lost a fumble at the
Jaguars' 1, Brunell was sacked in the end zone for a safety and a
19-14 Titans lead about four minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   On the ensuing free kick, Titans receiver Derrick Mason fielded
Bryan Barker's punt and ran 80 yards for a touchdown and a 26-14
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It changed the momentum when we got the safety and then the
return,'' Wycheck said. ``That was a breath of fresh air, new life
into our team. We knew we had them on the ropes.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair, who battled turf toe on his left foot all week,
delivered the knockout blow in the fourth quarter. Facing
third-and-1, McNair broke loose for a 47-yard run to the Jaguars'
1. He scored on the next play for a 33-14 lead with 6:59 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of guys on this team that were told their entire
lives that they'd never play in the NFL,'' Evans said. ``But we're
a blue-collar team. Somebody had to go down and, fortunately, we
were the last ones standing.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
