<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN IOWA, THE NEWS MEDIA ARE EVERYWHERE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Over coffee at the Waveland Diner on Sunday,
the NBC anchor Tom Brokaw was telling a group of Iowans that by his
calculation, if the reporters and editors covering the caucuses
were voting in them, they would make up 1 percent of the
electorate.
</P>
<P>
   This did not faze Steve Kopf, a supporter of Steve Forbes who
was one of several local people being interviewed by Brokaw. ``The
media,'' Kopf argued, ``should pay more attention to Iowa.''
</P>
<P>
   Brokaw looked stricken. ``I don't think that's possible,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   It does seem, at times, that if one more journalist were to set
foot here, Iowa would collapse under the weight of ink and wiring.
For if the caucuses, the inaugural election-year test of the
candidates for president, are normally an event of immense interest
for the news media, they are being even more intensively
scrutinized, analyzed and reported on this year than ever before,
especially by the electronic press.
</P>
<P>
   With the advent of the 24-hour cable news channels _ two of
which, Fox News Channel and MSNBC, had not even been launched by
this time four years ago _ the rise of political coverage on the
Web and contested races in both parties, the caucuses are destined
to be one of the most plugged-into political events the Midwest has
ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier to be here now than ever before,'' said David
Yepsen, the chief political writer for The Des Moines Register, who
has been covering politics here for 26 years. ``Satellite time is
cheaper. The gear is cheaper.'' Several newscasts on the Web are
starting this week, he added, ``And Fox and MSNBC didn't exist last
time,'' said Yepsen. ``There's more media altogether.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there is enough public affairs programming being beamed
out of Des Moines this week to send the most rabid political addict
into a kind of sugar shock. CNN, the granddaddy of all-news on
cable, has 200 staff members here working on a total of eight
separate talk shows, political shows, legal shows and newscasts.
``Our level of coverage is not driven by the level of viewer
interest,'' said Bernard Shaw, the CNN anchor and the host with
Judy Woodruff of the popular ``Inside Politics'' show. ``This is a
compelling story because it is the first event in a yearlong drive
to the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   The network Sunday talk shows all originated from Des Moines
this weekend. C-SPAN took out a full-page advertisement in the
Register on Friday, trumpeting its ``All politics all weekend''
coverage, including live transmissions from caucuses in towns with
names like Mingo. The Fox News Channel secured the State Capitol
rotunda and chambers of the state legislature as the sets for the
variety of political talk and news shows it is broadcasting all
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Obtaining the embodiment of government for the visuals was
viewed by Fox as a coup. ``We first came here in September,'' said
Marty Ryan, executive producer for Fox News. ``We wanted a location
that said `Iowa.'''
</P>
<P>
   Fox also wanted a talking head who spoke Iowan. So they put
Yepsen under contract. On Saturday, he was a guest on ``The Beltway
Boys,'' one of the seemingly countless cable gabfests chewing on
Iowa politics. It is hosted by Morton Kondracke and Fred Barnes,
formerly panel members on ``The McLaughlin Group.'' The show was
taped in the ornate rotunda, with the Boys' high-tech desk _ its
circular Lucite lights made it look like a piece of office
furniture from ``The Jetsons'' _ added to the historic
surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes and Kondracke have day jobs as editors, respectively, at
two Washington-centric publications, the Weekly Standard and Roll
Call. On cable, they compete weekly for the loyalty of a rather
small subset of the American viewing public, a pool Barnes defines
as ``the 10 million who are political junkies, who are interested
in public affairs.'' Their 18-month-old show, each installment of
which is rerun several times on the channel, has a viewership in
the hundreds of thousands, as opposed to millions, said a
spokeswoman for the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're more exciting than golf,'' Barnes maintained, adding
that more and more, political discourse is moving from the networks
to cable. Many in the cable news business cite as a watershed event
the decision by Ted Koppel and ``Nightline'' four years ago to
depart the Republican National Convention before it ended.
``Network television once served them, and now it's C-SPAN and Fox
and MSNBC,'' Kondracke said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is network stars like Brokaw who generate the most
buzz. After he finished a roundtable interview with a group of
voters in the diner, for broadcast on Sunday night, the congenial
anchor autographed copies of his best-seller, ``The Greatest
Generation,'' for the interviewees and one for Nancy Holmes, a Des
Moines high school teacher who was waiting with her own copy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brokaw is a hero of mine,'' said Ms. Holmes, who majored in
journalism in college. ``I'd rather meet Brokaw than any of the
candidates _ except maybe Bradley.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
