<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY GATHERS ENDORSEMENTS FROM 5 PAPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Mass., N.H., Calif.)  
(js) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CEDAR RAPIDS, Iowa _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley spent the final
day before the Iowa caucuses at three college campuses, trying to
energize the students and professors he hopes will help power his
insurgent candidacy to a strong finish in the first vote of the
presidential primary season.
</P>
<P>
   At Cornell College in Mount Vernon, more than 400 people crowded
into a small room to hear Bradley's call to reduce poverty, bring
health care to all Americans and help people ``find meaning in life
that is deeper than material things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not lead unabashedly from your ideals in this country so
you can give people a North Star to guide by,'' said Bradley, who
was loose and animated.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Bradley addressed enthusiastic crowds at the University
of Iowa in Iowa City and Drake University in Des Moines.
</P>
<P>
   After struggling through one of the most difficult weeks of the
campaign, Bradley's aides were almost triumphant Sunday in
announcing endorsements from five newspapers: the Des Moines
Register and Fort Dodge Messenger in Iowa, the Nashua Telegraph and
Valley News in New Hampshire, and the Lawrence Eagle Tribune in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Anna Eshoo of Palo Alto, Calif., on Sunday became the 11th
member of Congress to endorse Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley took four hours off in the middle of the day to attend a
memorial service for John Crystal, the honorary chairman of his
campaign, who died last week.
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance on ABC's Face the Nation Sunday morning,
Bradley articulated a message his aides said he plans to repeat
often in the coming week: that he would be better at managing the
nation's prosperity than Vice President Al Gore, his rival for the
Democratic nomination, because of his ability to predict changes in
the economy.
</P>
<P>
   On ABC, Bradley also rejected suggestions that he might drop out
of the race if he loses in both Iowa, as is expected, and New
Hampshire, where the race is tight. ``I hope that we're going to
have major wins down the road, and we'll be able to move on to the
convention, no question about that,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
