<SLUG> BC-IOWA-FORBES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DAY OF POLITICAL THEATER FOR FORBES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMES, Iowa _ Sunday did not start out particularly well for
Steve Forbes. The Des Moines Register carried its endorsement of
George W. Bush and published a recent poll showing that Forbes, who
has spent more than $25 million on his current presidential bid,
has not budged from the 20 percent standing in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   That poll still has a large number of undecided voters, and the
Forbes campaign has long said that they must get a healthy share of
the uncommitted vote. A strong showing in Iowa is vital for Forbes
to propel his long-shot bid as he campaigns in New Hampshire, where
he is a distant third, behind Bush and Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   At an appearance before around 170 people at Iowa State
University here, Forbes reiterated his opposition to abortion and
called again for lower taxes _ when he said ``we are overtaxed in
this country,'' the crowd roared back a hearty ``yes, yes'' and
applauded.
</P>
<P>
   It was also a day of high political theater. At a press
conference following his appearance, Forbes accused the Bush
campaign of calling Forbes supporters and, when they say they are
supporting Forbes, their phone call gets patched into a
``pro-abortion group that is tacitly supporting Bush and they do a
job on me,'' said Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes identified that group as the Republican Leadership
Council, an independent liberal Republican group. ``The RLC is
financed by Bush people and they've attacked me before,'' said
Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   To underscore Forbes' anti-abortion stand, he is running graphic
anti-abortion television ads, featuring a fetus shown in a
sonogram, with the heavy sound of a beating heart. A woman's voice
says that she doesn't understand that if the killing of animals is
illegal, why the same shouldn't be true for babies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
