</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLL SHOWS GORE'S LEAD OVER BRADLEY WIDENING 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWTON, Iowa _ With a new poll showing his lead growing over
former Sen. Bill Bradley, Vice President Al Gore Sunday went after
another opponent _ complacency.
</P>
<P>
   A poll in The Des Moines Register Sunday showed Gore's lead over
Bradley widening to 28 points from 21 points two weeks ago. Gore
was ahead 56 percent to 28 percent, with about 10 percent of likely
caucusgoers undecided.
</P>
<P>
   As Gore raced across central and eastern Iowa Sunday by bus and
airplane, he pleaded with audiences to turn out for him in this
state's caucuses on Monday. He canvassed door to door in a
neighborhood in Des Moines. He spent hours on his bus telephoning
precinct captains to urge them to ferry voters to the caucuses. And
he attended a training session for precinct workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please do not believe the polls,'' he implored about 150
campaign workers Sunday morning at a meeting at Rastrelli's
Restaurant in Clinton. ``Don't let anyone foster the slightest hint
of complacency or overconfidence, because the only decision that
matters is the one that will come out of the caucus itself, the one
in your precinct.''
</P>
<P>
   In the only shadow over the Gore campaign, The Des Moines
Register, the biggest and most influential newspaper in Iowa,
endorsed Bradley Sunday. Its editorial said that Gore ``is sharp on
the issues and can recite the details of just about every
government program'' and that he ``campaigns with an intensity that
borders on excess.''
</P>
<P>
   But, it said, Bradley ``has the better appreciation of the
possibilities'' for overcoming the partisanship in Washington and
has ``the right kind of leadership to realize them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
