<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE HAS A REID ON TRINIDAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ David Reid is hesitant to say exactly what he
learned about Felix Trinidad by watching the Trinidad-Oscar De La
Hoya bout. He just smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot. I'm just not going to tell you,'' he said,
laughing, at a news conference to promote his bout against Trinidad
on March 3 in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after more prodding, he spoke generally about his
impressions of Trinidad's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked a little slow,'' he said, trying not to be
inflammatory. ``... After watching that fight, yes, I'm very
confident because Oscar De La Hoya ... he exposed him.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, Reid is biased. He has to defend his WBA junior middleweight
championship against Trinidad in the most compelling matchup (with
Fernando Vargas-Ike Quartey) scheduled this year. He's supposed to
say that his opponent is vulnerable and he will take advantage of
it.
</P>
<P>
   He just happens to be right in this case. Trinidad was exposed,
at least to some extent.
</P>
<P>
   Sound ridiculous? Tell that to the bettors.
</P>
<P>
   The Reid-Trinidad odds opened at roughly 3-1 for Trinidad on
Wednesday. However, that dropped immediately to 2-1 because heavy
early betting was on Reid.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, such a thing seems strange in a sense. Big, bad Trinidad,
the pride of Puerto Rico, has been welterweight champ since he
knocked out Maurice Blocker to win the IBF title in 1993. He's had
15 title defenses and beat De La Hoya in September to add the WBC
version.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad would seem to be seasoned: He's 36-0 with 30 knockouts.
And, generally, his performances have been impressive: He has
dominated most opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Reid? The only American to win a gold medal in the 1996 Olympics
would seem a work in progress.
</P>
<P>
   However, a few things just don't seem right on Trinidad's side
of the ledger.
</P>
<P>
   One, aside from De La Hoya, his most significant opponents have
been Oba Carr and an aging, shell-of-himself Pernell Whitaker. It
remains difficult to gauge Trinidad because of mediocre
competition.
</P>
<P>
   And, two, there's that darned De La Hoya fight.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad, who struts around as if he's Sugar Ray Robinson,
didn't win as much as De La Hoya lost. The Tarnished Boy, thinking
he'd won the fight, ran the final three rounds and Trinidad
narrowly won on points.
</P>
<P>
   We saw what we saw _ a seemingly ordinary, frustrated boxer who
couldn't touch De La Hoya for three quarters of a fight. Most
conspicuously, Trindad looked painfully slow, which was shocking in
light of his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that I have any advantages except my speed,''
Reid said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, is picking Reid to beat Trinidad going too far?
</P>
<P>
   Not only is Reid a babe in terms of experience, he hasn't looked
particularly impressive. He beat a marginal champion in Laurent
Boudouani to win his title and outpointed Kevin Kelly and Keith
Mullings in his two defenses. Not exactly a glorious run to the
top.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he'll win on March 3.
</P>
<P>
   He's bigger, stronger and faster than Trinidad. Simple as that.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad will be fighting at 154 pounds for only the second time
in his career. He stopped Troy Waters in 1997 at 153 pounds, which
he says gives him confidence that he can handle himself at junior
welterweight.
</P>
<P>
   However, his knees were buckled a few times when De La Hoya hit
him. What's going to happen when a solid 154-pounder with a good
punch lands a big right on his suspect chin? It'll be interesting
to find out.
</P>
<P>
   OK, no one will be surprised if Trinidad wins. He has had twice
as many fights as Reid. And there's Reid's droopy eyelid, which has
caused him problems in his past.
</P>
<P>
   It might turn out that Trinidad's ability _ which he has yet to
display against an elite fighter _ will compensate for Reid's
advantages. And, after all, Trinidad is the favorite.
</P>
<P>
   In light of evidence, the underdog is simply the better choice
in this case.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won a gold medal, he won a championship,'' Trinidad said
through an interpreter. ``He must be good.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe too good for Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad-De La Hoya: Trinidad is tired of questions about
passing up $20 million to fight De La Hoya for about $5 million to
face Reid, the result of failed negotiations between his promoter,
Don King, and De La Hoya's, Bob Arum.
</P>
<P>
   His response: ``Ask De La Hoya why he passed up $20 million to
fight me (for a smaller payday when he faces Derrell Coley on Feb.
26)?
</P>
<P>
   ``. .. People have to understand. I was willing to fight one
more time at welterweight. !ital!He didn't want it. Now I'm not
going to worry about it. I'm focusing on Reid.''
</P>
<P>
   Arum has said he will try to make a second De La Hoya-Trinidad
fight in June, presumably if Trinidad will come back down to 147
pounds. Trinidad believes De La Hoya and Co. purposely delayed the
fight because they know Trinidad won't return to 147.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what I think? I think he's afraid of me,'' Trinidad
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still around: Julio Cesar Chavez, 37, is scheduled to fight on
the Reid-Trinidad undercard. Organizers have yet to sign an
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, King put the popular Chavez on the card to bolster
pay-per-view sales because the card is on Friday and he's competing
against a March 4 card featuring WBA bantamweight champ Paulie
Ayala against Jimmy Bredahl.
</P>
<P>
   If Chavez wins, he's expected to face WBC junior welterweight
champ Kostya Tszyu next in what could be Chavez's final title
fight.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley-De La Hoya? If they can't make Trinidad-De La Hoya, Shane
Mosley Might face De La Hoya in June at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley made that prospect even more interesting with his third-
round knockout of Willy Wise on Saturday. There's no doubt that
Mosley is a legitimate welterweight.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right: Mike Tyson, who faces Julius Francis on Saturday in
Manchester, England, said he would've beaten both Evander Holyfield
and Lennox Lewis in his prime.
</P>
<P>
   He believes his stints in prison had a devastating effect on his
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I hadn't been in trouble and been off so many times, you
wouldn't have heard of those guys. I would have gutted them like
fish,'' Tyson said.
</P>
<P>
   Not likely.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom inside the boxing world is that Holyfield
has had Tyson's number since they were amateurs and the style and
courage to beat him consistently. And remember: Holyfield wasn't
exactly in !ital!his prime when he beat the you know what out of
Tyson in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   We'll never know how Tyson might've done against Lewis in his
prime. However, we do know that Lewis would've towered over Tyson
and outweighed him by about 30 pounds. With that advantage and
Lewis' solid skills, he certainly wouldn't have been ``gutted.''
</P>
<P>
   Branching out: Holyfield hopes to give a boost to the ``club
fighters'' of the music world.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield is launching Real Deal Records to provide
opportunities for unknown adult contemporary, hip-hop and
contemporary music acts.
</P>
<P>
   Nine artists already have signed with the label, it was
announced by Trans World Entertainment, which will be Real Deal's
distributor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-00 2055EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
