<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUG-MERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKS ON BIG MERGER CONTINUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Discussions by executives at Procter &AMP; Gamble and the drug
makers Warner-Lambert and American Home Products continued over the
weekend as Procter &AMP; Gamble explored whether to buy one or both
drug companies in a deal that would create one of the largest
consumer-products and pharmaceutical companies in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Procter &AMP; Gamble _ whose consumer brands include Tide, Pampers
and Crest _ could announce as early as Monday that it is proceeding
with formal merger negotiations, a person close to the talks said.
Industry executives and analysts say that if the company's chief
executive, Durk I. Jager is going to strike a deal, he needs to do
so quickly or risk having the uncertainty do further damage to his
company's stock price.
</P>
<P>
   ``P&AMP;G can't drag its feet,'' said Neil B. Sweig, a drug analyst
at Ryan, Beck &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Procter &AMP; Gamble's share price fell 9 percent on Friday to
$102.6875 _ down 12 percent for the week _ suggesting that
shareholders are concerned about the prospect of spending more than
$142 billion to buy the two drug companies.
</P>
<P>
   An executive who talked with P&AMP;G officials over the weekend
agreed with Sweig's assessment. ``The people that own P&AMP;G _ the
investors _ don't have the stomach for roller-coaster rides,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   American Home is primarily a maker of over-the-counter remedies
like Advil but also makes drugs like Premarin, a
hormone-replacement treatment. Warner-Lambert is best known for
Lipitor, a prized cholesterol-lowering drug, and consumer brands
like Schick razors.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies announced in November that they would merge in
a stock deal that was worth $78 billion at the time. But the deal
was thrown into immediate uncertainty by the drug maker Pfizer
Inc., which made an $82 billion hostile bid for Warner-Lambert.
Pfizer's products include the popular male-impotence treatment
Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago Warner-Lambert finally agreed to talk to Pfizer,
even as it seeks other suitors. People close to Pfizer and
Warner-Lambert said the two companies had been discussing a
possible price, but no figure had been agreed upon. The discussions
centered on an exchange of three shares of Pfizer stock for every
Warner-Lambert share, higher than the 2.5-share offer now on the
table.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the executive who spoke with Procter officials over
the weekend said discussions continued between Procter and
Warner-Lambert ``at the highest level.''
</P>
<P>
   To signal Procter's eagerness to grow faster by buying its way
into new, potentially lucrative businesses _ especially
pharmaceuticals _ the company lately has described itself as a
technology company that just happens to be in consumer products.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people have the misimpression that P&AMP;G is a marketing
company,'' Dr. Ralph Snyderman, a Procter board member, said
Sunday. ``In the future, it will be a technology-driven company.''
</P>
<P>
   Some industry analysts have speculated that Procter might be
seeking a different partner, possibly in lieu of a deal with
American Home or Warner-Lambert. Snyderman would not comment on
that, but did say, ``P&AMP;G, I have found, is always looking around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-00 2102EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
