<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-ICESTORM24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia ice storm puts freeze on power
 &HT;    By Paul Donsky
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A winter storm coated much of the northern third of
the Georgia in a sheet of ice Sunday, leaving downed trees, snapped
power and phone lines and darkened homes.
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday night, about 200,000 customers remained without power.
Power company officials said outages were so widespread it could
take several days before electricity is fully restored.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Roy Barnes declared a state of emergency in 15 counties.
</P>
<P>
   At one time Sunday morning, more than 500,000 customers were in
the dark, the biggest power failure in the area since Hurricane
Opal in 1995. It took six days to fully restore power after that
storm.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Power called in crews from south Georgia and Alabama and
had about 1,000 people working to restore power to homes and
businesses. The effort was hampered by poor weather that kept power
lines falling throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Limbs are still falling on lines, and that is not helping us
make progress. It's a little like sliding backward when you're
climbing on a hill,'' said Tal Wright, Georgia Power spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Power outages were reported over a widespread area in Georgia,
but they were scattered. On some streets, power remained on at some
homes and off at others. In other areas, entire neighborhoods lost
power.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 2.5 million phone lines in metro Atlanta, only 3,000
lines were reported out Sunday, said BellSouth spokeswoman Lynn
Bress. However, Bress said repair crews expected that number to
grow as more trees fall and people come home to find their phones
dead.
</P>
<P>
   The problems stretched all the way to North Carolina, where
major utilities reported about 20,000 customers without electricity
Sunday after parts of that state got a mixture of sleet, rain and
snow. However, Carolina Power &AMP; Light spokeswoman Sally Ramey said
not all of the outages could be blamed on the weather.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters say the Atlanta area is not out of the woods.
Temperatures were expected to drop overnight to freezing, meaning
areas still wet could refreeze, said Matt Sena, meteorologist with
the National Weather Service in Peachtree City.
</P>
<P>
   The good news: Precipitation is expected to end today, with
temperatures warming to the low 40s, according to the National
Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writers Diane Stepp, Chris
Quinn, Janet Frankston, Gary Hendricks, Rick Badie, R. Robin
McDonald, Doug Payne and Joshua B. Good contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
