<HEADLINE>
CITIZEN-SOLDIERS ARE INCREASINGLY CALLED TO SERVICE IN A DWINDLING
MILITARY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Va., Pa.)   (Subs 8th graf to add details on De La Rosa's family history;subs
18th graf, (bgng `The Army has now...' in orig. text) to add
sentence to beginning on U.S. involvement in Bosnia and readiness
of regular forces.) 
(EDS: This special report is the first article in an occasional
series on the National Guard and the 49th Armored Division. An
abridged version, NATIONAL-GUARD-ABRIDGED, is also being sent.)  
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Daniel L. Teafatiller, a rancher, sold all his
cattle, except his two prize bulls, which he asked his son-in-law
to look after while he is away. Patrick F. Martin, an account
manager for Microsoft, is trying not to think about the six-figure
stock bonus he will miss when he is gone. Ron De La Rosa, a lawyer
with his own practice down by the courthouse here, is scrambling to
try or settle as many cases as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a murder the judge wants me to finish before I go,''
he said the other day in his office.
</P>
<P>
   De La Rosa and the others are citizen-soldiers, members of the
Texas National Guard who serve one weekend a month and two weeks
each summer _ unless a national crisis compels them to answer the
call to duty. That was always a possibility, they knew, but for
years, a remote one.
</P>
<P>
   Now the call has come. Only there is no war, no tornado, no riot
to quell. Instead, the Army has ordered them to set aside their
civilian lives, their jobs and their families to serve as
peacekeepers in a faraway place that few of them gave much thought
to a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   In February, about 700 men and women of the 49th Armored
Division _ the Lone Star Division _ are to board transport planes
and fly to Bosnia, not for a couple of weeks, but for nearly nine
months. On March 7, they will take command of the U.S. sector in
NATO's operation there, responsible for ensuring that Bosnia's
tenuous peace somehow endures.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has deployed guard and reserve units overseas
before; more than 265,000 guardsmen and reservists were called up
to support the Persian Gulf War in 1990 and 1991. But the 49th's
mission is something new. The division is sending its headquarters
company, which includes the commanders and senior officers, along
with aviation, engineering and military police units. Not since the
Korean War has a guard division been put in charge of an overseas
operation. And never before has one commanded regular Army combat
units.
</P>
<P>
   The 49th's deployment represents the culmination of a trend that
is transforming the nation's military, while roiling cities and
towns across America, with consequences that the Pentagon has only
now begun to assess.
</P>
<P>
   De La Rosa, 42, a staff sergeant in the 49th's aviation brigade,
has had his life turned upside down. He has served on active or
reserve duty since 1979, the last six years in the Texas Guard,
without ever having been mobilized. He joined because military
service is a family tradition. His father served in the 49th and
was once mobilized during the Berlin crisis of 1961. His brother
was killed in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   He is eager to serve _ ``I'll go wherever they need me,'' he
said _ but the deployment means leaving behind his elderly parents
and his small law office on San Antonio Street. He is the only
lawyer in his practice but hopes to keep it running, relying on his
office manager and wife, Olga, to hold on to clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping we'll be able to pay the bills,'' De La Rosa said.
``Then at least when I get back, I'll still have my business.''
</P>
<P>
   With overseas military operations proliferating and the armed
services having shrunk by a third since the Cold War, the Pentagon
has been forced to rely more heavily on the 870,000 men and women
in the Guard and Reserves to ease the strain. In the Army today,
guard and reserve soldiers actually outnumber those in the regular
force, 564,000 to 479,000.
</P>
<P>
   Once a place to go to avoid being sent to Vietnam or, more
recently, to earn some extra cash or sometimes college tuition, the
Guard and Reserves have become essential to U.S. military
operations from the Persian Gulf to Kosovo to East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   As the 49th's members have learned, anyone who joins the Guard
or Reserves today is more likely than ever to be called up,
especially in critical units like medical, police and civil
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, reservists spent less than 1 million days on
active duty supporting military operations; last year they spent
nearly 13 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't a one-time reliance or a short-term fix,''
Secretary of Defense William Cohen said in an interview. ``We
simply could not undertake a sustained operation anywhere in the
world without the Guard and Reserves.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, in the first four years of the Bosnian operation, more
Army reservists have been activated than during the entire Vietnam
War, though never in a single group as large as the 49th's. At
Incirlik Air Base in Turkey, a third of the pilots and crew members
patrolling the ``no flight'' zone over northern Iraq have belonged
to the Air Guard or Air Force Reserves. Guard and reserve F-16
pilots have bombed Iraqi targets.
</P>
<P>
   And there is no end in sight. A recent Pentagon study predicted
the demand for guard and reserve deployments ``is likely to remain
high over the next 15 to 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Army has nearly a half-million regular troops, its
commanders argue that the length of the U.S. involvement in Bosnia
has strained regular divisions in Germany and at home, leaving them
unready for their wartime missions. In addition to the 49th, guard
units from Virginia and Pennsylvania have been designated for
rotations in Bosnia into 2003. Some 1,200 reservists have already
served in Kosovo and more are expected to go. The Army is also
considering a plan to send reservists to relieve the 800 soldiers
serving in the international observer force on the Sinai Peninsula,
which has monitored the peace between Egypt and Israel since 1982.
</P>
<P>
   The increased reliance on the reservists, however, has come at a
cost.
</P>
<P>
   It has meant more money for training, equipment and pay. The
49th's deployment to Bosnia alone will cost an estimated $35
million. Citing the Army's dependency on them, Cohen last month
postponed a planned reduction of 25,000 guard and reserve
positions, a 4 percent cut that would have saved $900 million over
the next five years, according to Army officials.
</P>
<P>
   The greater demand has also raised questions about whether
part-time units are ready to take on missions important to the
nation's security. And it has tested the Pentagon's desire to
better integrate active-duty and reserve units, particularly in the
Army, where internecine rivalries of the past still simmer.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the biggest impact _ and the one that most worries
Pentagon officials _ is here at home.
</P>
<P>
   Deployments have forced the nation's so-called weekend warriors
to juggle their civilian lives and military service. While
reservists are used to being away for two weeks of drilling a year,
longer tours mean disrupting families and putting careers or
college on hold.
</P>
<P>
   Spc. Meghan A. Wood, an administrative clerk in the public
affairs office of the 49th, joined the Guard in 1998 to earn
tuition for the University of Texas. She was about to enter her
senior year last fall; her degree will now have to wait.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. John R. Fitzgerald, an intelligence officer, is going to
Bosnia as a newlywed. He and his wife, Naima Mery, first planned to
marry in November, but he had to go to a three-week mission
rehearsal exercise at Fort Polk, La. So they squeezed in a ceremony
at the St. Louis Catholic Church here last week, with no time left
for a proper honeymoon.
</P>
<P>
   Staff Sgt. Mary E. Manley, who works for MCI-Worldcom's office
in Richardson, Texas, is going to miss a wedding altogether: her
25-year-old daughter's.
</P>
<P>
   ``She promised to videotape the wedding and send it to me,'' Ms.
Manley said as she completed a last round of training at nearby
Fort Hood. She paused wistfully, then added, ``She'd better.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Deployments have also forced employers large and small to
scramble to fill vacancies created when reservists leave, often at
a cost. By law, an employer cannot dismiss someone called to active
duty, but many reservists face subtle and not-so-subtle
retribution, as well as lost wages and missed opportunities for
promotions. Last year, the Department of Labor investigated 1,029
complaints against employers accused of violating the law; many
more are mediated locally, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really nothing in it for the employer except losing
me,'' said Brig. Gen. Michael H. Taylor, deputy commander of the
49th _ and the vice president for human resources with the Memorial
Health System of East Texas, a small chain of hospitals based in
Lufkin.
</P>
<P>
   Many employers are supportive of their workers called to active
duty. Some even supplement their pay, though they are not required
to do so. But conflicts over jobs are the leading reason reservists
quit, according to Pentagon surveys, followed by separation from
their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``The repercussions are more severe than people think,'' said
Jerry Mendez, a major in the 49th who is an insurance manager in
San Antonio. ``People are going to have to choose'' between
military service and family. ``Guess what they're going to chose.
That's why the Guard is losing quality people.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While officials insist there is not yet enough evidence to
establish a trend, there are signs that the increased use of guard
and reserve units has begun to hurt recruiting and retention. In
recent years, the Army and Air National Guards and the reserves for
the Army, Navy, Air Force and Marine Corps have all faced
difficulties signing up enough new recruits.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. Thomas J. Plewes, chief of the Army Reserve, said that
active-duty soldiers, the biggest source of reserve recruits, have
shown a declining propensity to join the Guard or Reserves after
they retire, at least in part because of the increased deployments.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Guard and Reserves fell more than 12 percent
short of their enlistment goals, leaving every reserve force except
the Army National Guard short of its authorized strength. While the
regular services have also had recruiting difficulties, the
reserves appear hardest hit by the increasing tempo of deployments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may well be that the increased use of the Guard and
Reserves in the post-Cold War world has made it harder to attract
people,'' Charles L. Cragin, the assistant secretary of defense for
reserve affairs, warned the Defense Science Board last year.
</P>
<P>
   For the Army, for the Pentagon, for communities across the
nation, the 49th's deployment has become a major test. A review of
the division's deployment to Bosnia over the next nine months will
show how well the Guard and Reserves are adapting to their new role
and whether the strains on families and employers put that new role
in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   As the Pentagon prepares for its next strategic review, in 2001,
which will shape the military well into the new century, the
results are likely to affect all the services and their budgets, as
well as popular support for the nation's involvement in missions
like those in Bosnia and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   For the members of the 49th, which has its headquarters at Camp
Mabry here in Austin, the impact is felt closer to home. What has
happened in small ways as smaller guard and reserve units are sent
overseas is happening in larger ways in cities and towns across
Texas, from Dallas to San Antonio and De Kalb to Weslaco.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with nearly nine months away, the 49th's soldiers and
officers are scrambling to put their civilian lives in order,
making arrangements for their children, moving out of homes and
offices, wondering what will have changed when they get home in
October or November.
</P>
<P>
   They are a cross-section of life in Texas, which is why the
effects of their deployment will ripple across the state. Lt.
Christopher C. Ryan is a city prosecutor in Austin. Sgt. John P.
Casto is a customer service manager at Kroger's grocery store in
Houston. Staff Sgt. Bruce A. Devore works for the Central Texas
blood bank.
</P>
<P>
   Like De La Rosa, many came from families with military
backgrounds; the 49th is taking three sets of fathers and sons, a
married couple and twin brothers. Others previously served on
active duty and wanted to continue serving, although as
part-timers.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those going see the mission as an opportunity to put
into practice what they have learned in years of training. Many of
the 49th's 15,000 members volunteered.
</P>
<P>
   Teafatiller, the rancher, is a master sergeant in a supply unit.
He was drafted into the Army in 1963 and served in Korea. Now, at
60, he is eager to go overseas again, even though it meant selling
the 50 head of cattle he kept at his ranch in De Kalb, in northeast
Texas. Having held on to his two Angus bulls, he says he can ``go
back to messing with cattle again'' when he returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe anyone who lives in this country owes it
something,'' he said. ``And every person doesn't get a chance to
pay it back.''
</P>
<P>
   The first word they were going to Bosnia came in October 1998.
The Army wanted to give the 49th enough time to prepare, as a unit
and individually, even though it is regarded as one of the most
combat-ready guard units in the country.
</P>
<P>
   By law, the president can only activate reservists for a maximum
of 270 days, but for most members of the division, their
mobilization orders do not actually take effect until Feb. 7.
</P>
<P>
   And yet for the last year, the 49th's soldiers have spent 108
days drilling for the operation. For officers, the training,
including supervising a mock election at Camp Mabry this month to
prepare for Bosnia's municipal balloting in April, has consumed as
many as 150 days, far more than the 39 days a year they signed up
for.
</P>
<P>
   The training was necessary to prepare for a mission as complex
as this one, the division's commanders said, but the schedule has
bent the time-limits set by Congress in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law says you can only serve for 270 days, but we couldn't
perform this mission if we didn't break that mold,'' said Col.
Garry D. Patterson, the division's chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   Until last fall, the 49th was scheduled to send more than 1,200
soldiers, but as NATO reduced the size of the peacekeeping force in
Bosnia to 20,000 troops, including 3,900 Americans, from 30,000,
the division has been able to reduce its contingent to about 700,
most of whom will work at the U.S. headquarters in Bosnia near
Tuzla.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the reductions, the division commander, Brig. Gen.
Robert L. Halverson, has had some flexibility in selecting those
who will go. As the deployment neared, he was flooded with appeals
from members who had conflicts with jobs or families. Ultimately,
he let 35 people transfer to other parts of the 49th in order to
stay behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not out to ruin somebody's marriage, school, job,'' said
Halverson, who retired as deputy insurance commissioner for the
state of Texas when the deployment orders came.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I told a soldier, `I don't care about your marriage. I
don't care about your civilian job. You're going with me,' he might
go with me and come back,'' he said. ``But he wouldn't stay.''
</P>
<P>
   (STORY CAN ALSO END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Mark A. Brinkman, the president of Brinkman Technologies Inc., a
software company in Carrollton, a suburb of Dallas, wrote to
Halverson last month pleading that one of his vice presidents,
Craig D. Yarbrough, be excused.
</P>
<P>
   Yarbrough, a lieutenant, oversees computer and online banking
projects for the company, which has only 23 employees. He is going
to Bosnia to be the 49th's contracts officer just as the software
company markets new products and spins off a publicly traded
company. ``This has come at the worst possible time in my civilian
career,'' Yarbrough said
</P>
<P>
   Halverson considered, but rejected Brinkman's appeal. ``Craig is
invaluable,'' Brinkman said. ``The general wrote that those same
qualities that Craig has were the reasons why the Army needed him
for this mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more difficult, for some, has been the disruption to their
personal lives, especially their families.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Deanne E. Lins, 39, is going to be an aviation supervisor
in the 49th's headquarters. Her husband, J. Anthony, is also a
major in the Guard and works full-time for the 49th's aviation
brigade. Parts of his unit were also called up for Bosnia, but
knowing his wife was already going, his commanders let him stay
behind.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lins, a Blackhawk helicopter pilot, worked as a systems
engineer for Texas Instruments until her son, Matthew, was born
five years ago. Being in the Guard left her more time to be with
him and her daughter, Megan, 13. Matthew has not yet absorbed the
significance of her impending departure. On the other hand, it has
drawn Megan closer to her.
</P>
<P>
   Only a couple weeks before she leaves, she worries that she will
miss a critical time in her daughter's development. She worries
about how her son will adjust. She worries that her absence will
upset the family's routines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pay all the bills,'' Ms. Lins said, sitting in the living
room of their home on the northern edge of Austin. ``He doesn't
even have to look at the checkbook.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry,'' her husband interjected. ``I'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lins, who joined the National Guard in 1981, strongly
supports the idea of serving, but she believes the increased use of
the Guard and Reserves will have an impact on soldiers and families
like hers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to make people think a lot more carefully,'' she
said, ``about why they join.''
</P>
</TEXT>
