<HEADER>
A4138 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-MEDICAL-MISTAKES-2TAK     01-23 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAL-MISTAKES-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. HEALTH OFFICIALS REJECT PLAN TO REPORT MEDICAL MISTAKES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Conn)  (rk) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal health officials say they are unwilling at
this time to embrace the National Academy of Sciences' recent call
for a new federal law requiring hospitals to report all mistakes
that cause serious injury or death to patients.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal came from the academy's Institute of Medicine,
which also recommended that the information on medical errors be
made available to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Some federal health officials said the proposal for mandatory
public reporting could have unintended consequences and might
elicit less information than a well-designed, well-run system of
voluntary reporting. So far, federal health officials said, they
have been unable to agree on the right mix of mandatory and
voluntary reporting.
</P>
<P>
   But members of Congress are nonetheless moving ahead with plans
to require some new form of reporting, which could resemble the
comprehensive system used by airlines and federal agencies to
report aviation accidents and safety hazards.
</P>
<P>
   In its report, issued in late November, the Institute of
Medicine said that medical errors caused 44,000 to 98,000 deaths a
year _ more than the number resulting from auto accidents, cancer
or AIDS, and far more than the numbers killed or injured in plane
crashes each year.
</P>
<P>
   When the academy presented its report to President Clinton on
Dec. 7, he instructed federal health officials to evaluate the
proposals and report back by Feb. 5. Clinton seemed to favor
mandatory reporting of serious errors, as recommended by the
academy. But doctors and hospitals fear that such reports could
expose them to more lawsuits, liability and damages.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John M. Eisenberg, who is leading the administration's
review of the proposals, said, ``We are generally enthusiastic
about the framework of the Institute of Medicine report.'' But he
said officials were not prepared to endorse mandatory reporting of
serious medical errors at this time.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Eisenberg, who is also director of the Agency
for Health Care Research and Quality, said: ``The evidence and
experience with reporting systems is scattered and pretty
rudimentary. We want to know more about how mandatory reporting has
worked in states where it has been tried. What does mandatory
reporting get you that voluntary reporting does not? What are the
costs of each?''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James P. Bagian, director of the National Center for Patient
Safety at the Department of Veterans Affairs, said he and other
officials shared the academy's desire to reduce errors, but had
reservations about enacting a federal law to require reporting and
allow disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   ``There needs to be some level of national reporting, so we can
learn from our mistakes,'' Bagian said. ``But to allow disclosure
of hospital names and practitioners' names would be
counterproductive. It could inhibit reporting and drive the
problems further underground.''
</P>
<P>
   Safety experts have long known that medical errors were a major
cause of death and suffering. But the academy's report shined new
light on the problem and ignited public interest in the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Within the next few weeks, Clinton and other officials plan to
announce initiatives to enhance patient safety.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Dr. Sue Bailey, assistant secretary of defense
for health affairs, said she would soon instruct military hospitals
across the country to report medical errors, but she said the
reports would be confidential. One of her deputies, Dr. John F.
Mazzuchi, said the Pentagon would require reporting only of certain
types of errors, where it saw a potential problem or a significant
opportunity to improve the quality of care.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the administration's plans exceed anything recommended
by the National Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bailey said she intended to reduce the working hours of
interns and residents at military hospitals. These doctors, like
trainees at private civilian hospitals, often work 36-hour shifts
and 100-hour weeks, Dr. Bailey said. She said the Defense
Department should follow the example of New York state, which for
the last decade has had rules limiting most interns and residents
to 24-hour shifts and 80-hour weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., said, ``The Institute of
Medicine report pushed an alarm button, and we are responding to it
as quickly as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman is leading a bipartisan group of six senators drafting
legislation to reduce errors in Medicare, Medicaid and health care
programs for military personnel, veterans and civilian federal
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Federal health programs cover 90 million people and account for
more than 40 percent of health care spending in the United States.
But the sweep of the legislation would be much broader. The
senators are considering a proposal that would require hospitals to
report errors as a condition of participating in Medicare and
Medicaid. That would affect nearly all hospitals in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Lieberman said, ``We've got to make it
mandatory, but we should also protect confidentiality so hospitals
don't have to fear a lawsuit every time they report a preventable
error.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Federal health officials advising Clinton said they had agreed
on these points:
</P>
<P>
   _ When a hospital investigates its own errors to improve the
quality of care, it should, as a rule, not have to disclose the
results of its internal deliberations or its analysis of the
causes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Whenever possible, doctors should use computers to order drugs
from hospital pharmacies, to avoid the misinterpretation of
handwritten prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Food and Drug Administration should step up its efforts to
prevent medication errors involving drugs with names that look
alike or sound alike.
</P>
<P>
   _ The government should develop a standard format, definitions
and terminology for reporting medical errors.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Donald M. Berwick, a member of the National Academy of
Sciences panel, said federal officials were justified in worrying
about the possibility that the disclosure of injuries might
discourage reporting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not clear how much mandatory reporting will help patient
safety, but it will address deep public concern about whether the
health care system is open and honest and accountable,'' said
Berwick, who is president of the Institute for Health Care
Improvement, a nonprofit research and education group in Boston.
``Suppose an airline could crash a plane and not tell anybody about
it. That would be wrong. Likewise, if people are seriously injured
because of errors in medical care, don't they or their families
have a right to know?''
</P>
<P>
   The patient safety program of the Department of Veterans Affairs
is often described as a model for the nation. The department
requires its hospitals to report mistakes to the agency's regional
offices, which in turn send the information to Washington. Veterans
hospitals must try to identify the causes of each incident, to
reduce the likelihood of a repetition. But the reports are not
generally made public.
</P>
<P>
   Bagian said it might be premature to require the nation's 5,000
community hospitals to follow the procedures of veterans hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The community hospitals operate in a competitive environment
where public embarrassment can have business implications,'' Bagian
said. ``If you're not careful here, legislation could have a
chilling effect on people's willingness and ability to report
errors.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., said that federal
laws requiring colleges to disclose campus crime statistics had
stimulated them to take precautions to prevent crime. He suggested
that a reporting requirement for hospitals could have similar
beneficial effects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
