<DOCNO> NYT20000123.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-23 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4140 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-WEB-DRUGSAFETY24-COX     01-23 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-DRUGSAFETY24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Regulators try to find way to ensure drug safety
 &HT;    By Irwin Spivak
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ ``Spend 25$ _ get $25$ credit! Online
Pharmacy _ no prescription needed! Foreign pharmacy will give
discounts up to 75% for non-FDA approved drugs!''
</P>
<P>
   So go the pitches made by some Internet pharmacies. Others
tantalize consumers with promises of 30 percent to 50 percent
discounts.
</P>
<P>
   Come-ons like these are hard to ignore if you are one of the 44
million uninsured Americans or among the 75 percent of seniors on
Medicare who lack prescription drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers indeed might find some of the best prices by buying
prescription medicines over the Internet. But an informal survey
suggests the savings are generally modest and may vanish when
shipping charges are included.
</P>
<P>
   Prescription drug shoppers may be able to match the best Web
prices by going to Publix or Costco, according to The Palm Beach
Post's survey of five local and five Internet pharmacies.
</P>
<P>
   Pricing is an issue because corner drugstores are increasingly
being replaced with a click onto the Internet, where one can find
hundreds of Web sites selling prescription drugs and other health
products.
</P>
<P>
   Some 200 Web sites dispense drugs but don't prescribe them,
according to the National Association of Boards of Pharmacy. The
association estimates that a far greater number of online
pharmacies provide prescriptions through ``patient questionnaires
and cyberspace consultations.''
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, online drug shopping can save money. A survey
last fall by Consumer Reports showed that buyers could save as much
as 29% by purchasing certain drugs online. But another 1999 study _
conducted by the University of Pennsylvania and published in the
Annals of Internal Medicine _ found that Viagra and Propecia cost
an average of 10 percent more online than at Philadelphia-area
pharmacies.
</P>
<P>
   SENIORS BIGGEST MARKET
</P>
<P>
   The elderly, who make up 12 percent of the U.S. population,
frequently have little or no insurance coverage for prescription
drugs. At the same time, they're the biggest users of such drugs:
The National Association of Chain Drug Stores reports that the
typical 65-year-old takes nine different prescription medicines a
year at an average of about $38 per bottle. Refilling all nine
prescriptions once a month would cost more than $4,000 over a year.
But experts urge consumers to use caution online.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should use the same kind of common sense you use when
buying from any business,'' said Dr. Jeffrey Shuren, a medical
officer at the U.S. Food and Drug Administration. ``You look for a
reputable dealer. You get recommendations from a friend. You check
the place out.''
</P>
<P>
   Online sales are booming because the Internet makes drugs easily
available for those who live far from the local pharmacy and makes
it easier to comparison shop. Some sites also offer a greater
variety of products, and consumers can order products and consult
with a pharmacist in the privacy of their homes.
</P>
<P>
   HOLES IN SAFETY NET
</P>
<P>
   Sales of drugs via the Web, however, make it easy to bypass the
FDA guidelines that protect consumers from harmful or ineffective
drugs as well as improper prescribing or dispensing. The FDA is
concerned about improper storage and shipping _ particularly of
drugs from overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Drugs offered by foreign Web sites are more likely to raise
safety concerns about contamination or subpotent strengths,
according to the FDA. The majority of drugs ordered from foreign
Web sites are coming in from Thailand, China, Mexico and
Switzerland, reports the U.S. Customs Service.
</P>
<P>
   Customs officials said they seized 9,725 packages of
prescription drugs ordered over the Internet last year because they
had not been approved for use in this country, did not comply with
American labeling requirements or fell below U.S. standards for
quality and purity. They also impounded almost 2 million pills and
tablets because they did not meet FDA guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet has given us a lot more work,'' reported Raymond
W. Kelly, commissioner of the customs service, on the agency's Web
site. ``We've been deluged with prescription drugs coming in from
overseas.''
</P>
<P>
   Buyers, however, rarely are prosecuted. Consumers can find
licensed pharmacies that comply with laws through a new service set
up by the National Association of Boards of Pharmacy. The VIPPS
program, or Verified Internet Pharmacy Practice Sites, was created
to protect consumers by ensuring patients have privacy, secure
orders and the option to consult with pharmacists.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmacies that volunteer for the program and meet its criteria
can display the VIPPS hyperlink seal on their Web site. By clicking
on the seal, consumers are linked to the association's site _
www.nabp.net _ and can verify that the pharmacy qualified for the
program. Consumers also can check the association's Web site for an
Internet pharmacy.
</P>
<P>
   PHYSICIAN'S INPUT NEEDED
</P>
<P>
   For Internet pharmacies to work properly, the patient's
physician should be involved in requesting the drug, said Jeff
Trewitt, spokesman for the Pharmaceutical Research and
Manufacturers of America. Patients who buy drugs online without
their doctor's knowledge might receive inappropriate drugs or
suffer side effects _ particularly if they don't tell the Internet
pharmacist about other drugs that they're taking.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Zelman _ president of SaveWell, one of the newer online
pharmacies _ said people need to be smart shoppers. Some walk-in
pharmacies such as Publix and Costco may be able to match online
prices because they want to bring in customers who will buy other
products, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping electronically offers convenience, but consumers should
beware of ``rogue'' sites that use unapproved, imported drugs or
dispense drugs without prescriptions, Zelman said.
</P>
<P>
   States and the federal government are grappling with how to
police online pharmacies at a time drug sales are soaring. Last
year, pharmacists from walk-ins and the Web combined to fill nearly
2.8 billion prescriptions, according to the Consumer Reports Web
site. That figure is expected to jump to about 4 billion by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Florida has set up a task force to study the growing number of
questions arising about Internet drug sales.
</P>
<P>
   And last month, Michigan's Attorney General threatened to sue 10
online pharmacies because Michigan bars prescribing drugs without
having an in-person physical. President Clinton's administration
has proposed strengthening the penalties for selling drugs
illegally and giving the FDA more authority to investigate online
pharmacies. It also has recommended investing $10 million in a
``rapid-response team'' and FDA computer technology to identify,
investigate and prosecute illegal Internet pharmacies.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
