u s BC-FBN-JETS-GROH-BOS &LR;      01-23 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-GROH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS EXPECTED TO NAME GROH HEAD COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Jets will name Al Groh their coach Monday and will
also announce that former coach Bill Parcells will remain in an
advisory capacity for the immediate future.
</P>
<P>
   Groh, who has coached under Parcells for more than 15 years, was
linebackers coach of the Jets the past three years and defensive
coordinator with the Patriots when they went to the Super Bowl
under Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   Groh was the personal choice of Parcells after Bill Belichick
resigned from the position less than 48 hours after becoming coach
Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick, by a contractual arrangement he had with late Jets
owner Leon Hess, moved into place as head man when Parcells retired
following the final game of the regular season against Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   However, two days later, Belichick resigned and subsequently
filed a grievance with National Football League commissioner Paul
Taglaibue trying to free himself from the Jets to accept an offer
as coach and general manager of the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Tagliabue ruled against Belichick, saying he had a
contract for the next three years with the Jets and he could not
coach in the league during that time unless allowed to do so by the
Jets.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots offered New York two draft choices, neither in the
top two rounds, to pry Belichick loose, but the Jets rejected the
deal. Reportedly they still are looking for a first-round and a
middle-round pick as compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells and new Jets owner Robert Wood Johnson IV met with Groh
over the weekend, the first time Johnson had met Groh. But after
the meeting, Johnson decided to go along with the strong
recommendation by Parcells, who considered Groh the best available
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   There was no movement on the Belichick issue over the weekend,
which is fueling speculation that the Patriots are losing interest
in Belichick and turning their attention toward University of Miami
coach Butch Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has said in the last couple of weeks that he wants to stay
at Miami. There also have been reports Davis might be the next
coach in Dallas, where he served on Jimmy Johnson's staff when the
Cowboys won two Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Romeo Crennel, longtime defensive line coach with the Giants,
Patriots, and Jets under Parcells, left over the weekend to become
defensive coordinator with Chris Palmer in Cleveland, leaving New
York depleted on the defensive side of its staff.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Belichick was the coordinator, Groh the linebackers
coach, and Crennel the line coach. The Jets' offensive staff is
expected to stay intact, with the possible exception of coordinator
Charley Weis, who testified on behalf of Belichick in the grievance
hearing and is very close to Belichick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-00 2126EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
