<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS SEEK ALTERNATES TO BELICHICK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There were no talks over the weekend between the
Patriots and Jets regarding compensation to free Bill Belichick
from his contract with New York, so New England began to formulate
an alternative regarding its coaching situation.
</P>
<P>
   With Jacksonville being knocked out of the playoffs Sunday, the
Patriots have asked for permission to speak to Jaguars defensive
coordinator Dom Capers about their coaching job. And New England
will interview former Pittsburgh director of football operations
Tom Donahoe for the general manager's job Tuesday in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Capers-Donahoe likely would come as a team, having worked
together for three years in Pittsburgh (1992-95) when Capers was
defensive coordinator under Bill Cowher and Donahoe was director of
football operations, a position he held until he was fired at the
end of the season, losing a power struggle with Cowher.
</P>
<P>
   Donahoe has been highly sought after. He could take the GM job
in Miami and work with another friend, Dave Wannstedt. But Donahoe
is attempting to see if he and Capers would be attractive to teams
looking for a coach-GM tandem. Another team that might be
interested would be New Orleans. Dallas also has a coaching
vacancy, but is reportedly looking for someone more offense-minded.
</P>
<P>
   By talking with Capers and Donahoe, the Patriots may be sending
a message to the Jets that they could get nothing for Belichick if
they don't play ball.
</P>
<P>
   Capers's Jacksonville defense didn't have the best of games in a
33-14 loss to Tennessee in Sunday's AFC Championship Game. But
Capers is known for being tough and instilling discipline, and he
has experience leading a team into the playoffs. His resume is
similar to Belichick's in that regard.
</P>
<P>
   Capers was 31-35 from 1995-98 in Carolina, but was fired after
going 4-12 and replaced by George Seifert. He landed as Tom
Coughlin's defensive coordinator in Jacksonville and did a good job
upgrading an already decent defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets have scheduled a news conference for Monday to announce
they've signed Al Groh to a five-year deal to be their new coach.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have the 16th pick in the first round this year and
are trying to hold on to it, believing there's a chance they could
get a top offensive lineman or Wisconsin running back Ron Dayne.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have distanced themselves from former Kansas City
coach Marty Schottenheimer, who also would require compensation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
