<HEADLINE>
COMPTROLLER CAREFULLY LAYING FOUNDATION FOR GOVERNOR'S RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ H. Carl McCall has a reputation as a most
cautious politician. So as he contemplates the most incautious of
acts, challenging a popular incumbent governor, he is going about
it in the most cautious way _ starting almost three years before
the election.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two weeks, McCall, the state comptroller, has laid
the groundwork for a run for governor in 2002 with a seriousness
that has impressed even those who question his nerve. He has
established a campaign committee, opened a Web site and begun a
concerted, very early attempt to lock up the support of all the
Democrats who matter and head off any potential primary challenger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going through a process of assessing a candidacy, and to
date the indications are very, very positive,'' McCall, a Democrat,
said on Friday in his first interview on the subject. He said he
needed to begin now to raise the $15 million to $20 million he
estimates he will need for the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent to hundreds of elected officials and other
prominent Democrats over the weekend, McCall's committee said,
``While he will not make an announcement until later this year,
Carl has begun making plans to run for governor in 2002.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic elected officials and strategists say that McCall's
jump on the race is aimed at positioning him to take on not only
Gov. George E. Pataki, the Republican incumbent who has hinted that
he will seek a third term, but also a fellow Democrat, Andrew M.
Cuomo, the secretary of Housing and Urban Development and son of
former Gov. Mario M. Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Cuomo says he may run for governor, though he could have
a prominent role in the White House if his friend, Vice President
Al Gore, wins the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   McCall conceded that one reason for starting so early is ``to
develop the kind of support so that there's the possibility of
avoiding a primary,'' though he insisted that he had no particular
opponent in mind.
</P>
<P>
   As for whether he expects Pataki or Cuomo to run, he said: ``I
have no idea. My efforts and my final decision will have nothing to
do with any other candidate in a primary or in a general
election.''
</P>
<P>
   One Democrat who has been talked about as a potential candidate,
Attorney General Eliot L. Spitzer, took himself out of the running
in an interview on Friday by endorsing McCall. ``I will be 100
percent behind his effort to get the nomination and to get
elected,'' Spitzer said. ``I think Carl is the best candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Between now and the 2002 election, there will be contests for
the U.S. Senate, for president and for mayor of New York City, yet
the talk among the state's Democratic political strategists is of
the race for governor, and in particular, of a McCall-Cuomo
primary.
</P>
<P>
   The contest offers enough rich story lines to fill a gothic
novel. McCall, the first black person elected to statewide office
in New York and the state's first serious black candidate for
governor, would be expected to energize the black vote and draw
money from black contributors around the country. Cuomo would be
seen as seeking to avenge himself against Pataki, who defeated his
father in 1994. And there is history aplenty: Mario Cuomo wanted
McCall as his running mate in 1982, but McCall lost the primary for
lieutenant governor to Alfred B. Del Bello.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A sure sign of Cuomo's interest came on Friday, when a reporter
received a number of unsolicited calls from people close to him _ a
Cuomo aide, a political consultant and a few politicians _ saying
that they had heard the reporter was working on an article about
McCall and the 2002 race, and offering to weigh in.
</P>
<P>
   One caller, Mayor Gerald D. Jennings of Albany, said he had
heard about the article ``from some people in Washington,'' and
added that while he had not endorsed anyone, ``there are a lot of
positives that Andrew has.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Cuomo himself said: ``I think we should focus
on the foreseeable future. We have two very important goals. One is
to elect the next president of the United States and the other is
to elect the next senator from New York. That should be the focus
of the Democratic Party. There's plenty of time for the governor's
race. This is a very early start for a political contest that's
basically three years away.''
</P>
<P>
   Though polls show Cuomo faring better than McCall in
hypothetical matchups against Pataki, most Democratic strategists
interviewed said they thought McCall, assuming he raised enough
money, would defeat Cuomo in a primary, mostly because of heavy
support from black and Hispanic voters. Political analysts say that
based on the experience of black candidates in other states, race
could hurt McCall in a general election, though how much is
anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCall's intentions right now are to close everybody else in
the party out, to line up support early and line up money early,''
said Hank Sheinkopf, a Democratic political consultant who does not
have strong ties to either McCall or Cuomo. ``The specter of Andrew
Cuomo will always be looking over his shoulder, but I would expect
him to beat Cuomo. McCall should certainly be competitive against
Pataki, too.''
</P>
<P>
   For McCall, the challenge now is to persuade Democrats that he
is serious about this race, and that he will make the kind of
all-out effort that a statewide campaign demands _ and that he is
not known for. All this at an age, 64, when most people are
thinking about retirement, though he looks and seems a decade
younger. (Cuomo is 42, and his supporters make it clear that if he
ran, they would make his youth and energy an issue.)
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have grumbled for years that McCall was too unwilling
to attack Pataki. Black politicians complained that he did not
identify with the issues of concern to their community _ it was
only after considerable lobbying that he joined hundreds of others
in being arrested in protests after the police shooting of Amadou
Diallo last year.
</P>
<P>
   But the most damning and frequent criticism of McCall is that he
does not have the fire needed for a real contest. After months
spent publicly weighing a run against Pataki in 1998, he declined.
He passed up the chance to run for the Senate this year, before
Hillary Rodham Clinton's name had been floated, even after Sen.
Daniel Patrick Moynihan said that McCall would be his preferred
successor.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '98, I had only served one term, George Pataki had $20
million, the economy was good and he was very strong,'' McCall
said. As for the Senate race, he said: ``I've devoted my energy to
New York state, to executive positions. The Senate wasn't some
place I wanted to go, start from the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   McCall certainly has the kind of resume that makes for an
attractive candidate: son of a single welfare mother graduates from
Dartmouth and becomes a high school teacher and an ordained
minister in the United Church of Christ, is elected to the state
Senate from Manhattan, is appointed U.S.ambassador to the United
Nations, serves as a vice president of Citicorp, and becomes
president of the New York City Board of Education. His wife, Dr.
Joyce F. Brown, a former deputy mayor, is president of the Fashion
Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Chosen by the Legislature in 1993 to fill the vacant
comptroller's office, he won it in his own right in 1994 and 1998.
In that job, he has sole control of investments made by the $120
billion state pension fund, making him probably the single biggest
investor in the world and thus a prominent figure in the world of
high finance, where he has won generally high marks. In state
government, he has espoused prudence so often that Democrats chide
him that he sounds more like a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   McCall has had a diffident relationship with the assembly
speaker, Sheldon Silver, who is closer to Cuomo, but most
strategists do not think that would pose a real threat if McCall
proved to be a serious candidate. Silver's office declined to
comment for this article.
</P>
<P>
   For now, all signs are that McCall means to do what it will take
to mount a serious run for governor. He has a well-known antipathy
to fund-raising and has taken more than a year off from it. (He has
$72,000 in his campaign treasury, to more than $2 million for
Pataki.) But he has hired Shawn Thompson, a former fund-raiser for
the Assembly's Democratic majority, and has scheduled two
fund-raising events next month.
</P>
<P>
   He has gathered an impressive roster of backers, including
Spitzer; Rep. Charles B. Rangel; the Assembly majority leader,
Michael J. Bragman, a power in the Assembly and in central New
York; Assemblyman Roberto Ramirez, the Bronx Democratic chairman;
Assemblyman Herman D. Farrell Jr., the Manhattan chairman; and
Assemblyman Clarence Norman Jr., the Brooklyn chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there remains the nagging question: why would a cautious
politician leave a job in which he is courted by financiers from
every part of the world for an arduous and uncertain campaign?
McCall said, ``You just can't do the same thing forever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
