<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A COLD WIND BLOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BOB HERBERT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ We were in the middle of a brutal cold snap last
week, just like the winters of old, with temperatures diving into
the single digits and winds as sharp and merciless as a razor
slicing through the city's streets.
</P>
<P>
   In the hours before dawn on Wednesday the temperature in Central
Park was 11 degrees. For the police and the Department of Homeless
Services this was the perfect moment to inflict further torment on
that group that has become a favorite target of the Giuliani
regime, the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   And so, in coordinated raids in all five boroughs, the regime
struck. The homeless, some of them mentally ill, never had a
chance. There was no resistance. They awoke startled in their
temporary bunks and watched in absolute astonishment as cops swept
through several shelters and arrested 129 men and women who had
outstanding warrants for such dire offenses as _ get this _
relieving themselves in public, drinking beer in the open air,
trespassing.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said five or six of the miscreants who were
pulled from their beds, handcuffed, dragged into the bitter cold
and taken to jail had been wanted for felonies. As for the rest,
the other 123 or 124 _ well, who cares about them? A bunch of bums
and mental cases as far as the city is concerned. And if they're
reluctant after this harrowing experience to go into the shelters
again, choosing instead to remain in an alley or a park in the
life-threatening cold _ well, that's their call. The winter wind is
not the only thing that's merciless in this town.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Markee of the Coalition for the Homeless told me that 18
mentally ill homeless men were arrested at the Fort Washington
shelter in Upper Manhattan, which provides special services for the
mentally ill. Two of the men had not been heard from by the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of them is an older gentleman who suffers from major
depression and hypertension,'' said Markee. ``The staff is very
worried about what has happened to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Underlying the criticism of the raids was the stark fact that
two homeless men died last week as a result of the cold. One was
found dead in the back of a station wagon that he had crawled into
for shelter, and the other died near a loading dock on which he had
been living in the Sheepshead Bay section of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Brosnahan, the executive director of the coalition, said
the raids were part of a ``reign of terror'' against the homeless
in New York. ``They send a very strong message to the folks out in
the street who are trying to make a calculated decision on a bitter
night about whether to come in out of the cold. That message is: no
matter how small the infraction is that you may have in your past,
if you come into the shelters you are running a very severe risk of
being rounded up and hauled off to jail.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not a matter of concern to Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who
vigorously defended the raids. And his commissioner of homeless
services, Martin Oesterreich, told me on Friday that they will
continue because last week's sweep ``was very successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Oesterreich was not at all moved by complaints that the raids
took place on one of the coldest days of the year. ``It takes a
while to gin up these kinds of operations,'' he said. ``And then
they fall on a certain date and it doesn't matter whether it's a
driving rain or snowstorm or it's, you know, 2 degrees below zero.
That doesn't really concern us.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would take a look at the impact of the raids on the
mentally ill, however.
</P>
<P>
   The city had never before conducted a sweep of the shelters that
was as broad as last week's. ``The reason that it's never happened
before,'' said Oesterreich, ``is that I now have a director of
security who works very closely with the Police Department to
coordinate all of our security issues, including these warrant
sweeps. I just hired the guy two months ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Oesterreich said the homeless advocates were putting an entirely
incorrect spin on the sweeps. They should, he said, be happy about
last week's operation and the predawn raids to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not some way to deter people from coming into the
shelters,'' he said. ``It is to encourage people to come in by
making them the safer spots that the homeless have a right to
demand of us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
