<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ABORTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: BUSH SETS JAW AND COURSE, IF NOT VIEWS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ At no point in the last several months did
Gov. George W. Bush seem quite as rattled as he did at a news
conference on Thursday, when reporter after reporter challenged him
to elucidate his feelings about the Supreme Court and abortion.
</P>
<P>
   As the questions multiplied, pressing him ever harder to fill in
the blanks, his answers grew briefer, his lips narrower, his jaw
tenser. He clearly wanted to talk about something _ anything _
else.
</P>
<P>
   That was also true on Saturday, when reporters tried to prod
Bush into discussing the abortion plank in the Republican Party's
platform. The Texas governor and his aides responded with a
concerted effort to change the topic to tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   And that should come as no surprise, because as Bush goes
through a Republican primary process in which his ultimate victory
seems almost foreordained, his greatest challenge is arguably not
the loftiness of the numbers he posts in the precinct caucuses here
on Monday or even his fate in New Hampshire, a state he could lose.
</P>
<P>
   It is to emerge from this obstacle course with a record of
statements and an overall image that can play in the general
election, which will likely be fought in the center of the
political spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Sunday that he is toeing a straight and steady line
and hewing to unwavering principles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing about me is I'm a candidate who has run
consistently throughout this primary,'' Bush told reporters here
Sunday morning. ``And I'll run the same kind of campaign in the
general election.''
</P>
<P>
   But in what Bush emphasizes and what he does not, what he
embraces and what he avoids, he seems to be exhibiting a fair
degree of caution about not picking up any ideological baggage that
will weigh him down come summer and fall.
</P>
<P>
   In Iowa, Republican rivals like Steve Forbes, Gary Bauer and
Alan Keyes, and some of their ideological allies, have made that
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Phyllis Schlafly arrived in the state to beat the conservative
drums for Forbes; Bauer went so far as to hold a prayer service
over the gravesite of an aborted fetus. And Forbes repeatedly
portrayed Bush as soft on abortion, leading reporters to grill Bush
on the topic and compelling Bush to make some strong statements
about his opposition to abortion that may well come back to haunt
him.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush has also been trying to signal to voters outside of
Iowa and New Hampshire what many political observers in Texas have
noted: he is not a politician who cares to spend his political
capital on highly divisive, emotional battles, nor is he fond of
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   In a television interview that he taped with CNN on Saturday, he
would not be roped into a firm statement about whether or not he
would consider a vice presidential candidate who supports legal
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Nor would Bush be lured into a negative analysis of Supreme
Court Justice David Souter, who turned out to be much more liberal
than Bush's father, who appointed him, perhaps expected him to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nice try,'' Bush said. ``I am not going into all of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush has held a news conference with reporters on the
campaign trail almost every day since the beginning of the year,
that ritual suddenly ended after Thursday's session, which was
intended to highlight an endorsement from a farmers' group but
turned into a tense back-and-forth about abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides explained that with the caucuses just days away,
Bush was simply too busy with events more closely related to
getting out the vote.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday, Mindy Tucker, a spokeswoman for the Bush campaign,
answered a question from several reporters about Bush's
availability this week by saying that a daily news conference is
``not in our best interests.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a message of the day and we're going to stick to it,''
Ms. Tucker said. ``We are not going to have one big, fat news
conference on our schedule where you can come and ask what you
think is the news of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, Karen P. Hughes, the communications director of
the campaign, said that Bush would continue to be available to
reporters, and she pointed out that he had done two extended
national television interviews.
</P>
<P>
   On the stump in Iowa, Bush has avoided the subject of abortion
entirely, instead talking about improving education for poor
children, ushering lower-income people into the middle class and
finding a ``purpose to our prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the specific proposals he is advocating will
accomplish any of this is open to debate, but what is unequivocal
is Bush's desire to cast himself as a more sensitive, moderate
Republican. And that is an effort that has less to do with handy
victories in caucuses and primaries and more to do with wooing
swing voters in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   For the purposes of winning Iowa, Bush did not need to have
three black children right behind him on a stage in Waterloo
Sunday. For the purposes of the general election, and for changing
the Republican Party in the ways he has said he wants to change it,
that kind of image could be crucial.
</P>
<P>
   There are positions that Bush has taken, whether out of genuine
conviction or political expedience, that may prove to be
liabilities down the line. He has said that it is up to South
Carolinians to resolve the debate over the Confederate flag at the
Statehouse, drawing fire from people who find the symbol racially
offensive.
</P>
<P>
   And the enormity of his proposed tax cut, which his aides
believe will play well with Republicans in New Hampshire, may be
seen as fiscally irresponsible by voters elsewhere and give the
Democrats ammunition against him.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush has one eye obviously on the general election when he
sells the plan by talking about how much it will help the less
prosperous, especially, to use his example, a single mother with
two children making $22,000 a year, and reflects that audiences may
be surprised to hear a Republican focusing on such a person.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that what's lacking in a lot of the rhetoric in the
course of the campaign on the Republican side is not talking about
the people that live on the outskirts of poverty,'' Bush explained
to reporters in New Hampshire earlier this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
