<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-23 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4152 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-IOWA-CAUCUS-ART-NYT &LR;      01-23 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-CAUCUS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATES IN FINAL EFFORT TO REACH IOWA VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Vice president Al Gore has representatives
from organized labor working the phones and stuffing envelopes.
Bill Bradley has turned to the Internet to try to reach voters.
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas tapped into his vast network of
friends and supporters. And Steve Forbes, the publisher, wants to
make sure everyone has a ride.
</P>
<P>
   At 7 p.m. on Monday night, registered voters will fill church
basements, meeting halls and school auditoriums to cast their vote
and argue about party platforms in one of the 2,142 caucus
precincts in the state.
</P>
<P>
   To get his supporters to the meetings, Bush is relying on
``captains'' in each precinct to help staff members work through an
elaborate phone tree of supporters and registered Republicans. The
captains supply the campaign with a list of friends and neighbors
to be contacted for the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``The captains ask voters who they plan to support, answer
questions on what to expect on caucus night and help explain the
process,'' said Eric Woolson, a spokesman for the Bush campaign.
``They're getting people on board.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president has the labor force. In addition to making
about 30,000 telephone calls, members of the Iowa Federation of
Labor are mailing letters to local union leaders on behalf of the
Gore campaign. Letters are then reproduced over the local leader's
signature for personalized mailings that will be sent to all
150,000 union households in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley has about 400 volunteers in the state, working the
precincts. Over 1000 precinct leaders are in place to urge voters
to go to the caucuses. According to the Bradley campaign, staffers
at phone banks have reached more than 150,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, who trails Bush in Iowa polls, has implemented a
Neighbor to Neighbor program that Jim Tobin, national policy
director for the Forbes campaign, called a ``ground game
organization'' to turn out voters for the caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   Each supporter recruits five people, who in turn reach out to
five others, and so on, thus spawning a web of support throughout
the state. And on caucus night, Tobin said, the campaign will do
``whatever it takes to get everyone to their precinct.'' Volunteers
will spread out across the state in their own cars, and staffers
will employ minivans ``to provide transportation for all of our
Iowa supporters,'' Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one will be left out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Good thing. The forecast for Monday: a low of 12 degrees and
snow.
</P>
</TEXT>
