<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-INTERTAINER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT INVESTS IN INTERACTIVE TELEVISION BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In another step toward extending its reach from
the personal computer to the television set, Microsoft Corp. will
invest $56 million in Intertainer Inc., a privately held company
that provides a video-on-demand service, Microsoft executives said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which was expected to be formally announced Monday,
would give Microsoft a stake of slightly more than 20 percent in
Intertainer, making it the largest single shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   The investment would allow Intertainer, which is based in Culver
City, Calif., to more quickly role out its service, which offers
pay-per-view movies, music, television programs and electronic
shopping to personal computers connected to cable modems,
high-speed digital telephone lines or television sets with digital
set-top boxes. The company has started offering its service
commercially in some cities, but has fewer than 1,000 subscribers
so far.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is trying to position itself as a leading software
provider for interactive television.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to make this whole marketplace come true,'' Jon
DeVaan, senior vice president for Microsoft's consumer group, said
Friday. The investment in Intertainer, he said, would give
Microsoft ``an innovative broadband service committed to using its
platform.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Microsoft also hopes to work with similar services.
Microsoft agreed in May to invest $5 billion in AT&AMP;T in exchange
for a promise that the company, which owns cable provider
Tele-Communications Inc., would use Microsoft software in 7.5
million to 10 million digital set-top cable boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also bought an 11 percent stake in Comcast Corp., a
cable company, several years ago and acquired Web TV, a company
that allows Web surfing using a television set.
</P>
<P>
   Intertainer was formed in 1996 by Jonathan Taplin and Richard
Baskin, veteran Hollywood executives. It has received smaller
investments from Comcast, the Intel Corp., NBC, and US West.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
