<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BRADLEY'S RESURGENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A couple of months ago, Al Gore was suffering the
tortures of the media-damned.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president was derided for running a Washington-based
campaign with a sclerotic staff. He was falling behind in fund
raising. He was seen by even his knee-jerk union supporters as the
Ultimate Stiff. He was overpaying media advisers to give him an
earth-tone transplant to turn him into an Alpha Male.
</P>
<P>
   At that nadir moment, a piece appeared in this space headed
``The Gore Comeback.'' Based on the pendulum theory of political
popularity, as well as on the media's needs for a spirited contest,
it laid out the likelihood of a roaring return of Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   See? The contrarian theory sometimes works. The loosened-up,
slashing debater, supposedly advised to press the flesh by his
daughter (a reliance on family advice that didn't help Boris
Yeltsin), is now the favorite to win in Monday's Iowa caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   As promised here back then, the moment has come to reveal the
blueprint for the ``Bradley resurgence.'' (The best advice for
lefties comes from righties, because we're not emotionally
involved.)
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley's media problem is that the bloom is off his
challenger's rose. A savage analysis in The Washington Post derides
his attempt to overcome in photo ops what had been criticized as
aloofness. He is pilloried as well for not running the gentle,
intellectual, sure-fire-loser's campaign he promised at the start.
On top of all that, his ticker's been kicking up.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's personal problem is that he has been much too
comfortable in his own skin. This internal easiness is not the
attribute it is cracked up to be. Rather than merely being himself,
Bradley must become Himself.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how: Stop complaining about Gore's exaggeration about the
cost of your big-idea proposals. The let's-not-go-negative pitch is
posited by goo-goos who don't vote. Instead, embrace the ``upbeat
negative'': attacking the other guy's cheap, weaselly, crackbrained
ideas is a necessary counterpoint to presenting your own.
</P>
<P>
   In going upbeat negative, don't dredge up ancient history about
Gore's first use of Willie Horton. In this week's debate, be
realistic about the great danger to Democrats in the fall campaign:
Gore's shameful record in abetting Clinton's 1996 political money
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   When a huge GOP ad campaign zaps fund-raisers by Gore at
Buddhist temples; when Gore's ``no controlling legal authority'' TV
clips become as familiar as the clip of Clinton's finger-wagging
lie; when new facts emerge about Clinton-Gore fund-raising
predations, Democrats in 2000 will suffer from ``Clinton-Gore
fatigue.''
</P>
<P>
   Your central point to Democrats: Gore Can't Win. Recount the
influence-peddling charges sure to come from Republicans as
stipulated in Orrin Hatch's recent damning speech. When all this
sleaze was going on, where was Al? Up to his hips in it. Where were
you? Miles away, earning an honest living.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been able to portray your revulsion at this kind of
contracts-and-China-policy and Lincoln-bedroom-for-sale as being a
``quitter.'' Don't let him get away with that twist: He's the one
who stayed and choked. Only a Democrat who is clean of the scandals
can win. That's you.
</P>
<P>
   Raise the dire outside possibility of a McCain candidacy:
Because he would have the independents, and Republicans would
``come home,'' McCain would clobber Gore and carry the House with
him. Only you, unencumbered by the baggage of the impeachment
trauma, could compete with McCain for the decisive swing vote. And
if the market bubble pops in October, the GOP can't blame you.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, be a real Democrat and promise the moon. Where's your
``I see an America where'' speech? Let's hear those ideals, boiled
down to a triple pledge: health insurance for all, the end of gun
violence, a new era of honest politics not dominated by fat cats.
</P>
<P>
   Use your big war chest now to create spots that take up that
simple, triple theme. Your low-key delivery can be at its most
effective if the words uplift. Contrast Gore's strident
niggardliness with your sincere generosity. And don't look guilty
about taking the good fight to the front-runner: It shows you're
able, as Gore was, to get up off the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Go to it, fellas. I'll hold your coats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
