<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-RELIGIOUS-RIGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS COURT CORE BLOC, IN AN EVENING WITH SOCIAL
CONSERVATIVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ The pale, slight 14-year-old in a severe
black suit stood before a crowd of more than 1,000 at the Family,
Faith and Freedom rally on Saturday night while her mother gave a
graphic account of how, ``under the influence of pornographic
videos,'' the girl's father had sexually abused her ``on her very
first birthday.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was the girl's turn to speak, she stepped behind the
pulpit of the First Assembly of God Church and, without affect,
said quietly, ``I feel there is a place within me, a dark place of
unknown things.'' Hospitalized for anorexia at one point, and
battling depression, she helps with what she called her mother's
anti-pornography ministry, Kids Hurt, Too.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the program was Frances Johnston, who said her son
Michael ``found out he could walk away from homosexuality, but he
walked away too late; he has AIDS.'' And Mike Gabbard, with Stop
Promoting Homosexuality International, who spoke about the need for
laws ``basically saying marriage between a man and a woman will be
valid,'' before playing ``The Wedding Song'' on his guitar.
</P>
<P>
   Then three Republican presidential candidates, Alan Keyes, Gary
L. Bauer and Steve Forbes, showed up to court the social
conservatives gathered here. George W. Bush sent a surrogate, Sen.
John Ashcroft, R-Mo., who spoke on his behalf in an upstairs
classroom before the event.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Christian right is splintered this year, divided
among Bush and the other candidates, they remain active here. This
gathering represents a core constituency of the Republican Party _
and one voting bloc that seems to be searching for a candidate
whose themes will  &UR; not &LR;  make them feel good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking for someone I might even disagree with but who is
a moral leader with the good of the country at heart,'' said Josh
Eshelman, 39, who was browsing the books for sale at the event:
``Ministry to the Homosexual,'' ``The Bible and Homosexuality,''
and ``Informed Answers to Gay Rights Questions.''
</P>
<P>
   A mother standing next to Eshelman with her young son picked up
another book, ``On Wings Like Eagles,'' and was ready to buy it for
him until she saw the subtitle: ``Convincing evidence that Christ
provides hope for those who feel trapped by homosexual desires.''
``Oh no,'' she said, dropping it. ``It's about homosexuality.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why all the focus on homosexuality, Eshelman said,
``Homosexuality is one of the tough issues facing young people.''
And certainly, the speakers here did not shy away from tough
issues.
</P>
<P>
   The keynote address, from Christian writer Josh McDowell,
scolded Christians _ who should not, he said, be so sure that they
hold the moral high ground. Quoting a study that he said showed
that more born-again Christians than atheists are divorced, he
thundered, ``Until we are willing to live the Ten Commandments
ourselves, we have no right to hang them up in schools!''
</P>
<P>
   Then came the candidates. Forbes was introduced by Phyllis
Schlafly, the founder of the anti-feminist Eagle Forum, who
reminded the crowd that ``you're not going to pick the best-looking
candidate,'' or the one with the best personality, and asked them
to consider Forbes instead. ``Steve Forbes is not running for
president because he needs a job; He had a better life before he
got into this campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes mostly stuck to his stump speech, and on the 27th
anniversary of Roe v. Wade, promised religious conservatives that
he would consign the decision ``to the dustbin of history.''
</P>
<P>
   He also asked, ``Who determines what reality is, in the United
States of America? Those power elites in Washington, or we the
people?'' And he promised to retrain the lobbyists who will be
thrown out of work when he dismantles the tax code: ``We'll bring
them to Iowa and they can learn to shovel snow.''
</P>
<P>
   Next up was Keyes, who chided the crowd to stop applauding.
``I'm skeptical about you all. I've seen it all too often; they
applaud, then vote for someone who's going to do God knows what.''
</P>
<P>
   And he suggested that God wants them to vote for him, to cast a
vote ``which accords with what God wishes with all his heart.''
</P>
<P>
   The next speaker, Bauer, had attended several anti-abortion
rallies earlier in the day and visited a cemetery where he placed
roses on the headstone of a stillborn infant found here in a ditch
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you happy with your country?'' he asked the crowd. ``Are
you happy they're passing out condoms and telling our kids they're
no better than barnyard animals, who can't restrain themselves?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Amen,'' shouted one man in the crowd. ``Preach it!''
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest applause of the night, in a standing ovation,
went not to any of the candidates but to Michael Johnston, who said
God helped him go straight. ``Mr. Bush, you can't say you won't
meet with the Log Cabin Republicans,'' a group of gay Republicans,
``just because it might create a controversy,'' he said, as the
crowd roared its approval. ``Tolerance of wickedness and sin is no
family value.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also Johnston who got the biggest laugh, on a night when
there were very few light moments, by addressing another candidate
who was not present, Sen. John McCain: ``And Mr. McCain, you can't
stand for the family and say you can foresee a day when a
homosexual could be president. Who would be the first lady, Ru
Paul?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-00 2145EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
