<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-COPYRIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 COPYRIGHT LAWSUITS TEST LIMITS OF NEW DIGITAL MEDIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Calif., N.Y.)  (js) 
 By SARA ROBINSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A flurry of court activities last week revealed a growing
conflict between the entertainment industry, which is struggling to
protect its products and profits in the Internet age, and consumer
groups, which accuse the industry of interfering with free speech
and people's rights to control their watching or listening
experience.
</P>
<P>
   The digital media market is still small compared to traditional
media, but record companies, film studios and publishers are
preparing for what they see as an inevitable migration of
entertainment online.
</P>
<P>
   Three lawsuits in play last week all dealt with different
aspects of protecting copyrighted works. But at the heart of each
is the question of what framework will govern the distribution of
digital content. It will fall to the courts to set the scope and
application of existing copyright laws _ both new laws and those
enacted long before the Internet _ to digital content.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's really going on in these legal skirmishes is a broader
conflict between traditional means of media distribution and
digital means,'' said Mark Lemley, a professor specializing in
Internet law at the University of California at Berkeley. ``The
media companies have a legitimate concern that the medium of the
Internet enables piracy, but there is also an unsavory concern that
they are losing their traditional distribution mechanism.''
</P>
<P>
   Lemley added: ``The statutes are frighteningly complex, and it's
not clear how to apply them to the Internet. The result that we get
when we work through the statutes and figure it all out may not be
the one that we want.''
</P>
<P>
   The real problem, said Peter Jaszi, a professor specializing in
copyright law at American University, is that ``there are things in
some of the laws which may tilt the results in a direction that is
too restrictive as far as consumer interests are concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Recording Industry Association of America filed
suit against MP3.com, a Web site that last week started a service
allowing customers to store and listen to their CD collections and
newly purchased CDs from a password-protected account online.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Robertson, MP3.com's chief executive, described the
service as a benefit to consumers, letting them listen to music
from any place with an Internet connection. The company took
measures intended to protect copyrights, like allowing the music to
be played but not recorded on a hard drive and limiting the
accounts to one user at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the recording industry filed suit on Friday. In a
letter to Robertson that same day, Hilary Rosen, chief executive of
the recording association, wrote: ``Simply put, it is not legal to
compile a vast database of our members' sound recordings with no
permission and no license. And whatever the individual's right to
use their own music, you cannot exploit that for your company's
commercial gain.''
</P>
<P>
   Lemley, the Berkeley law professor, said he doubted that the
association's lawsuit would prevail.
</P>
<P>
   The suit accuses MP3.com of violating a part of the Copyright
Act of 1976 that grants copyright holders the exclusive right to
make reproductions of their copyrighted sound recordings. But
Lemley said the MP3.com service was technologically equivalent to a
user's making a copy for personal use _ something specifically
allowed under the law.
</P>
<P>
   Jaszi said, though, that it was not clear that the fair-use
exemption applied to MP3.com.
</P>
<P>
   Two other cases in play last week are considered crucial tests
of a much newer law, the Digital Millennium Copyright Act, a
sweeping piece of legislation enacted in 1998 but largely untested
in the courts so far. This law, which makes it illegal to
circumvent copyright-protection technologies, was pushed by the
entertainment industry. But consumer advocates managed to work in
an exemption that allowed software developers to engage in
``reverse engineering'' of copyright protection codes as they try
to create products compatible with the protection technology.
</P>
<P>
   This exemption is an issue in cases that involve software for
cracking encryption codes designed to protect DVDs from illegal
copies. Also on Friday, a federal district judge granted in New
York a request by the Motion Picture Association of America for a
preliminary injunction prohibiting three Web-hosting sites from
distributing the code-cracking software.
</P>
<P>
   The studios say the software, written by a Norwegian teen-ager,
is a piracy tool. But the defendants argue that the purpose of
their program is to allow DVDs to be played on computers that run
the Linux computer system.
</P>
<P>
   Even more important, Jaszi said, the case addresses the issue of
whether the newer law overrides the fair-use provision of the 1976
Act, which has sometimes been construed to embrace reverse
engineering.
</P>
<P>
   The preliminary injunction does not necessarily indicate that
the plaintiffs will prevail, since there is a general bias in the
courts toward granting injunctions in intellectual property cases.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a similar injunction was issued on Tuesday in Seattle
in a case by RealNetworks Inc., a leading provider of software for
distributing multimedia content over the Internet. A federal
district judge there barred Streambox Inc. from further
distributing a product that enables Internet users to record
so-called streaming audio and video on their hard drives.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge did not bar distribution of another product, the
Streambox Ripper, which enables users to convert RealNetwork's
proprietary media format into other formats _ most notably that of
RealNetworks' rival, Microsoft Corp. That ruling, Jaszi said,
suggests that the judge may believe Streambox is likely to prevail
in the case of the Ripper.
</P>
<P>
   Jaszi noted that the Ripper tool did not clearly circumvent
copyright protection technologies. Rather, he said, the judge may
believe that it is a threat mainly to RealNetworks' interest in
maintaining the exclusivity of its proprietary format, which would
not be protected under the 1998 law.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Alben, the RealNetworks vice president for government
affairs, said that the company would continue to pursue the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-00 2150EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
