<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-23 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4170 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-JETS-GROH-780&AMP;ADD     01-23 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-GROH-780&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROH IS NOW AT THE CENTER OF THE JETS' STORY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Al Groh likes to tell a story about how he met his
wife and Bill Parcells on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   Those momentous meetings came back in 1968 at West Point, where
Parcells was an assistant coach, Groh was in the Army hoping to
coach the freshman team, and his future wife, Anne Stahle, was home
from college and working in the officers' club. More than 30 years
later, Groh remains with both of them.
</P>
<P>
   What is the moral? That Groh is a creature of habit? That he
sticks with what he knows? Or that he just likes to tell a story _
that every situation that man or football player or coach faces can
be made simpler by just looking at history?
</P>
<P>
   The new head coach of the New York Jets, whose ascension will be
announced Monday, considers himself a teacher. The Jets, seeking
stability and a continuation of the success that Parcells brought
to the franchise, have given Groh a four-year contract worth
$800,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, Groh tells a story that he somehow relates to football.
It could be a metaphor about Christopher Columbus or Mark McGwire,
but the aim is the same: to get his players to play better
football.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, his second season as the Patriots' defensive
coordinator, he saw the club fall to 3-6. Groh and his son Matthew
ransacked the garage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was with him looking for the shovel in the garage,''
Matthew, now a freshman quarterback at Princeton, said Sunday.
``The shovel took on a celebrity of its own. I have T-shirts with
the shovel on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Groh took the shovel and planted it in front of the team.
``We've got to dig ourselves out of this hole,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And everywhere the Patriots went the rest of the season, the
shovel went, too. The Patriots won their final seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Before another game, Groh asked the defensive players if they
had ever heard of Christopher Columbus. Well, he told them:
``People thought he was crazy sailing to America. But it turned
out, he wasn't crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   That was by way of introducing the defense to the fact it was
about to shift from an eight-man front _ which everyone thought was
necessary to stop a running game _ to a seven-man front. The
Patriots used it and won with it.
</P>
<P>
   To focus last season's Jets linebackers, he told them they
should think of themselves as the most important unit on the team.
He likened them to McGwire's role on the Cardinals; they were the
cleanup hitters, and they had to accept the responsibility that
that entailed.
</P>
<P>
   Now Groh, with Parcells continuing as the head of football
operations, will have to try and control the story line. He has the
top post because Bill Belichick quit on Jan. 4 after a day on the
job, and even Groh may not have an analogy for this situation.
</P>
<P>
   Groh reads the works of Tom Clancy and Richard Ludlum. He just
saw ``The Green Mile.'' This Jets saga has become an equally
improbable and twisted tale, but the 55-year-old Groh seems to be a
sensible sort and has certainly been around. He was even a head
coach once, leading Wake Forest from 1981 to 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Groh went 26-40 with the Demon Deacons, but when he left he had
the second-most victories of any football coach in that school's
history.
</P>
<P>
   He has been with Parcells for two college stints (Army and Air
Force), and with three pro teams (the Giants, the Patriots and the
Jets).
</P>
<P>
   He was the defensive coordinator and linebackers coach during
Parcells' four years in New England. Patriots quarterback Drew
Bledsoe once asked Groh to teach him defense, so Groh would draw up
various formations the quarterback might face and advise him on the
best way to beat them.
</P>
<P>
   Groh remained as coordinator and defensive play caller in 1996
when Belichick joined the Patriots as assistant head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Groh left New England and went to the Jets with Parcells, for
whom he has been the linebackers coach, one of the assistants
Parcells derides as ``the geniuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells has favored a 3-4 defense, and Belichick often shifted
midgame between a three-man front and a four-man alignment. Groh's
preferred basic defense is a 4-3 when he has the manpower.
</P>
<P>
   Now Groh needs a coaching staff. With the defensive line coach
Romeo Crennel's decision on Saturday to take the defensive
coordinator's post at Cleveland, with Groh's ascension from
linebackers coach to head coach, with Belichick's departure after
being both coordinator and defensive backs coach, there is no
carry-over coach from the defense.
</P>
<P>
   What Groh will be facing immediately, then, will be daunting.
The question of assistants will be addressed Monday, and he has
already spoken to several candidates. The new Jets owner, Robert
Wood Johnson IV, will also explain Parcells' role in the front
office Monday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And Groh, who grew up in Manhasset, N.Y., will be adjusting to
his new role, six miles south in Hempstead.
</P>
<P>
   Groh was a varsity football star at Chaminade High School and
then the University of Virginia. His father, Al, was the first
football coach at Cardinal Hayes High School in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Groh followed his Army stint with a return to Virginia, then he
was on to North Carolina, where he helped recruit and coach
Lawrence Taylor. His first pro job was in 1987, a one-year layover
as special teams and tight ends coach with the Falcons. Parcells
hired him to coach the Giants linebackers in 1989-1990.
</P>
<P>
   Groh also was the Giants' defensive coordinator, in 1991, with
Ray Handley as head coach. A year later Groh joined Belichick in
Cleveland for one season, then rejoined Parcells for four years in
New England before moving back to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Groh taught Parcells' daughter Suzy in the second grade at
West Point, also has a football background. Her father, Buck Stahle
was on the 1943 Army team. Her godfather is Glenn Davis, the famed
Mr. Outside and a Heisman Trophy winner in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   Al and Anne have three children: Michael, now a stockbroker in
Richmond, Va., who was a quarterback at Virginia; Ashley Anne, who
teaches hearing-impaired children; and Matthew.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a big screamer,'' Matthew said Sunday. ``But he's a
pretty intense guy. He's as intense as Parcells is. As a child, I
used to see my father's intense stare.'' Fans, he added,
``shouldn't be worried.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
