<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFCMAIN24-C0X </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Late TD saves St. Louis from stingy Tampa
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ It was hardly an artistic achievement, or anything
remotely similar to the fashion in which the St. Louis Rams had
advanced to Sunday's NFC Championship Game. Their powerful offense
was rendered impotent. Their self-esteem, which bordered on
overconfidence, was tweaked. And yet, in the face of dire
circumstances, the Rams refused to succumb.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, they rallied around their MVP quarterback, a reserve
receiver and an underappreciated defense to outlast the
irrepressible Tampa Bay Buccaneers 11-6.
</P>
<P>
   And so, the edict has been lifted in St. Louis. The Rams can not
only talk about the Super Bowl without the threat of a fine, they
are Atlanta-bound.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we played in Atlanta (on Oct. 17), I told the team when
we come back here it's going to be a bigger game,'' said coach Dick
Vermeil, who last made the title game in 1981 as coach of the
Philadelphia Eagles. ``When we look at the tapes, we will say,
`Geez, there was a lot of things we could have done or should have
done.' But I do know that our destination is to go to the Super
Bowl in Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   Just barely. The Buccaneers showed a defense that was as fierce
and quick and relentless as advertised. The Rams' offense that
averaged a league-high 33 points in the regular season _ and scored
49 points against Minnesota a week earlier _ was limited to 309
total yards.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Tampa Bay was protecting a 6-5 lead deep into the
fourth quarter. And considering how the Rams were unable to solve
the Bucs' two-deep zone and multiple blitz packages, that thin
margin was significant. However, Kurt Warner, who was underwhelming
for the first time this remarkable season, convened with third
receiver Ricky Proehl during a timeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kurt said that if the safety blitzed, to run a fade pattern,''
Proehl said. ``He blitzed and I ran past him.''
</P>
<P>
   On third-and-4 from the 30-yard line, Warner lofted a pass
toward the left corner of the end zone. Proehol slowed down in
order to shield the Bucs' Brian Kelly, then went up and made the
touchdown catch with 4:44 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that kicker Jeff Wilkins had a bad knee, ``I just
thought we had better complete it,'' Vermeil said. ``You don't want
to dump a game in a kicker's lap if you don't have to.''
</P>
<P>
   The score gave the Rams an 11-6 lead after a failed two-point
conversion try, and the trip to the Georgia Dome rested with the
St. Louis defense.
</P>
<P>
   London Fletcher and his group of linebackers had instituted $50
fines for anyone saying the words ``Super Bowl'' before Sunday. And
with that destination in the balance, Fletcher and Co. produced.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie quarterback Shaun King showed significant moxie in
leading the Buccaneers to the St. Louis 22-yard line in the last
minute. But that was as far as they got. Defensive end Grant
Wistrom sacked King for a 13-yard loss, moving the ball to the 35.
On second down, King connected with Bert Emanuel for what was ruled
on the field to be a 12-yard gain. But the replay official
overruled the call, making it an incompletion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The officials made what they thought was the right call,''
said King, who was 13-for-29 for 163 yards and two interceptions.
``You have to live with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Buccaneers died with it. Two incompletions later, Tampa Bay
relinquished the ball on downs with 34 seconds left, touching off a
sustained celebration among the 66,396 at the Trans World Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We showed we can play any type of game,'' said running back
Marshall Faulk, who was held to 49 yards total offense. ``It was
back and forth for a long time. But we felt our defense would make
more plays than theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   Turned out, it made one more play than the Bucs. And it was an
interception by rookie cornerback Dre Bly that set up the
game-winning TD.
</P>
<P>
   ``Huge,'' said cornerback Todd Lyght, who also had a pick. ``As
a defense, we had to get the ball back.''
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 5-3 at halftime was almost like a victory for Tampa
Bay. The Bucs were within striking distance, which is all coach
Tony Dungy wanted. They were there because their defense's speed
and aggression grounded the potent Rams attack, giving up just 159
yards and no touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard to score against them,'' said Warner, who threw
three interceptions. ``We didn't finish drives. We were struggling,
but it wasn't us. They were play-making.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bucs' play-making began with the game's first play. Warner
dropped back and attempted to hit Faulk with a screen pass.
However, defensive end Steve White snagged the ball for an
interception, giving the Bucs possession on St. Louis' 20-yard
line, just 15 seconds into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa managed a first down, but had to settle for a field goal
and 3-0 lead. St. Louis then drove to the Bucs' 6 in 16 plays, but
the league's No. 3 defense stiffened, and St. Louis reluctantly
took Wilkins' 24-yard field goal to tie the score.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been tied at halftime if Tampa center Tony
Mayberry had not snapped the ball over the head of quarterback
King. Wisely, King ran the ball down and knocked it out of the end
zone for a safety. St. Louis took that 5-3 lead into halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
