<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOTBALL COLUMN: MCNAIR'S NEXT STOP ENDS AN ODD JOURNEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ About six years ago, Steve McNair stood in
front of his mother's modest home in Mount Olive, Miss., and
contemplated questions I asked about the path he had chosen. Why
hadn't he gone to one of the prestigious colleges that had
recruited him? Why had he opted for tradition and followed his
brother to Alcorn State?
</P>
<P>
   McNair said he wanted to play quarterback, but then he spoke
about the importance in life of going through a process. He had
seen so many of his friends go for the quick strike, trying to get
from point A to point Z without going through all the steps in
between. McNair said back then that he was willing to wait.
</P>
<P>
   In the American Football Conference championship game Sunday,
McNair took a tremendous step in his stunning process of becoming a
star National Football League quarterback. Running and passing like
a latter-day Jim Thorpe, minus mud on his uniform and a leather
helmet, McNair led the Tennessee Titans to a berth in the Super
Bowl with a 33-14 victory over the Jacksonville Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   As stunned fans shuffled out of Alltel Stadium, some cursed the
lack of a Jaguars pass rush and questioned the defensive line's
effort. They did not get it.
</P>
<P>
   There was a pass rush _ the problem was, the rush could not
consistently get to McNair. When the rush found McNair, he escaped
and punctured the defense with a long run or a pass. At least three
times defenders had McNair cornered, and each time McNair shook off
tackles, changed direction and broke down the defense. On one
drive, with his team trailing by 7-0, McNair took off and ran for a
backbreaking 8-yard gain. On the same drive, facing second-and-5,
McNair ran for 4 yards. On third-and-goal from the 9, McNair threw
a touchdown pass to Yancey Thigpen to tie the score.
</P>
<P>
   On Tennessee's first possession of the third quarter, McNair
dropped back to pass, eluded two defenders who appeared to have him
trapped, wheeled and sprinted left before throwing a pass to a
wide-open Eddie George for a 15-yard gain. The Jaguars, frustrated
by their inability to reach McNair, hit him late and drew a 15-yard
penalty. Three plays later, McNair scored on a 1-yard run to give
Tennessee a 17-14 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mark Brunell, McNair's counterpart on the Jaguars,
who had been touted as the better, prettier passer, was chased,
harried and harassed without mercy. Jacksonville fumbled five times
and lost four of them. Brunell threw two interceptions and was
sacked three times. His sack in the end zone with 5 minutes 13
seconds left in the third quarter gave Tennessee a 19-14 lead. On
the ensuing free kick, Derrick Mason went 80 yards for a touchdown.
Game over.
</P>
<P>
   Just to put an exclamation point on the day, McNair _ on a
third-and-1 at the Tennessee 48-yard line _ raced 51 yards to the
Jacksonville 1-yard line. He scored on the next play.
</P>
<P>
   His line for the day: 23 passes, 14 completions for 112 yards,
one touchdown, one interception. But here are the more stunning
statistics: McNair had nine rushing attempts for a team-leading 91
yards and two touchdowns. The only other Titan to run Sunday was
Eddie George, who ran 25 times for 86 yards. The Titans defeated
Jacksonville with two runners _ their fullback and their
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   McNair is 12-2 as a starter this season and has led the Titans
to the Super Bowl in his third season as a starter. Still, in many
minds, McNair flies too low to be picked up on some fans' radar,
too high for others. After the game, McNair was peppered with
questions about the perceived lack of respect from those who said
he would never lead his team to a Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   During a six-game stretch this season, McNair threw just one
touchdown pass with seven interceptions. Titans fans booed him at
Adelphia Coliseum. On radio talk shows they called for the backup
Neil O'Donnell to start and openly lobbied for a trade for Peyton
Manning, their favorite son.
</P>
<P>
   The criticisms were familiar:
</P>
<P>
   McNair can't read (defenses).
</P>
<P>
   McNair can't think (on his feet).
</P>
<P>
   McNair can't win (the big game).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm out there to play football,'' he said Sunday. ``Regardless
of what numbers I put up, people talk about not throwing
touchdowns, or not getting 300 yards passing. We're winning. That's
what counts. You have to do what it takes to win.''
</P>
<P>
   For McNair this season, that has included playing with a flak
jacket to protect his bruised ribs, playing with an arm-length pad
on an injured elbow. He underwent back surgery early in the season
and has played with a severely sprained toe throughout the season.
Bruce Matthews, the Titans offensive lineman and a veteran of 17
NFL seasons, called McNair the toughest football player he has ever
played with.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, as he attempted to put this season in
perspective, McNair repeated the themes of process, endurance and
the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through a lot this whole season, from start to
finish,'' he said. ``I've been through a lot to make this moment
special: not winning the Heisman, not throwing for as many yards as
other quarterbacks. But of all the things I've been through this
year, this means the most to me. Taking this team to the Super
Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, 75,206 mostly Jacksonville fans saw Tennessee defeat
their Jaguars for the third time this season. You get the sense
that the Jaguar fans still don't know what hit them.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot more to Steve McNair than meets the eye.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
