<HEADLINE>
FREE E-MAIL FOR SIMPSONS FANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The word AT in parentheses has been used instead of the
symbol, which is nontransmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(lb) 
 By LAURIE J. FLYNN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   News Digital Media, the online publishing arm of News Corp.'s
Fox Network, has joined the fray of companies offering free
Internet service. But unlike other companies, which provide access
through shopping sites and search engines, News Digital uses a fan
club.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of Bart Simpson and family can now sign up for free e-mail
and Internet access at www.Simpsons.com, a new World Wide Web site
whose debut marks the 10th anniversary of the animated sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement comes just after Kmart said it would provide
free Internet service through its shopping site, following similar
announcements by Yahoo, Excite(AT)home and others. America Online
offers free access in Britain through a Netscape-brand site.
</P>
<P>
   To create the new service, News Digital Media contracted with
1stUp.com, a San Francisco-based company owned by CGMI that
supplies advertising-based Web access.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, 1stUp.com said it had a million subscribers to its
free service, indicating that the idea appears to be catching on.
</P>
<P>
   For free service via Simpsons.com, users must first download an
application that becomes an add-on feature to their browsers _ a
sponsored navigation bar that becomes part of the browser screen.
They are then given e-mail addresses at Simpsons.com.
</P>
<P>
   The site is supported by advertising, and is intended to
complement the TV show and give fans a place to congregate, said
Jordan Kurzweil, vice president of development for Fox.com in New
York. The site also helps Fox gauge viewer reaction to individual
episodes of the show, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company is able to aim advertising at individuals based on
their usage of the site, Kurzweil said. But he added that Fox has a
strict policy against selling user information to other companies
or for use in direct mail.
</P>
<P>
   The company does not appear concerned that people might sign up
for the free service and then change their opening page to another
portal. Such users, Kurzweil said, would probably sign up for free
service from a search engine or other general site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We assumed that if they're signing up through Simpsons.com
rather than through one of the portals that offer free service,
it's because they're a fan,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-00 2159EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
