<SLUG> BC-NY-WRESTLING-RESTAURANT-545&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW PRO WRESTLING FANS HAVE A HOME IN TIMES SQUARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The long line that snaked down 43rd Street from
Broadway to Eighth Avenue and the screaming fans who rushed to get
inside were reminiscent of the days when Frank Sinatra played the
old Paramount Theater in Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   But it was professional wrestlers like the Rock and Chyna, not
pop singers, who climbed out of the limousines last week in front
of 1501 Broadway, once the theater's home, to celebrate the formal
opening of the latest generation of theme restaurant: WWF New York.
</P>
<P>
   The owners of the $25 million restaurant, retail store and
entertainment center are betting that their venture with the World
Wrestling Federation can succeed when many other expensive theme
restaurants closed. Most have failed because of poor food,
declining sales and customer indifference.
</P>
<P>
   While wrestling fans lined up in a snowstorm for a chance to get
the Rock's autograph, Robert Griese, one of the owners of WWF New
York, said his 610-seat restaurant would go a step beyond other
theme restaurants, tapping the popularity of professional wrestling
and providing live entertainment, television broadcasts, World
Wrestling Federation T-shirts and dolls, a nightclub and good food.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not exactly the same as the old theme restaurant,'' said
Ron Paul, president of Technomic, a restaurant consulting company
based in Chicago. ``They have constantly changing entertainment
available, and if they tie into contemporary TV, maybe there's a
niche. But they better have a concept with lasting appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, less than 48 hours after WWF New York's formal
opening, Planet Hollywood, the chain that touched off the
theme-restaurant fad in the mid-1990s, completed reorganization
under bankruptcy court protection, claiming that it too had a
future. ``We're on our way back,'' said Robert Earl, chairman of
Planet Hollywood. ``We're leaner, meaner and raring to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has abandoned its plans for world domination,
selling or closing 30 restaurants and stores. There will no longer
be a Planet Hollywood Hotel in Times Square. The 50-story hotel, at
47th and Broadway, is nearly finished but will no longer be a
Planet Hollywood site, and WWF New York occupies the very space
where Earl once planned to open a new live music chain, Sound
Republic. He has spruced up the Planet Hollywood menu and interior
design.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to revive the beleaguered chain, Planet Hollywood
also plans to move its flagship restaurant from 57th Street into
the Official All Star Cafe, a site it owns at Broadway and 46th
Street. The All Star, in turn, will disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Planet Hollywood's move would be only the latest indication that
the center of gravity for tourism in New York has shifted to Times
Square from 57th Street, where theme restaurants and brand stores
like Warner Bros. proliferated in the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   But the question remains whether WWF New York or a relocated
Planet Hollywood can survive, even in Times Square. Most analysts
say that the first generation of theme restaurants, where
merchandise sales accounted for up to 40 percent of the revenue and
70 percent of the profits, faltered because they overexpanded,
thereby undercutting the chain's appeal, and gave patrons few
reasons to visit more than once.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   WWF New York, like the ESPN Zone, a sports-theme restaurant at
42nd Street and Broadway, has a tie-in to television and a ready
supply of athletes or, as they prefer, entertainers, to attract an
audience.
</P>
<P>
   It may succeed, but analysts are divided over what will happen
to Planet Hollywood. Arnold Ursaner, who follows Planet Hollywood
for CJS Securities, said Earl had refocused the company on food and
entertainment in major cities and tourist markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bankruptcy bought them some time,'' Ursaner said. ``They're
only in key markets now and they may be able to recreate some
cachet.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are not so sure _ Paul for one. ``You've got to be a real
gambler to bet on this one,'' he said. ``It's far too late to fix
the food.''
</P>
</TEXT>
