<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JAGUARS-TITANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TITANS HAVE JAGUARS' NUMBER: IT'S XXXIV
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ With two minutes left and ahead by 19
points, the Tennessee Titans paced their sideline and offered mild
and measured congratulations among themselves. The Titans, though,
looked worried. They wondered if this three-peat against the
Jacksonville Jaguars was really complete, if their apparent spot in
Super Bowl XXXIV would somehow vanish in an odd twist of surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Was it truly over?
</P>
<P>
   Had Jacksonville hidden a miracle in its pocket? Or, indeed,
were the Tennessee Titans these playoffs' lone miracle team?
</P>
<P>
   With 1 minute 22 seconds left, Titans linebacker Eddie Robinson
forced a fumble _ the sixth Jacksonville turnover this afternoon _
and cornerback Denard Walker recovered the ball near midfield. Jeff
Fisher, the Tennessee coach, then jumped higher than any player had
managed all afternoon. Fisher leaped into the waiting arms of
Titans place-kicker Al Del Greco. Their embrace was joyful and
their words flowed while focusing on each others' eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's over with!'' Fisher yelled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going!'' Del Greco responded.
</P>
<P>
   To the Super Bowl. To play the St. Louis Rams, 11-6 winners over
Tampa Bay on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   As Fisher and Del Greco completed their merry spin, all of the
Tennessee Titans turned Jacksonville's Alltel Stadium into their
house. Their dance floor. Their party. It was fitting, especially
since the Titans had done that all afternoon in a too-physical,
too-confrontational, too-tough game for the Jaguars. It was
Tennessee in a breezy 33-14 victory in the American Football
Conference championship game Sunday before 75,206 fans, the largest
crowd ever in this stadium and the quickest group ever to exit,
exasperated after their Jaguars were disjointed and exposed.
</P>
<P>
   As the game's final seconds ticked away, the Titans _ having
scored the game's final 26 points _ were celebrating on the
sideline full throttle, handshakes and hugs all around. Some
players were even shooting with their own personal video cameras,
savoring the scene, the moments. Out came the AFC championship
shirts and hats. It was bizarre that in this conference
championship title game, with a Super Bowl berth at stake, with
Tennessee on the road trying to beat Jacksonville in a historic
manner, that the final seconds would end this way, not with any
twinge of drama, but so relaxed and carefree for the Titans.
</P>
<P>
   But that was exactly what happened for Tennessee, a team that
has won seven straight games. A team that opened its postseason
with a victory at home in the wild-card game, beating Buffalo on a
miracle lateral on a last-seconds kickoff, on a majestic play when
it seemed there was no Titans pulse, no Titans chance. A team that
won at Indianapolis against Peyton Manning and Edgerrin James and
Marvin Harrison, controlling a dynamic offensive threesome that few
teams contained this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee Titans are a team of destiny and more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were here today to make history!'' yelled receiver Yancey
Thigpen across the Titans' locker room. Thigpen, who will miss the
Super Bowl because of a broken right foot sustained Sunday, knew
that no team had ever won a conference championship game on the
road as part of a three-games-in-one-season sweep of an opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee did it Sunday and made glimmering history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe in ourselves, we've got a lot of talent, a lot of
depth, team speed and aggressive guys that fly to the ball and with
the ball,'' said Anthony Dorsett, a Titans safety. ``We expected
Jacksonville to start fast. We also expected them to be unable to
sustain that.''
</P>
<P>
   Those expectations became reality.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville exploded to a 7-0 lead. Tennessee tied the game at
7-7. Jacksonville jumped ahead, 14-7, with 4:36 left before
halftime. And then, with 1:34 left, came one of the game's two
signature plays _ the Jaguars' Reggie Barlow fumbled a punt at his
19-yard line that was recovered by Titans safety Steve Jackson.
That play led to Del Greco's 34-yard field goal only 20 seconds
before halftime. The Jacksonville lead at halftime was 4 points
instead of 7.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee absorbed that momentum. It won the third quarter,
16-0. It won the final quarter, 7-0.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half there were two 1-yard touchdown runs by
quarterback Steve McNair, a safety and Derrick Mason's 80-yard
return of a free kick for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   A fast Jacksonville start _ and then a Jaguars crawl.
</P>
<P>
   ``They talked all week about matching us as a physical team,''
Thigpen said. ``But their mouth said one thing and their mind said
another. Any time you've already lost twice to a team that stays
close at the start of the next game, you start to doubt yourselves.
That's what they did. They made a lot of mistakes but we forced
them into some of those mistakes. They tried to get physical with
us, but if you haven't played that way all year, how are you going
to do that in one game?''
</P>
<P>
   In the second quarter, Jaguars quarterback Mark Brunell, on a
pass from the Tennessee 6, was intercepted in the Tennessee end
zone by safety Marcus Robertson. (Robertson later broke his left
ankle and, like Thigpen, will miss the Super Bowl.) And then, to
end the half, there was the Barlow fumble.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I looked up, they weren't that close to me,'' Barlow
said. ``But those guys came full speed and after I dropped it, I
should have just fallen on it. I messed up. I catch balls like that
every day during the week, in practice before the game, and that
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   After the first two turnovers, Jacksonville was tight. It would
make four more for a total of two interceptions and four fumbles.
It would commit nine penalties for 100 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The penalties, the turnovers, you're not going to win football
games that way,'' said Tom Coughlin, the Jacksonville coach. ``They
work you to the point where you are the team that makes the errors.
When we play them, we find the way to make the errors. However it
happens, when we play Tennessee, we get a little out of our element
and we turn the ball over, for whatever reason. We were never able
to get the crowd back in the game and energize ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the stern Tennessee defense and the marvelous legs of
McNair that helped bury Jacksonville for good. In addition to
scoring twice in the second half, he offered the game's second
signature play in spectacular fashion.
</P>
<P>
   It was McNair's third-and-1 run of 51 yards to the Jacksonville
1 that set up his final 1-yard touchdown run, with 6:59 left. It
put the game squarely in Tennessee's hands. McNair scrambled nine
times for 91 yards, outrushing running back and teammate Eddie
George (25 carries, 86 yards).
</P>
<P>
   And McNair did it with a sore big toe that had hampered him in
practice all week. McNair passed for a touchdown and ran for two
more and that easily offset Brunell's 226 passing yards and minus-1
rushing yards.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville too frequently lost both line battles. It got
pushed around more than it shoved. It could not effectively tackle
McNair.
</P>
<P>
   The game proved too big for too many Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the fourth quarter came, they couldn't score and pretty
much knew it was over,'' Tennessee safety Blaine Bishop said.
``They knew we had their number.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee Titans are made of miracles and more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
