<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRANNY-CAMPAIGN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRANNY D MAKING IMPACT IN WALK FOR CAMPAIGN REFORM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY MICHAEL COIT 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Few followed when Doris ``Granny D'' Haddock set out from
Pasadena a year ago on a cross-country trek for campaign finance
reform.
</P>
<P>
   The diminutive activist, trudging through the first major winter
snow to sock the East, now has the ear of Congress and presidential
candidates Bill Bradley and John McCain. The national magazine
George ranks her among the most fascinating women in politics.
</P>
<P>
   Haddock expects to cross the 3,000-mile mark today in
Cumberland, Md., where she will celebrate her 90th birthday. She's
coming around the mountain with 200 miles remaining to the nation's
capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Alice in Wonderland, I can't really believe it,''
Haddock said from a snowbound home in aptly named Frostburg, Md.
``It's madness, absolute madness. But here I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Overcoming bouts of pneumonia and a troublesome bunion on her
left big toe, Haddock has mostly kept to a 10-mile-a-day pace since
leaving Pasadena in the wake of the Tournament of Roses Parade on
New Year's Day 1999.
</P>
<P>
   She's aiming for a Feb. 29 arrival in Washington. Legions of
supporters ``Granny's angels'' -- from across the nation are
expected to join Haddock for the last stretch of her walk, from
Arlington National Cemetery down the Capital Mall and along K
Street -- home to major lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   The retired shoe company clerk from southern New Hampshire has
come a long way in both distance and impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as a river starts with a drop of water, I hope the
efforts of Granny D will build into a stream of public support for
campaign finance reform that flows into Washington and washes our
democracy clean of special interest money,'' Bradley, the former
Senate Democrat from New Jersey, said in a statement during the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of her,'' McCain said during his campaign. ``It
tells me that I have to do a better job of making connections to
Americans, the way Granny D does.''
</P>
<P>
   The presidential candidates credit Haddock with helping generate
a grass-roots movement to ban large, unregulated contributions
known as soft money. Both political parties have used soft money to
influence presidential and congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing with Bradley on the stump in Claremont, N.H., that
October day was Haddock, making one of the many side trips that
have delayed her trek but bolstered her activism.
</P>
<P>
   On another, she made an early appearance in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Haddock walked with McCain and Sen. Russell Feingold
from their offices to the U.S. Senate for the opening debate on
their campaign finance reform legislation. Joining the Republican
from Arizona and Democrat from Wisconsin were the House sponsors of
a broader reform measure, Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., and
Martin Meehan, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this was pretty funny, this old lady walking with
them. But it made me feel that I was maybe making a mark,'' she
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Being there was not enough. Haddock demonstrated her activism
and delivered personal letters to all 100 senators urging fairness
and an open mind in considering the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The measure died even though it was stripped down to focus on
soft money after it passed the House. Supporters fell seven votes
short of the 60 needed to end a Republican filibuster and force a
vote.
</P>
<P>
   But the great-grandmother who once trembled when speaking to
crowds vows to take her reform crusade through the political
campaign season. She is convinced a soft-money ban is a year or two
from passage and that public financing will follow in decades to
come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to rattle some more cages around the states,'' she
said. ``There's no sense in stopping while you're rolling.''
</P>
<P>
   Haddock has challenged all members of Congress to sign a 25-word
pledge to support the soft-money ban. She will target those who
don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to proceed now is to change a few minds or change
a few seats and she's going to try to do both,'' said Dennis Burke,
director of Arizona Common Cause.
</P>
<P>
   Burke was one of the first volunteers to help Haddock, who
initially set out with a 25-pound backpack and planned to camp when
she couldn't find hosts or lodging for a night. Burke would find
lodging on the route ahead and rented a camper so Haddock could
have meals and rests during her daily walks.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Granny D entourage has included at least a
driver and often several supporters walking with her.
</P>
<P>
   Haddock's faith in people has been continually rewarded.
``Granny's Angels'' number more than 200, and more will follow in
the miles to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think we were fortunate,'' said Susan Conley, who
hosted Haddock over Thanksgiving in Cincinnati, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Conley's two young sons were particularly fascinated with
Haddock. They asked her a lot of questions about why she's walking
across the country and why people get involved in causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they will talk about her for years,'' Conley said.
</P>
<P>
   For Haddock, days and nights walking and resting with strangers
drawn to her has become a love affair.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Morgantown, W.V., she remembered Sandy Pierce, mayor
of tiny Parker, Ariz. Haddock recalled how Pierce embraced campaign
finance reform after they met and then introduced her around town
as a defender of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, all I would have to do is smile and shake hands after
Sandy introduced me. People would immediately see that what I was
doing, did, in fact, relate to serious issues that disturbed them
too,'' Haddock recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Her honors have been many. Haddock has received too many city
keys to count, thrown out the first pitch for a minor league
baseball game, been feted at a rodeo and joined several parades.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Haddock was asked to speak during her home state's
commemoration of the Martin Luther King Jr. holiday.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire officially recognized the national holiday for the
first time this year. The state's civil rights coalition invited
Haddock, knowing she has drawn inspiration from the civil rights
movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great day. Doris has a deep commitment to what is
fundamental to all progress in America,'' said John Rauh, a New
Hampshire political activist who walked with Haddock through
stretches of Arkansas and Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am almost finished with this walk, but I am far from
finished with this work,'' Haddock said.
</P>
<P>
   xxx
</P>
</TEXT>
