<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-23 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4204 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-FBN-RAMS-BUCCANEERS-1     01-23 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAMS-BUCCANEERS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMS HAVE ENOUGH TO SQUEAK PAST BUCS
</HEADLINE>
  (CORRECTS ``triple-teaming'' to ``double-teaming'' in graf
beginning: Tampa Bay was also doing something...) 
 (rk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ This is what can happen when a team gets a little
too smug. Kurt Warner, the league's most valuable player? Three
interceptions. Isaac Bruce, the wide receiver who basically said
the Tampa Bay secondary could not cover his grandmother? Just three
catches. Coach Dick Vermeil, the man who bragged that his offense
had no weaknesses? Stumped.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis had averaged 33 points a game this season in what was
one of the most marvelous offensive displays in NFL history. But
the Rams were shut down Sunday by Tampa Bay's physical,
intimidating style of football.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a play late in the fourth quarter of the NF C
championship game that overcame the Rams' dreary offensive
performance and sent them to the Super Bowl next Sunday against the
Tennessee Titans. On third-and-four at the Tampa Bay 30, Warner
connected with wide receiver Ricky Proehl down the left sideline,
the football barely staying within Proehl's grasp as he tumbled
into the end zone for an 11-6 lead with 4 minutes 44 seconds
remaining. It was his first touchdown catch of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay still had a chance to win the game. After an
instant-replay ruling overturned what appeared to be a catch by
wide receiver Bert Emanuel, which would have given Tampa Bay a
first down at the St. Louis 23-yard line, the Buccaneers still had
two more downs. Both times, however, the rookie quarterback Shaun
King was sacked.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams advance to Super Bowl XXXIV against the Titans with the
victory, capping their spectacular but unpredictable season with a
spectacular but unorthodox victory against a great Buccaneers
defense.
</P>
<P>
   No team has a better collection of inspirational stories than
the Rams do. There is Vermeil, the former coach of the Philadelphia
Eagles who retired in 1982 because of burnout; Warner, who was once
unwanted by most teams and played in the Arena Football League; and
Marshall Faulk, who was traded from Indianapolis, but this season
set an NFL record for all-purpose yards.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis will most likely be favored to beat the Titans, but to
win the Rams will need to play much better than they did against
Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   This was not the type of game most had expected. It was a
defensive struggle. The Rams were out of sync, and at one point the
crowd booed the team, especially after they wasted a timeout to
avoid a delay-of-game penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay took the lead at 6-5 early in the fourth quarter when
Martin Gramatica kicked a field goal from 23 yards. The field goal
came after a deep pass to Jacquez Green, who also had his face mask
nearly ripped off by defensive back Taje Allen. The penalty tacked
15 yards onto the play, giving Tampa Bay the ball at the Rams' 12.
</P>
<P>
   King was 13 for 29 passing for 163 yards but was intercepted
twice and sacked five times.
</P>
<P>
   While Warner was not sacked, he was pressured all afternoon and
on occasion hit hard after delivering the ball. It was all part of
Tampa Bay's game plan. The Buccaneers wanted to knock Warner
around, and they did, and after a Rams offensive player made a
play, the Buccaneers wanted to batter him as well.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay's secondary was brilliant, holding Bruce to one catch
for 7 yards going into the fourth quarter, and only three catches
for 22 yards over all. Warner wound up 26-for-43 passing for 258
yards; Faulk gained only 44 yards on 17 carries and 5 yards on
three receptions.
</P>
<P>
   The punishment of Warner paid off for Tampa Bay with about 12
minutes left in the game. Warner, jittery in the pocket, rushed a
pass down the left sideline to Torry Holt. Defensive back Steve
Kelly stepped in front of the ball and returned the interception to
the St. Louis 42. The Buccaneers were not able to convert the
turnover into points, but had, once again, stopped the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis, perhaps more than any other of the final four teams,
was the most talkative, especially Vermeil, who chirped that he
could find few weaknesses in his offense. Two days before playing
Tampa Bay, Bruce criticized the Buccaneers' secondary, specifically
safety John Lynch, saying it was an unimpressive group.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay plays an abundance of ``cover two,'' a type of zone
defense, and thus Lynch plays very little man-to-man in that
coverage. Bruce jumped on this, saying that because of the speed of
the St. Louis wide receivers, Lynch would be forced at times to
cover a receiver one-on-one. The implication was that Lynch was too
slow to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The bragging by Vermeil and Bruce was somewhat surprising. Most
coaches and players tend to make their public comments as bland as
skim milk at this time of year. But their talk said a lot about the
Rams' confidence going into this game. As the second half of the
season unfolded, the Rams began to believe they were unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   The Buccaneers took notice, storing away the comments, using
them as motivation.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On the first play of the game, the Tampa Bay defense showed why
it is one of the best in the league. When Warner dropped back to
pass, he was immediately pressured, and a planned screen was
hurried. Tampa Bay defensive lineman Steve White tipped the ball,
then caught the errant pass, giving the Buccaneers the football at
the 20. Tampa Bay could not capitalize with a touchdown but did
take a 3-0 lead after a 25-yard field goal by Gramatica.
</P>
<P>
   For a team that supposedly has few weaknesses on offense, the
Rams looked mortal early on. The reason was Tampa Bay. The
Buccaneers' defense is a hard-hitting, disciplined unit, and when
St. Louis receivers caught passes, they paid for it. The Rams' Holt
was hit so hard in the ribs after making a catch, he had to leave
the game temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay was also doing something that other teams had been
unable to accomplish against St. Louis. Rams players rarely broke
tackles, especially Faulk, who has made a living out of making the
first defender miss, and then the second and third as well. And
Tampa Bay was succeeding even though the Pro Bowl defensive end
Warren Sapp was quiet, thanks to double teams.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Tampa Bay, as it has been all season, was the
offense. The score was tied at 3-3 after the first quarter, and
then it was a baseball-like 5-3 after Buccaneers center Tony
Mayberry snapped the ball several feet over King's head. As the
ball skipped into his end zone, King made a smart move, batting it
out of play, but it was still a safety, and the Rams got the two
points.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams' offense was shaken. That showed late in the second
quarter when, on fourth-and-one at the Tampa Bay 26, it decided to
try a 44-yard field goal instead of going for the first down. That
would never have happened during the regular season when the Rams
were racking up more than 400 yards of offense a game.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Wilkins' kick was wide right, and Tampa Bay, at least for a
half, had done exactly what it wanted. It had held the best offense
in football to no touchdowns. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
