<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAGUARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BAD DAY AT THE OFFICE DRIVES THE JAGUARS OUT OF THE PLAYOFFS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ Jacksonville quarterback Mark Brunell was
asked to pinpoint the moment it all started to slip away, the play
that irrevocably turned the tide in Sunday's American Football
Conference championship game and swept the Jaguars out of the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   And so he began his chronicle of chaos.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were bad reads, bad blocks, bad throws,'' Brunell said.
</P>
<P>
   There was bad everything for the Jaguars, a team that scorched
Miami for 62 points only a week ago but Sunday self-destructed
after being physically overwhelmed by Tennessee. The Jaguars turned
the ball over six times. Four of the turnovers came in the second
half, when the game got away from Jacksonville entirely.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars were penalized for 100 yards, 83 in the second half.
They dropped passes as if the ball had just come out of the
microwave, allowed a safety and gave up a kick return for a
touchdown on the next play.
</P>
<P>
   The turning point?
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the second half,'' Jaguars Coach Tom Coughlin said.
``We were never able to put anything together to get the crowd back
in the game and energize ourselves and keep us from shooting
ourselves in the foot. You worry early on when you have a turnover
and a penalty negates a turnover. You think, `I hope it's not going
to be that kind of day.'''
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of day. Still, Jacksonville led by 14-10 at
halftime, although the Jaguars' first drive of the third quarter
ended on an incomplete pass. Brunell had 19 of those, although at
least a dozen seemed to bounce off his receivers' hands or chests.
</P>
<P>
   On Tennessee's first drive of the third quarter, two penalties
for a total of 43 yards meant that the Jaguars essentially grabbed
the Titans' hands and pulled them downfield. One came after a
15-yard Steve McNair completion to Eddie George for a first down.
But because of a roughing-the-passer penalty on Tony Brackens,
Tennessee wound up at Jacksonville's 35-yard-line.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans gained just 1 yard on first down, and McNair's pass
to Kevin Dyson on second down was incomplete. But Fernando Bryant
was penalized for pushing off on Dyson down the right sideline,
giving the Titans the ball on Jacksonville's 6-yard line. Two plays
later, the Titans scored to begin their roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Penalty, penalty, penalty,'' Coughlin said. ``We escorted them
the length of the field, and they finished it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Jaguars had to play catch-up, which forced them out of
their conservative game plan. Brunell threw incomplete on first
down. He failed to complete another pass on second down, but
offensive lineman Ben Coleman was called for a false start to back
up the Jaguars five yards more. On second-and-15, Brunell completed
a throw to tight end Kyle Brady. But linebacker Eddie Robinson
grabbed Brady and forced a fumble, which was recovered by the
Titans.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans did not score on that drive because tight end Fred
Wycheck fumbled on the Jaguars' 1-yard line as he was struggling to
score. But in the next 1 minute 5 seconds, the Jaguars' season
effectively ended. With Jacksonville trying to jam the ball out of
its own red zone, Fred Taylor gained nothing up the middle. The
Jaguars took a timeout. On second down, Brunell backed up to pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called a maximum protection scheme, we kept everybody in
except the two wide receivers,'' Coughlin said. ``We got the
coverage we wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   But Titans left tackle Josh Evans had been set loose and, as he
got to Brunell, his teammate, right tackle Jason Fisk, was there to
meet him. They sacked Brunell for a safety to make the score 19-14.
On the free kick that followed, the Titans' Derrick Mason caught
the ball at the 20, juked past Jason Craft _ the only player with a
legitimate shot at him _ and was gone for a touchdown. Suddenly,
the Titans' lead was 12 points with five minutes left in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Brunell went into the shotgun even on short-yardage situations
as the Jaguars abandoned the running game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get out of your element like that, the numbers may
look good, but it's not the quality game,'' Coughlin said. ``When
you're in a mode of almost needing two scores, you're exposed not
only because you're going to throw on every down, but because there
is more of a chance of turnovers.''
</P>
<P>
   The next drive ended with an incomplete pass on fourth down. And
the one after that ended on a Brunell interception after the drive
had sputtered early because of two consecutive penalties. The
Titans scored off that interception to complete the scoring and
send the Jaguars into their devastated locker room.
</P>
<P>
   There, Taylor insisted that Tennessee deserved only a small bit
of credit for the victory because, he reasoned, Jacksonville is
still the better team and gave the game away with turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys have got to learn in a game of this magnitude, you
can't afford turnovers,'' offensive lineman Leon Searcy said. ``If
you don't play error-free football, you're going to get beat.
Everything started rolling downhill. Turnovers, safety, kickoff
returns, breakdowns. We didn't have too many breakdowns, but all
you need is a couple.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has our number. They own the Jaguars right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
