<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BUCCANEERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAMPA BAY LETS SECRET SLIP AWAY AT WRONG TIME
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The Tampa Bay Buccaneers had been keeping a secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rams didn't think they could be stopped,'' said Buccaneers
safety John Lynch. ``The secret was that we knew they were wrong.
And we were positive we could prove it.''
</P>
<P>
   For all but the final five minutes of Sunday's NFC championship
game, the Buccaneers had not only kept their secret, they had kept
their promise. Tampa Bay's defense had held St. Louis'
record-setting offense to one field goal.
</P>
<P>
   But on a third-down-and-four, with 4 minutes 44 seconds left in
a game Tampa Bay led by one point, the Buccaneers' defense made the
mistake that would cost them a trip to the Super Bowl. The
Buccaneers blitzed, leaving cornerback Brian Kelly alone to cover
Rams receiver Ricky Proehl.
</P>
<P>
   Rams quarterback Kurt Warner recognized the advantage and threw
the football into the end zone for Proehl, who outjumped Kelly for
the catch.
</P>
<P>
   Proehl made the pivotal play in the Rams' 11-6 victory an
instant before a sprinting Lynch arrived from the middle of the
field _ back-up help that was a step tardy to salvage 55 minutes of
brilliant defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody had stopped them like we did,'' Lynch said after the
game. ``Then again, we didn't stop them for the whole game. That's
all it takes sometimes _ one play and you lose. That's the story of
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Buccaneers did not blitz often their gamble on the
game's only touchdown was a calculated risk. At the 30-yard line,
the Rams, who trailed, 6-5, were in field-goal range.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to either get them out of field goal range or make
it a longer kick,'' Tampa Bay coach Tony Dungy said of his
strategy. ``It's a bitter pill because we did so much of what we
wanted to do. But in the end, they found a way into the end zone.''
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, Tampa Bay disrupted the Rams' offensive
timing. Defensive end Steve White deflected and then intercepted
Warner's first pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see him,'' Warner said of White. ``It wouldn't be the
last time something like that happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner, who completed 26 of 43 passes for 258 yards, was
intercepted three times. The Buccaneers defensive game plan was to
stop running back Marshall Faulk in his early rushing attempts,
which worked as Faulk had only 44 yards on 17 carries. Then they
took the Rams' top receiver Isaac Bruce out of the game _ he had
only two catches for 8 yards in the first three quarters and only
three for 22 yards in the game. And finally, they collapsed the
pocket on Warner, who had to rush a lot of his decision making.
</P>
<P>
   When Kelly intercepted a Warner pass intended for Torry Holt
early in the fourth quarter _ another pass Warner hurried _ it
looked like the Buccaneers, who were nearly two touchdown
underdogs, were going to pull off the biggest pro football upset
since last year's NFC title game, when Atlanta beat Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly might have been thinking that way. He taunted the Rams
bench, doing an impersonation of the Rams' receivers touchdown
dance, near their sideline. After Proehl caught his touchdown, the
video screen on the Trans World Dome scoreboard displayed a tape of
Kelly's dance from earlier in the quarter and added the words: Not
in our house.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly didn't discuss his antics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I was in good position,'' he said of Proehl's
touchdown. ``I was stumbling a little bit and couldn't really jump
like I wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   While there was obvious disappointment in the Buccaneers locker
room, there was clearly a sense of satisfaction, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody gave us a chance,'' defensive end Warren Sapp said.
``But we told you it would be a war and it was a war. We went toe
to toe with them.''
</P>
<P>
   But in most of their 12 victories this year, the Buccaneers
defense could be counted on for one or two game-changing plays.
They did not get them Sunday. Sapp, for example, was double-teamed
for most of the game and did not have a tackle or a sack.
</P>
<P>
   The one game-changing play belonged to the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We surprised them, I think,'' Lynch said. ``I don't know if
they thought we could do that to them. But you have to give them
credit. They got us back with that one play.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
