<SLUG> BC-ECUADOR-NOBOA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECUADOR'S NEW PRESIDENT SWORN IN &HT;     

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN OTIS 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
QUITO, Ecuador _ After a weekend rebellion forced out a president
and briefly ushered in a military junta, Ecuadoreans have turned to
a low-key lawyer to lead them back from the abyss.
<P>
   ``Today, I had a dream. Today, I dream of a different country, a
new country,'' said President Gustavo Noboa, who arrived at the
national palace Sunday to form a new government.
</P>
<P>
   Noboa was sworn in after the ouster of President Jamil Mahuad on
Friday in a military-backed coup. But the coup leaders decided to
give way to Noboa, who was Mahuad's vice president.
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday, calm prevailed across the country. Stores reopened,
buses and taxis were back on the streets, and thousands of
anti-government protesters, who converged on Quito last week, had
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Noboa named the first five members of his Cabinet and flew to
his home in the Pacific coast city of Guayaquil.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ecuadorean government has returned to normal,'' said
Francisco Huerta, the newly appointed minister of government.
``Stability is guaranteed.''
</P>
<P>
   Stable is how many observers describe Noboa.
</P>
<P>
   A devout Roman Catholic, the 62-year-old Noboa comes from a
family of public servants. A distant relative was once president of
Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   Noboa's heroes include the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. and
Abraham Lincoln. In fact, he said, he styles his beard to look like
Lincoln's. Noboa was governor of Guayas state, and law professor
and rector of the Catholic University in Guayaquil. He also was a
member of the government commission that negotiated the end to a
long border war with Peru.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Mahuad, who dithered so long before making decisions that
cartoonists depicted him as Shakespeare's Hamlet, Noboa appears to
have a sense of mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mahuad never said what he was going to do,'' said political
analyst Simon Pachano. ``Noboa is already defining his path.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Noboa was vice president for 17 months, he was not part
of Mahuad's inner circle and kept his office in Guayaquil rather
than Quito, the capital. He spent much of his time supervising the
rebuilding of coastal roads damaged by floods during the 1997 El
Nino weather pattern.
</P>
<P>
   With Ecuador mired in its worst economic crisis in 70 years,
Noboa further distanced himself from the unpopular Mahuad. In fact,
he was so out of the loop that he learned about Friday's coup
through TV reports.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the strategy paid off, allowing Noboa to come across
as a newcomer rather than as a retread from a failed government,
said Fernando Bustamante, a political science professor at San
Francisco University near Quito.
</P>
<P>
   ``Noboa didn't want to get burned,'' Bustamante said. ``He
always thought that this could happen and that he had to be
untainted.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Mahuad, Noboa has vowed to pursue free-market reforms to
resurrect the economy. But the opposition-controlled Congress
rejected most of Mahuad's initiatives, and the resulting gridlock
has been one of the main reasons for the current economic woes.
</P>
<P>
   Some say Noboa may enjoy a brief honeymoon with lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were close to having a dictatorship, and now the Congress
is scared about what could happen,'' said a Quito banker who
requested anonymity. ``In this atmosphere, it's easier to get
things done.''
</P>
<P>
   Jaime Nebot, leader of the powerful Social Christian party,
warned that Noboa could be in for a rough term if he ignores the
poor, tries to raise taxes, or focuses on paying off Ecuador's
debt. ``If we have a government that's concerned only about the
holders of Ecuador's foreign debt, I will have to say `no.' My
party will have to say `no,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Noboa said he would go forward with a controversial
plan proposed by Mahuad to scrap the local currency for the U.S.
dollar. In the past year, the sucre has fallen from 7,000 to 25,000
to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Noboa also said he would address the concerns of impoverished
Indians, farmers and other Ecuadoreans who were involved in last
week's protests.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here have suffered... They have been tricked and have
good reason not to believe'' in the government, Noboa said in an
interview on Ecuadorean television.
</P>
<P>
   Noboa also pledged to stamp out corruption.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Mahuad was accused of accepting millions of dollars
in campaign donations from a banker who later benefited from a
multi-billion-dollar government bailout of the financial sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to be personally involved in this issue,'' Noboa
said. ``There are honest bankers but what has happened in this
country is very grave... We have witnessed outrages.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Noboa was magnanimous when asked about Mahuad's downfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought that Mahuad was intelligent... and someone
that the country needed,'' Noboa said. ``I'm very sad about what
happened. I think he deserved better.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
