<HEADER>
A4220 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-LYNCHING-EXHIBIT-1015     01-23 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCHING-EXHIBIT-1015(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACIST HATRED FROM PAST RESONATES IN EXHIBITION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Thay Bowser of Manhattan remembers being a little
girl in Pickens, S.C., when a black man was lynched some 30 miles
away. ``My mother was told to keep her children in, her boys in,
because there might be problems,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bowser, 72, stood quietly and alone on Saturday afternoon in
a line of spectators crowded into a tiny one-room gallery on
Manhattan's Upper East Side to see photographs of Americans _ the
vast majority of them black men _ who were hanged from dogwood
trees and telephone poles, and the throngs of white people who had
come to watch, often with children in tow.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to hold back sobs, Ms. Bowser said, ``I knew I had to
come.''
</P>
<P>
   When she neared the end of the show and stood looking at a
triptych of a man named Frank Embree, his eyes looking straight at
the camera just before he was lynched, Ms. Bowser said she could
bear no more. ``I'm going to have to come back,'' she said, burying
her head in her coat. ``It's just too much.''
</P>
<P>
   So it went Saturday afternoon at the Roth Horowitz gallery at
160A East 70th St., as the exhibition, called ``Witness,'' evoked
emotions as varied as the people who had come to see it. The show
contains some 60 photographs, picture postcards and assorted
artifacts chronicling the practice of lynching from Illinois to
Mississippi, between 1883 and 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds have seen the exhibition since it opened 10 days ago.
Visitors on Saturday said they had heard about the show through
reviews in newspapers, on black talk radio and on the Cable News
Network's Web site and the America Online home page.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, between noon and 4 p.m., about 300 visitors went to
the gallery, so small that it can accommodate no more than about 25
people at one time. By midafternoon, nearly 30 people were lined up
outside in frigid temperatures, most waiting for about 20 minutes
on the sunless street.
</P>
<P>
   The Saturday before, 200 people visited the gallery, which had
drawn only about 15 or 20 visitors on Saturdays for previous shows,
according to one of the gallery's owners, Andrew Roth.
</P>
<P>
   For some, the show lighted memories. For others, it brought to
light their ignorance.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Stevenson, 45, of Brooklyn, saw two photographs that his
father, who was raised in Montgomery, Ala., had in his own
collection. He said he was 10 when his father pulled them out of a
loose-leaf binder, as a history lesson on what it meant to be black
in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Roberta Slotnick, a Manhattan shoe-store owner, said she could
only compare the pictures to what she could relate to as a Jew:
Hitler's Germany. A white college student said she was horrified to
see the picture of a white couple casually watching the hanging of
a black man. A Korean-American woman from Queens said simply,
``That could be us.''
</P>
<P>
   Scholars of race in America are not in complete agreement about
what to make of the zeal with which Americans _ blacks, whites and
others _ have flocked to an exhibition so explicitly devoted to
racist violence.
</P>
<P>
   Some say it signals a greater willingness to face past
injustices, sparked most notably by efforts to ensure that the
Holocaust is not forgotten. Perhaps, they say, Americans,
particularly whites, are willing to suspend what the Civil War
historian Eric Foner called ``a historical amnesia about slavery,
about racism.''
</P>
<P>
   As evidence, they point to the renewed attention on the
Confederate flag that flies over the state Capitol in South
Carolina and the widely publicized discovery of Thomas Jefferson's
liaison with his former slave, Sally Hemings; the latter is even
the subject of an upcoming television miniseries.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the popularity of this exhibition, Foner added, should
serve as an argument for a museum devoted to slavery.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Berger, a cultural historian, said the exhibition points
to ``a zeitgeist moment in the culture.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hit a chord,'' Berger said. ``Americans, particularly
white Americans, have been reluctant to look at their own racism.''
</P>
<P>
   Some suggest that the lynching exhibition has drawn attention
because of the 1998 murder of James Byrd, a black man dragged to
death by three white men in Jasper, Texas. Others question whether
the willingness to look at lynchings _ associated with another era
and another place, mostly in the South _ equates with a willingness
to confront racism today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the mainstreaming of black collective history,'' observed
Patricia J. Williams, a professor of law at Columbia University.
``We all know it. Yet there's a disbelief in the dominant culture,
because it's not yet in the history books. The longer test is
whether it will be remembered.''
</P>
<P>
   The gallery was full soon after it opened at noon on Saturday.
The first to walk in, Bruce Chambers, a bank worker from the Bronx,
had arrived two hours early. Looking at the photographs, he said,
he was struck by the faces of both the executed and the
executioners.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an African-American, you try to put yourself in the
perspective of the people that this actually happened to,'' he
said. ``Considering the fact that human beings have been executed,
for people to smile, to be actually jostling to be in the picture,
that's more stunning than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the afternoon, the crowd inside the gallery
surrounded the collector of the photographs, James E. Allen,
peppering him with questions, for most of the images are
unaccompanied by explanatory text.
</P>
<P>
   They asked: Who are these people? (The townspeople who came to
watch were ordinary people, Allen, an antiques dealer from Atlanta,
told them.) What were the alleged crimes of those who were lynched?
(It could have been anything, often entirely unsubstantiated, he
said.) Why were strands of human hair affixed next to a photograph
of a man hanging from a tree? (Because spectators liked to collect
body parts.) Why were postcards made of these events? (To publicize
them far and wide.)
</P>
<P>
   ``What country is this?'' Ms. Slotnick asked rhetorically. In a
whisper, she added: ``Are we so violent? Don't you feel ashamed?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Taylor, a stenography student from Queens, looked at the
faces of the men who had been lynched and said he could see
pleading in their eyes. ``I don't know these victims, but I feel a
connection, emotionwise,'' said Taylor, 23, whose family came from
Jamaica. ``It's difficult. I see them pleading not to be lynched,
begging for their life.''
</P>
<P>
   Fraser Robinson, the owner of a Manhattan Internet company,
stared at a picture of four black men hanged from the same tree and
said they still seemed to him slightly unreal, like dummies
suspended. ``Look at those guys _ doesn't even seem like real
people,'' said Robinson, 27, who is white.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor and his friend Dwight Williams, 23, said they wished the
exhibition had been publicized more widely for their generation _
like on the hip-hop radio stations they listen to. But even if it
were, Taylor said, many would probably pass it by.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of African-Americans, they don't want to remember
this,'' he said. ``They want to focus on the present, not look at
the past. I don't think that's good. Why wouldn't you want to see
this, as graphic as it is? It's history.''
</P>
<P>
   The historian David Levering Lewis agreed, saying he was not
convinced that Americans _ either black or white _ are willing to
face the past. ``There's a sense of a kind of success ethos
overtaking much of black America,'' Levering Lewis, a Rutgers
University professor, contended. ``We now want to emphasize, in
this half-full, half-empty glass, the full.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen, whose collection is on display through Feb. 12, suggested
that the attention on the exhibition was fueled precisely by the
suppressed nature of the subject of lynching. Remarkably, although
numerous photographs were taken and circulated, they have rarely,
if ever, been displayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this were discussed openly, if this were part of our
consciousness, there wouldn't be this response,'' he said.
``Vestiges of this cruelty exist in our system today.''
</P>
<P>
   For Stevenson, who was reminded of his father's collection, the
surprise came from seeing these bone-chilling pictures in the
company of so many whites, and not just in a roomful of
African-Americans like himself. How did it make him feel?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say more hurt than anything, that they could do this,'' he
said quietly. ``When I walked in, I was a little bit taken aback. I
also know a lot of whites are remorseful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
