<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: RAMS' WARNER GOES FROM THE SUPERMARKET TO THE SUPER
BOWL 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ He had one of the most improbable seasons in
football history. A virtual rookie, Kurt Warner threw 41 touchdown
passes and was the most valuable player of his sport. No
quarterback had ever came from so far, so suddenly.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody knew his story: stacking groceries at the Hy-Vee back
in Iowa for $5.50 an hour, sometimes tossing a roll of toilet paper
to a co-worker, just to keep the arm limber. Playing quarterback in
cramped indoor arenas. Showing up with a rose to court the lady
with the two children who is now his wife.
</P>
<P>
   So much has happened this season, but late Sunday _ very late
Sunday _ the trip to the Super Bowl pretty much depended on Kurt
Warner's right arm. He had earned that responsibility by playing so
magnificently for this entire improbable season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The character of this team has been that somebody has stepped
up to make a play every game,'' he said after slinging the 30-yard
touchdown pass to Ricky Proehl with 4 minutes 44 seconds left that
gave the St. Louis Rams an 11-6 victory over Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Even more improbable was that if Kurt Warner had not won this
game with one perfect throw down the sideline, another improbable
quarterback would be flying to Atlanta on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Buccaneers had their own outsider, Shaun King, fresh out of
Tulane, who was playing the likes of Rutgers and Army in the past
four years. King, a true rookie, was third string until late
November, but he nearly played the Buccaneers to the Super Bowl,
with his powerful arm and his quick mind.
</P>
<P>
   In this game of strange football scores, more of a Mark
McGwire-Sammy Sosa long-ball contest a few blocks away at Busch
Stadium, the two quarterbacks battled gamely to get a handle on the
ball and the game.
</P>
<P>
   King made the defining play of the first half, a snap judgment
that quite possibly saved 5 points for his team. His stratagem came
on the first play of the second quarter, from the Bucs' 27-yard
line, when the center, Tony Mayberry, snapped a floater that
wobbled past King, bouncing on the hard artificial turf and heading
toward the end zone, with King in chase.
</P>
<P>
   If the Rams retrieved the ball in the end zone, they would have
a touchdown and presumably 7 points. If King retrieved the ball in
the end zone, it would have been a safety and 2 points. But there
was no reason to think King could reach the ball and control it
with a phalanx of Rams coming down on him.
</P>
<P>
   So King made the split-second call on the run, extending his arm
and swatting the ball clear through the end zone, for the automatic
safety that put the Bucs behind, 5-3, which was better than 10-3.
</P>
<P>
   When the Bucs went ahead, 6-5, early in the third quarter, this
gave them points and space to maneuver. The Rams, who had been
behind for only a few minutes all season, now had to play from
behind.
</P>
<P>
   There had not been a single touchdown scored in this conference
championship game. The Rams could not count on any long-distance
field goal to save their season because their kicker, Jeff Wilkins,
was playing on a wobbly knee. They needed a touchdown, a jolt from
the blue, from their improbable quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was time for Ricky to make a big play and Kurt Warner to
make a big play,'' an emotional Coach Dick Vermeil said later.
</P>
<P>
   All the noise in the Trans World Dome favored the Rams. It was
home _ a familiar blur of blue and yellow _ but Warren Sapp had
been brutalizing the Rams' line all afternoon. It was second-and-4
on the Tampa Bay 30.
</P>
<P>
   Warner, who was not a starter at Northern Iowa until his last
year, his fifth in college, has been learning the game with the
Iowa Barnstormers, with the Amsterdam Admirals in Europe. Going
into this season, he had thrown only 11 passes in one game in the
National Football League. Now he had to read a defense under
pressure with the Super Bowl in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The safety blitzed, and Kurt had to read it,'' Proehl said
later.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing that Proehl would be racing down the left sideline,
one-on-one with a cornerback, Warner made the link between his
brain and his right arm and unleashed a perfect pass. Proehl stuck
out his right elbow, holding off Brian Kelly, and caught the ball
over his shoulder, leaving his feet and tumbling into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Warner would give witness to his Christian faith, but there was
also the matter of his dedication to his craft. He had stacked
shelves, he said, only because he was helping out at his old high
school during the day, keeping his arm warm for his next arena
football gig.
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't been back to the supermarket or his hometown of Cedar
Rapids, Iowa, recently. He won't make it this week. The improbable
quarterback is going to the Super Bowl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
