u s BC-GLF-BOBHOPE-CLASSIC-N     01-23 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BOBHOPE-CLASSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARNEVIK IS FINDING THE PGA TOUR TO HIS LIKING
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERMUDA DUNES, Calif. _ After hitting a spectator on the head
with an errant tee shot on the 15th hole Sunday, Jesper Parnevik
was shaken. His concern eased, however, when the fan was not
seriously injured and displayed a sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was down on the ground, and it looked like a big golf ball
was growing out of his forehead,'' Parnevik said. ``It was a
terrible sight. I asked if he was OK, and he said: `I'm fine. As
long as you win the tournament, I'm OK'''
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik followed instructions. With a decisive birdie on the
final hole for a closing 65, Parnevik continued his torrid start to
the 2000 season and won the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic by one stroke
over Rory Sabbatini and by two strokes over J.L. Lewis and David
Toms. Parnevik finished the 90-hole tournament at 27-under-par 331
to defeat Sabbatini, who shot a 68 Sunday. Lewis and Toms both had
final-round 65s.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third consecutive top-six finish for Parnevik, who
tied for sixth at the Mercedes Championships and then tied for
third at last week's Sony Open in Hawaii. Sunday's $540,000
first-place check put Parnevik atop the PGA Tour's early-season
money list at $808,700, and instead of splitting time between the
United States and the European Tour as he normally does, Parnevik
will consider playing exclusively in the United States this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to play full time on the U.S. tour one year, just
to see where I end up on the money list,'' said Parnevik, a native
of Sweden who played brilliantly for Europe during last year's
Ryder Cup. ``It would be fun to play 25 tournaments in one year,
just to see how well I can do. I know Tiger Woods can play 15
tournaments and win by miles, but it would be fun to challenge
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The main challenge Sunday for Parnevik came from Sabbatini, not
from David Duval, the world's No. 2-ranked player, who shot a
disappointing 69 and settled for a fifth-place tie with Hal Sutton
at 23-under-par. Starting the day tied with Parnevik just two
strokes behind the fourth-round leader, Sabbatini, Duval had a
terrible day with his putter, missing many putts from short range
and squandering numerous birdie opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing for me now is to regain confidence with my
putter, which is not something that I'm usually lacking,'' said
Duval, who shot a 59 in the final round last year to win this
tournament. ``Whatever I tried didn't help.''
</P>
<P>
   While Duval struggled from the beginning, Sabbatini started
boldly, making birdies on five of his first nine holes, bidding to
win for the first time on the tour at age 23. But the outcome was
decided on the par-5, 513-yard finishing hole at Bermuda Dunes
Country Club, which Parnevik birdied, while Sabbatini settled for
par.
</P>
<P>
   Playing one group ahead of Sabbatini, Parnevik hit an excellent
tee shot at No. 18 and then blasted a superb 5-wood shot from 255
yards away that landed on the green, 40 feet from the cup.
Parnevik's putt for eagle stopped five feet short, but he made the
next putt for birdie, giving him a one-stroke lead over Sabbatini.
</P>
<P>
   While a nervous Parnevik went to the driving range in case there
was a playoff, Sabbatini knew he needed at least a birdie on the
final hole. But Sabbatini pulled his tee shot into the left rough,
about four feet behind a tree that blocked his path to the green.
Then Sabbatini made another mistake when he struck the ball too
hard trying to hit a wedge shot back into the fairway. The ball
crossed the fairway and landed in the right rough, still 114 yards
from the flag, with more trees in the way.
</P>
<P>
   But Sabbatini kept the suspense going with a splendid approach
shot, lofting a wedge shot over trees and onto the green, stopping
the ball about 25 feet from the pin. Sabbatini's birdie attempt to
force a playoff slid past the cup, however, giving Parnevik the
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik, who will turn 35 in March, lit a victory cigar on the
driving range, celebrating his third tour victory in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Sabbatini, a native of South Africa, pondered what might have
been. After his early rash of birdies, Sabbatini, bogeyed No. 10
and No. 11 and finished with six consecutive pars, pulling several
tee shots on the back nine and showing his anger after poor shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a few distractions out there; I lost a little bit
of concentration,'' said Sabbatini, who was irritated by a marshal
who almost stepped on his ball twice on No. 10. ``The positive
aspect is that I managed to stay in it, even when I wasn't at my
best.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Parnevik, it was a victory that will be appreciated by
his father, Bo, who is a comedian in Sweden. Bob Hope is one of Bo
Parnevik's favorite comedians. And Sunday the Bob Hope tournament
became one of Jesper Parnevik's favorite events.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
