<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-23 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4225 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CHECHNYA-CIVILIANS-BO     01-23 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-CIVILIANS-BOS </SLUG>
  
 CIVILIANS SUFFERING INFLICTED BY BOTH SIDES IN cHECHEN WAR 
(For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE AND DMITRI SHALGANOV S  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GROZNY, Russia _ Svetlana Kapustina picks her way through the
rubble in the bombed-out wasteland that is Chechnya's capital,
Grozny, as she waits for her daughter to return.
</P>
<P>
   She has been waiting for two months.
</P>
<P>
   A tattered overcoat barely protecting her from the chilly fog
engulfing the city, Kapustina stands in the entrance to a gutted
apartment building and recalls the day when armed men took away her
15-year-old daughter, Irina. Several floors above her, Russian
soldiers peer through broken windows, watching for Chechen snipers.
Overhead, Russian warplanes streak toward Grozny's center as
artillery shells explode in the distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Nov. 22. They bombed our home, they bombed us and then
they took away my little girl,'' Kapustina said, her voice cracking
as she tried unsuccessfully to fight back tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were wearing uniforms. They had beards. Maybe they were
Chechens, maybe not. They didn't even talk,'' she said. ``They just
pushed us apart. They put my mother in one room, me in another. And
my daughter, she was hardly dressed when they took her away.''
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of civilians like Kapustina remain trapped in
Grozny, once home to about 400,000 people. About 2,500 rebel
fighters are also dug in throughout the capital, fighting off
Russian troops from bunkers or from rooftops.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the trapped civilians are women, children, and the
elderly, too weak, poor or infirm to leave. Helpless victims in a
war both the Russian government and Chechen separatists claim to be
fighting in their name, they huddle for shelter in the city's
basements.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin says its four-month-old military campaign in
Chechnya is an ``antiterrorist operation'' aimed at protecting
Chechnya's civilians from ``bandits.'' The Chechen rebels say they
are fighting to liberate their republic from Russian occupation.
But human rights organizations have accused both sides of abusing
civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived over there,'' Kapustina said, pointing to the
smoldering remains of a five-story apartment building that was once
her home. ``There are a lot of us here. We have nowhere to go.''
</P>
<P>
   In reports released last week, the New York-based Human Rights
Watch, which has placed observers in the region, accused both
Russian troops and Chechen rebels of endangering the lives of
civilians throughout the breakaway region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chechen fighters have repeatedly beaten and threatened
civilians who have attempted to spare their villages from Russian
bombardment. They have also endangered civilians by taking
positions in areas that were heavily populated by civilians and
firing at Russian aircraft,'' the report, released Thursday, said.
</P>
<P>
   The group also criticized the Russian military for
indiscriminate bombing of civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how provocative Chechen conduct may be, it cannot
justify the targeting of civilian objects by Russian forces,'' the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   Human Rights Watch also accused Russian soldiers of raping
Chechen women. Citing witnesses, the report described rapes in
Shali, 16 miles southeast of Grozny, and Alkhan-Yurt, just
southwest of the capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both sides need to take the necessary steps to limit the
impact of their fighting on the civilian population, as required by
the rules of war,'' the group said.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian Emergencies Ministry announced Sunday that 500
civilians escaped Grozny safely over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Russian warplanes flew more than 100 bombing raids
across Chechnya as ground troops continued to battle separatist
rebels for control over the capital. Military officials said that
Russian forces had ``liberated'' residential areas, a railway
depot, a hospital and a factory near central Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   But rebel forces staged a surprise attack in Staraya Sunzha, a
suburb east of Grozny. There, a group of separatist fighters
attacked Russian troops in an early morning ambush that reportedly
killed eight soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Also Sunday, Russian troops found the body of Major General
Mikhail Malofeyev, who disappeared during fighting last week,
Kremlin spokesman Sergei Yastrzhembsky announced in Moscow.
Earlier, Chechen rebel leaders had said that Malofeyev had been
taken prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel leaders, meanwhile, denied claims made earlier by Russian
officials that Chechen President Aslan Maskhadov had been wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops marched into the breakaway region in late
September after Chechen militants made a series of raids against
villages in the neighboring Russian region of Dagestan. The Kremlin
also blamed Chechen separatists for a series of deadly bombings of
apartment houses in Moscow and two other cities that killed more
than 300 people. The rebels have repeatedly denied involvement in
the blasts.
</P>
<P>
   During the military operation's first three months, Russian
troops met little resistance and easily occupied Chechnya's flat
northern regions. Their advance, however, stalled last month when
they tried to take Grozny, where rebel forces had dug in. While
Russian forces have since been making slow progress, winning
control of the capital's outlying districts, the rebels have
stubbornly held their ground in the city center.
</P>
<P>
   Kapustina's neighborhood, in Grozny's northeastern outskirts, is
among those areas that the Kremlin said it had ``liberated'' on
Saturday. Russia's tricolor flag was hoisted as soldiers fired
their weapons into the air.
</P>
<P>
   But Kapustina said she feels anything but liberated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't left because I thought maybe they would bring her
back,'' she said. ``Without my little girl I have nothing to live
for.''
</P>
<P>
   Shalganov reported from Grozny. Whitmore wrote and reported from
Moscow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-00 2240EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000123.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-23 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4226 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-FOERSTNER-NYT &LR;      01-23 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-FOERSTNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE FOERSTNER, 91, AMANA FOUNDER AND ADVOCATE OF THE MICROWAVE
OVEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Foerstner, an Iowa entrepreneur who founded Amana
Appliances during the Depression and led it for 48 years while
introducing the microwave oven and the side-by-side refrigerator to
American homes, died Monday in Miami, near his winter home in Bal
Harbour, Fla. He was 91.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving school at 13 to work in his father's auto parts
business, Foerstner proved a natural salesman and promoter,
founding in 1934 what became Amana when he was challenged by a
local businessman to build a reliable commercial beverage cooler.
Over the years he built Amana into an internationally recognized
brand with the help of such Hollywood stars as Groucho Marx, Cecil
B. deMille and Gary Cooper hired to appear in its advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Foerstner started with two employees in a corner of a small
furniture shop, with production of beer coolers leading to the
making of refrigerators for butchers and then to frozen-food
lockers that farmers could use to store foods outside their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Its reputation for high quality drew on the meticulous work of
craftsmen and cabinetmakers in the Amana Colonies, a communitarian
German settlement founded in east central Iowa in the mid-1850s.
</P>
<P>
   Foerstner's original Electrical Equipment Co. was renamed Amana
Refrigeration when it was sold to the Amana Society in 1936 but he
remained as principal manager. In 1950 Foerstner and a group of
investors that included Howard Hall, an industrialist, bought Amana
back from the society. They in turn sold it in 1965 to the Raytheon
Co., which had developed the microwave oven and needed an
established appliance company to manufacture and market it.
</P>
<P>
   When Amana's Radarange came under inevitable attack as unsafe,
Foerstner ``took the media head on,'' an official said, in a
fervent defense that included bringing in a scientist from the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration who said he would be
willing to sit on a Radarange for a year.
</P>
<P>
   He continued to lead the company, which had long been the
world's leading producer of home freezers, until 1982, when he
retired as chairman.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Raytheon sold the company to Houston-based Goodman
Manufacturing, but refrigerators continue to be made at the plant
in Middle Amana, Iowa, across the street from the house where
Foerstner spent most of the year. On one occasion, he was the first
person on the scene when the plant caught fire.
</P>
<P>
   Foerstner was a demanding but generous man, paying the highest
wages in the area, the company official said, and was often found
at the plant in off-hours, dressed like a farmer. One of his
innovations was to sponsor a sales competition among dealers that
offered as prizes shares in a mutual fund, which Foerstner
described as ``an investment rather than a one-shot reward.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Hollywood stars he enlisted to promote Amana
products, Foerstner, who lived modestly, had associations with
Vince Lombardi, the football coach, as well as with Dwight D.
Eisenhower and other Washington notables, on at least one occasion
leading an Iowa contingent to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Foerstner is survived by a daughter, Joanne Meyer, of Middle
Amana and a son, Richard, of Iowa City. His wife, Nora, died in
1990.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
