<SLUG> BC-BKC-BIG-EAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG EAST IS IDEAL CRUCIBLE TO MOLD CHAMPION
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why not another national basketball champion from the Big East?
Why not two teams representing the conference on Final Four weekend
in Indianapolis? Halfway through this strange college basketball
season, neither one is a fanciful notion.
</P>
<P>
   The Big East has three teams as good as any in the nation:
Syracuse, Connecticut and St. John's. It has two more intent on
filling tournament brackets come March in Seton Hall and Miami. For
the most part, rosters throughout the conference blend young stars,
like Notre Dame's Troy Murphy and Rutgers' Dahntay Jones, with
seasoned senior performers.
</P>
<P>
   Just check out the No. 6 Orangemen Monday night against the
defending titleholder, eighth-ranked Connecticut. The reason
Syracuse is the only undefeated team in the top 25 is its threesome
of seniors: point guard Jason Hart, shot-blocker Etan Thomas and
forward Ryan Blackwell.
</P>
<P>
   What players hanging around for four years means is that seven
times this season a different Orangeman has led the team in
scoring. Against Pittsburgh last Wednesday, the freshman DeShaun
Williams, who was scoreless in the previous three games, scored a
career-high 23 points in an 82-72 victory. Syracuse, which is 15-0,
no longer has to live and die by its 2-3 zone defense; it now has a
confident and stifling man-to-man defense to employ.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing better than senior leadership,'' Coach Jim
Boeheim said. ``This is a more veteran team that has to play hard
and together. We won't blow anybody out. We get the ball to more
people. If you just throw zone, teams get a feel and can beat you.
We can do some different things.''
</P>
<P>
   At Connecticut, Coach Jim Calhoun clicks off similar strengths
of his team. In Kevin Freeman and Jake Voskuhl, he has inside
senior strength. In the junior Khalid El-Amin he has perhaps the
best player in the conference. They were the cornerstones of last
year's national championship.
</P>
<P>
   At 13-3, the Huskies still haven't discovered a replacement for
the departed Richard Hamilton and his instant scoring from any
place on the floor. But like Syracuse, Connecticut will only get
better over the next month of conference play.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   In a season in which the traditional power North Carolina has
lost four straight games, underclassmen-heavy West Coast teams like
Arizona and Stanford have a slippery hold near the top of the polls
and newcomers like Auburn try to show they are for real, the Big
East is perhaps the most reliable testing ground.
</P>
<P>
   How's this for balance? In 32 Big East games so far this season,
the home team has won only half of them, so there are no easy
games. In addition, unlike the helter-skelter-run-the-floor style
in the Pacific-10 or the bang-and-cut of the Big Ten, Big East
teams are harder to fit in one style of play. Notre Dame's
first-year coach, Matt Doherty, compares it to the diverse and
balanced Atlantic Coast Conference he played in alongside Michael
Jordan, Sam Perkins and Kenny Smith at North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``You tell me where you can go in and circle a victory,'' asked
Doherty, whose 12-7 Irish beat Connecticut on the Huskies' home
floor. ``Rutgers plays you physical. Syracuse has more long and
quick athletes. Connecticut is more pressing. You see a far wider
style of play, which is challenging to me as a coach.''
</P>
<P>
   It also is the perfect preparation for March, when 64 teams with
a variety of styles converge in the National Collegiate Athletic
Association tournament. Last year, Ohio State and Michigan State
made sure the Big Ten owned half the Final Four. When St. John's
met the Buckeyes in the South Regional final, the Red Storm needed
30 minutes to figure out the poised backcourt of Scoonie Penn and
Michael Redd, as well as the inside presence of the 6-foot-11-inch
shot-blocker Ken Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 19 Red Storm (12-4) lost again to No. 13 Ohio State on
Saturday at Madison Square Garden, but for nearly 37 minutes it was
the better team and nettled practically the same Final Four team.
The reason? Four days earlier, the Storm got beat by a Seton Hall
team remarkably similar to the Buckeyes.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates' freshman center, Samuel Dalembert, defended the
middle with 11 blocks _ the same number Johnson had Saturday. Their
senior backcourt of Shaheen Holloway and Rimas Kaukenas bombed from
the perimeter _ just as Penn and Redd did.
</P>
<P>
   Two tough losses in January mean St. John's will have learned by
March. And in Bootsy Thornton and Lavor Postell _ seniors, of
course _ St. John's has the right makeup to heed those lessons.
</P>
<P>
   When Miami Coach Leonard Hamilton was asked recently about
Syracuse's national title chances, he was really thinking about his
own 11-7 team _ winner of six of its last eight, including an
impressive 71-64 victory at Seton Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Big East Conference will test them,'' Hamilton said. ``If
they get through this league, they can go pretty far.''
</P>
<P>
   Four-year players. Brutal conference games. Grind it out or run
it up. Syracuse, Connecticut, even St. John's, are taking the right
road to Indianapolis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
