<SLUG> BC-HKN-STEVENS-ARREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' STEVENS IS ARRESTED IN DRUG-RELATED CASE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Kevin Stevens, a 34-year-old left wing who serves as
an alternate captain of the New York Rangers, was arrested in
Collinsville, Ill., early Sunday morning and charged with
soliciting a prostitute and possessing drug paraphernalia.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens was arrested at a motel hours after the Rangers' 4-1
victory over the Blues in St. Louis on Friday night, said Maj. Ed
Delmore, assistant chief of the Collinsville Police Department.
Collinsville is a St. Louis suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens remained in custody Sunday night and was being held
without bail, Delmore said. Bail was scheduled to be set Monday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives will also seek felony drug charges and other charges
on Monday, according to a news release issued by the Collinsville
police. According to Delmore, a date for Stevens' preliminary
hearing will be set Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our thoughts are with Kevin and his family at this time,''
Neil Smith, the team president and general manager, said in a
statement released by the Rangers. ``The New York Rangers
organization will fully support Kevin in any possible way.''
</P>
<P>
   The NHL and the NHL Players' Association issued a joint
statement that said Stevens had been placed under the supervision
of the substance abuse program run jointly by the league and the
union. Two program doctors are in charge of Stevens' care, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the police report, Stevens was arrested with a
prostitute in Collinsville after a disturbance at the motel had
been reported to the police.
</P>
<P>
   Crack cocaine was found on all of the room's occupants, said the
police, who indicated that Stevens had been smoking crack.
</P>
<P>
   The police said Stevens took a cab from a nightclub in Sauget,
Ill., to nearby East St. Louis, Ill., where the cab driver
contacted a prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   The police said the woman told them that Stevens was already
smoking crack when she got into the cab with him. Stevens gave her
$500, also bought $500 worth of crack on an East St. Louis street
corner, paid for material for a crack pipe for her and smoked crack
with her, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Pamela J. Velia, 27, of St. Louis; the cab driver,
Alfred Triplett, 50, of East St. Louis; and Darryl Crawford, 30, of
Lovejoy, Ill., are also being held without bail. They will be
charged Monday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stevens and Velia went to the motel room, the police said, where
they were joined by Crawford, whom police identified as a member of
a street gang. After Triplett created a disturbance at the door,
motel personnel called the police.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers left Stevens behind when they flew here Sunday
morning after recording their fifth straight victory on Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens is in his 13th season in the NHL. Twice in his career he
has scored more than 50 goals. This season, however, has been the
most frustrating one of his career. Stevens had been scratched four
consecutive games before Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to the lineup only because Adam Graves, the Rangers'
acting captain, flew to New York to be with his wife, Violet, and
their twin boys, who were born prematurely recently.
</P>
<P>
   In 38 games this season, Stevens has three goals and five
assists and a plus-minus rating of minus-7. The Rangers have been
trying to trade Stevens to a team for which he can play regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens is married with two children. His wife is expecting a
third child.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
