<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGSNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVALANCHE STRUGGLES IN CALIFORNIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was a lost weekend for the Colorado Avalanche,
who were 8-1-2 in their previous 11 games before arriving in
Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Anaheim Mighty Ducks tied Colorado 3-3 Friday, when
the Avalanche was outshot 19-1 in the final 15 minutes. Sunday
afternoon, Colorado lost 3-2 to drop its record to 1-3 against the
Los Angeles Kings this season.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado pulled goalie Marc Denis after he allowed three goals
in the first period. Two were on the power play. But it was not
enough, even though the Avs had four straight power-play
opportunities midway through the game and scored twice in the final
two periods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our slow start definitely cost us two points,'' Colorado coach
Bob Hartley said. ``We are mature enough and have enough leaders on
this team to recognize that we did not have a very good first
period.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado, with 55 points, still has a wide lead in the Northwest
Division and should become the first team since 1975 to win six
consecutive division titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have so many skill players you can never let up,'' Kings
coach Andy Murray said. ``You have to keep after them all the time
or they will blow by you. We just have to do it without so many
penalties.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick whistles: The Kings are 14-4-3 when they score first....
With Jozef Stumpel and Glen Murray returning, the Kings are missing
just Donald Audette from their first two lines on opening night.
Audette still is nursing a sprained left ankle and is hoping to
return by the end of the week. Without their top players, the Kings
power play has suffered, even though it is ranked seventh in the
league with a 18.3conversion rate. ``You need to get all six of
your forwards from the first two lines to get the consistency you
need,'' said assistant Dave Tippett, who works with the team's
power play. ``We're in better shape now.''
</P>
<P>
   Stumpel, who has missed most of the past 10 weeks with abdominal
and knee injuries, wants to stay healthy the rest of the season.
``I've just never been able to get going all year,'' he said. ``In
the first month, everything looked so great for us. There is no
reason we can't have that again.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Dave Rein scored the Avs' second goal, his seventh of the
season. He had six all last year. ... The Kings are off today but
will practice Tuesday morning at their new facility in El Segundo
before leaving for Dallas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
