<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-23 23:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4260 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-TITANS-McNAIR-HNS     01-23 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS-McNAIR-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ Tennessee Titans quarterback Steve McNair has
been suffering from a case of turf toe that is so severe he has
been forced to wear a plastic boot to immobilize it and protect it
during the week.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the swollen big toe on McNair's left foot did not keep him
from kicking the playoff life out of Jacksonville on Sunday by
running for two touchdowns and throwing for another in Tennessee's
33-14 victory, which sent the Titans to Super Bowl XXXIV in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea behind Steve wearing the boot was to get him ready to
play today,'' coach Jeff Fisher said after the Titans secured their
first appearance in a Super Bowl. ``What a courageous performance.
Steve's so tough, he plays when most quarterbacks would sit out.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair completed 14 of 23 passes for 112 yards, including a
nine-yard touchdown pass to Yancey Thigpen. He was sacked once and
intercepted once.
</P>
<P>
   McNair did more damage to the Jaguars' defense with his running.
He ran nine times for a team-high 91 yards and scored twice on
one-yard sneaks. He had runs of 19 and 51 yards, the latter setting
up the touchdown that put the Titans ahead 33-14.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to sit out this game for anything, because this
is something I've dreamed about and worked hard for,'' McNair said.
``I wasn't going to let a chance like this slip away. I was ready
to face the consequences of how bad my toe was going to hurt after
the game, and right now it hurts good.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair, who came to the then-Houston Oilers from Alcorn State in
1995 as the team's No. 1 draft choice, underwent back surgery early
in the season and has seldom played without injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times last week, Steve couldn't even touch his toe without
it killing him,'' Titans tight end Frank Wycheck said. ``For him to
take the shots he took and make those kinds of plays shows what a
true warrior he is. He's an unbelievable leader, and we follow
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Titans are following McNair to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say to dare McNair, and he was going to do whatever he
could to make sure we won this game,'' Titans strong safety Blaine
Bishop said. ``People are going to have to start tackling him like
he's a tailback and not a quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's victory over the Jaguars improved his record as a
starter this season to 11-2. In three playoff games, he has thrown
for 76, 112 and 112 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve's all about winning, not statistics,'' Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   Added guard Bruce Matthews: ``Steve just sucks it up. He doesn't
care what the media thinks about him, and he doesn't care about
what his passer rating is. All he cares about is winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might not be pretty, but he's finding ways to make plays.
He's a lineman's best friend. I can't tell you how many times he's
saved me when I've been beat on a pass rush.''
</P>
<P>
   At times during the first half, McNair struggled. He seemed
confused by Jacksonville's strategy of reading and holding at the
line rather than penetrating and trying to sack him. Jaguars
defensive coordinator Dom Capers didn't want McNair to hurt his
team with his running and was confident McNair couldn't find his
receivers downfield.
</P>
<P>
   When McNair couldn't locate a receiver, he either dumped off the
ball or tucked it in and took off. He was dangerous either way.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the reason we won,'' Titans linebacker Eddie Robinson
said. ``Steve made the big plays today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have another African-American quarterback from the SWAC
going to the Super Bowl _ a la Doug Williams. Hopefully, he'll have
the same results.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, now the coach at Grambling State, his alma mater, led
the Washington Redskins to their third Super Bowl victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of what numbers I put up, we're winning, and that's
all that matters,'' McNair said. ``Our goal is to run the ball and
move the chains. Now we've got one goal left. As long as we're
going to the Super Bowl, we might as well win it.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-23-00 2302EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000123.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-23 23:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4268 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-TITANS-VIDEO-HNS &LR;      01-23 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS-VIDEO-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ Executives on Music Row in Nashville, Tenn.,
would not even consider listening to Uh Oh, The Jaguars Super Bowl
Song, but the Tennessee Titans had no choice but to sit through the
rap video at a team meeting Saturday night.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before coach Jeff Fisher dismissed his players from their
regular meeting the night before Sunday's AFC Championship Game,
the lights went out, and the music came on. The Titans saw Jaguars
defensive tackle Gary Walker, receiver Keenan McCardell, offensive
tackle Leon Searcy, receiver Jimmy Smith and cornerback Fernando
Bryant rapping their way to Super Bowl XXXIV in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``When coach played it, I couldn't believe it,'' Titans middle
linebacker Barron Wortham said after Tennessee's 33-14 victory over
Jacksonville. ``We were kind of shocked that they'd do something so
arrogant.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the video was over, there was total silence in the room.
The guys took it to heart. If you're a man and you get slapped in
the face, you strike back. And we did. That video was a big factor
in our mental approach to this game. Hey, that video's no good.
They should throw it in the trash and let BFI pick it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Nashville isn't exactly a rap music kind of town, so no wonder
news traveled slowly. The Jaguars video was made in November and
wasn't supposed to be released unless they reached the Super Bowl,
but a radio station in Jacksonville began playing it the week
before the divisional playoff game against Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins were furious that the Jaguars could be so
presumptuous, but they failed to back it up during Jacksonville's
62-7 victory. The Titans hadn't heard anything about the video, and
the players thought the Jaguars recorded it last week before
Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Bruce Matthews, a 17-year veteran, is an old rock 'n'
roller who loves Elvis and the Beatles. Matthews paid particular
attention to the performance of Walker, who left the Titans after
last season and signed with the Jaguars as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I'm no music expert, but that video was horrible,
especially Walker's part,'' Matthews said. ``He should definitely
stick to football. I liked the Bears' Super Bowl Shuffle (1985),
but this one was real cheesy. It took some nerve for the Jaguars to
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   When informed that the Jaguars made the video in November and
that it began playing in Jacksonville two weeks ago _ not the week
before the Tennessee game _ Matthews smiled and said, ``Really?
Huh. I hadn't heard anything about it, but I'm not a real big fan
of rap music.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, over the years, I've become a little jaded to
motivational tools, but I have to admit this one piqued my
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside linebacker Joe Bowden was the only player in the
Tennessee dressing room who had anything remotely positive to say
about the video.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to admit that I liked the video,'' he said. ``It had a
nice beat. It had me bobbing my head a few times.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what, though? That video definitely showed their lack
of respect for us. As for Walker, he's a better player than he is a
rapper. He should keep the day job.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher had someone tape the video when it was shown on Jaguars
coach Tom Coughlin's television show. When asked about the
motivational tactic, Fisher had a sly smile on his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a coach, you do different things at different times to
prepare your players,'' he said. ``I thought the team meeting the
night before the game would be a good time to show the players the
Jaguars' mindset, how confident Jacksonville was going into this
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the rivalry between these AFC Central foes grows more
bitter by the season, the Titans agreed that making a Super Bowl
video during the season and then allowing it to be released in the
playoffs was rather typical of such an arrogant team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, they're arrogant,'' Matthews said. ``But when you're a
winner, you can't help but be arrogant.''
</P>
<P>
   The Titans are 16-3 and on their way to their first Super Bowl,
so they must be arrogant, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, yeah, I guess you could say we're getting there,''
Matthews said.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
