<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-23 23:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4286 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     01-23 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ On the first play from scrimmage Sunday, the
Tennessee Titans were flagged for delay of game, an almost
inconceivable penalty _ but exactly the kind of dumb mistake we
grew used to expecting from the Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   Ditto rookie Jevon Kearse's stunningly ill-advised attempted
lateral early in the fourth quarter, with Tennessee having just
recovered a Jacksonville fumble deep in Jaguars territory, a
turnover that surely would have proved a fatal blow for the home
team.
</P>
<P>
   But the Titans, we can say for certain now, are not the Oilers.
What's in a name? Apparently, everything. We first suspected as
much the afternoon of the magical finish against Buffalo, of all
people, and the feeling grew when the Titans rallied past the
favored Colts in Indianapolis. This represents inarguable,
unequivocal confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   Four lost fumbles and two Mark Brunell interceptions deep-sixed
the uptight Jaguars. They stumbled, bumbled, fumbled and ultimately
crumbled, reeling into an angst-filled offseason by losing to a
franchise that had, for most of its 37 seasons in Texas _ and for
the 39 its helmet logo was the oil derrick _ established the
highest imaginable standards for creative stupidity.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention buzzard's luck.
</P>
<P>
   The simple folk of Nashville have no idea, do they? Heck, not
more than a year ago, Eddie George noted, they were merrily
cheering for the opposing team the day after Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Vikings were going to the playoffs,'' George said,
remembering the franchise's final game as the Oilers, played at
Vanderbilt Stadium. ``It was pretty strange. But that's all behind
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Lots of things are behind them, from the Steel Curtain to
Stagger Lee to Buddy Ryan's trying to slap Kevin Gilbride silly.
</P>
<P>
   For Super Bowl-bound Tennessee, so cruelly uprooted from Houston
when owner Bud Adams was rebuffed in his efforts to force the city
to give him a new stadium, the old demons have been exorcised.
While the Titans didn't play the perfect AFC Championship Game, as
the aforementioned gaffes plus a handful of other goofs would
suggest, they picked the Jaguars' pockets at the most opportune
moments.
</P>
<P>
   They made the plays Jacksonville couldn't and ultimately made
some convincing history 33-14, becoming the first team to complete
a single-season trifecta on an opponent's field. Never mind that
the Titans lost both valued free safety Marcus Robertson and
marquee receiver Yancey Thigpen to a broken ankle and a broken
foot, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   As the Oilers, Bud's bunglers seemed doggedly destined to lose
in the end. Reincarnated as the Titans, they are, pure and simple,
a team of destiny.
</P>
<P>
   The Jags went 15-0 vs. everybody else but 0-3 vs. the Titans,
who march on Atlanta as a wild card by definition only. Nothing is
fluky about their 16-3 record, which includes a Halloween defeat
of, uh-huh, the NFC champion Rams, their fellow nomads from St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe 75,206 people in Alltel Stadium couldn't believe it had
happened to their hexed heroes again, but the Titans fully assumed
they would prevail. Coach Jeff Fisher, who prides himself on
preparing his charges for every fathomable scenario, had even
rehearsed their receiving the Lamar Hunt Trophy afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt, the oilman owner of the Kansas City Chiefs, was here to
hand over his namesake piece of hardware to Adams, whose franchise
won the first two titles in the league _ the AFL _ that he and Hunt
founded in 1959 but, ironically, would be the last of its original
members to reach the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   At 77, Adams is only slightly older than his left guard, 17-year
veteran Bruce Matthews, who admitted he has grown tired of
answering the same tired questions for what feels like a lifetime.
Finally Sunday, Matthews had something fresh to say in reply.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to the Super Bowl,'' he said. ``I'm going to the
Super Bowl. Hey, I like the sound of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Titans came to town convinced of their superiority, a
mindset the Oilers never quite mastered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Confidence was a big factor in our favor,'' said defensive
coordinator Gregg Williams, whose big halftime adjustment was to
ask his charges to get themselves under control and ``stop trying
to blow up'' a Jaguar on every tackle.
</P>
<P>
   So ol' Bud heads off to the NFL's big hoedown, feeling
vindicated, no doubt. We thought (and perhaps hoped) hell, and
Atlanta, would freeze over before that would transpire. Well, as it
happens, Atlanta was socked hard by an ice storm over the weekend,
leaving thousands without power, and snow is in the forecast for
later in the week.
</P>
<P>
   Not that winter's intrusion on America's party will matter to
the Titans, especially to the happy handful of long-suffering,
one-time Oilers in their midst. For them, the next stop is heaven.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
