<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-AUSTRALIAN-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGASSI IN QUARTERFINALS, AND NOW SAMPRAS LOOMS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE, Australia _ If you wanted to understand what Sunday's
fourth-round match against Andre Agassi meant to Mark
Philippoussis, you did not need to look at the capacity crowd
surrounding and supporting him or the intensity with which he and
Agassi exchanged shots that were much closer to blows.
</P>
<P>
   All you needed to do was look at the condition of his racket
just moments after the end of the second set. Philippoussis had
already lost the first, and now he had gone down two sets to love
after surrendering a 4-1 lead in the tiebreaker. While Agassi
clenched his fist in the direction of his friends Steffi Graf, Brad
Gilbert and Gil Reyes, Philippoussis hurled the tool of his
lucrative trade at the Rebound Ace surface. Only it did not rebound
all that much. Instead, it hit the ground with a frame-cracking
crunch and lay there looking like road kill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy can make a racket look like a toothpick, you know,''
Agassi said. ``I was just thinking, `I'm glad I'm not the
racket.'''
</P>
<P>
   It is rare that Philippoussis shows much emotion in public,
either in interviews or on the court. Although his 6-foot-4-inch,
195-pound frame makes him look like a heavy, he does not have a
temper to match. But this was an encounter of rare quality and
significance to the Australian, who grew up in Melbourne and had
raised his standard of play to high levels in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   His problem was and remains that Agassi appears to be rising,
too, despite his coming 30th birthday and despite all the energy
and adrenaline he expended during his remarkable 1999 season.
Philippoussis managed to win the third set, as Agassi finally began
making a few unforced errors and double faults, but the No.
1-seeded player got his quick hands back around the match for good
to win, 6-4, 7-6 (4), 5-7, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is 29 years old and is playing the best tennis of his life;
it's quite incredible,'' Philippoussis said. ``He is the cleanest
hitter of the ball of any person I have played. He is not really a
nice player to meet early on in tournaments.''
</P>
<P>
   This tournament, the year's first Grand Slam event, is entering
its second week, and Agassi and Pete Sampras are just one victory
apiece away from meeting in a semifinal that could end up feeling
more like a final.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras also advanced to the quarterfinals in four sets Sunday,
defeating Slava Dosedel, a part-time actor and full-time Czech,
6-1, 6-2, 3-6, 6-1. Sampras was considerably sharper than in his
five-set victory over Wayne Black in the third round. Although
statistics are an overused commodity in tennis, the fact that
Sampras managed to hit 68 percent of his first serves into play was
a telling reflection of his form on courts he considers too quick
for comfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it woke me up a touch,'' Sampras said of his third-round
scare. ``I don't like to be down two sets and be woken up, but I
realized that my game isn't quite where I want it to be, playing
against Black. Today, I felt a little bit better out there, a
little more comfortable, and that's all you can ask for the second
week. This is where I raise the level, and I hope it happens this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Two seeded players _ Tim Henman of Britain and Mary Pierce of
France and Florida _ proved incapable of raising their level enough
to make it to the second week. Henman, the No. 11 seed who has
struggled lately, was beaten in five wind-swept sets by Chris
Woodruff, a former NCAA singles champion from Tennessee. Pierce,
the women's No. 4-seeded player who won this tournament in 1995,
was beaten by Ai Sugiyama of Japan, 7-5, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   The victories put Woodruff and Sugiyama in their first Grand
Slam quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   The first man into the quarterfinals was Hicham Arazi of
Morocco, who defeated France's Nicolas Escude in a match that was
much more eye catching than its 6-4, 6-3, 7-6 (7) score line.
Another Moroccan, Younes el-Aynaoui, reached the fourth round by
completing a rain-delayed five-set victory over Spain's rising Juan
Carlos Ferrero.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
