<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-VOUCHERS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL VOUCHER ISSUE COULD GAIN GROUND IN KANSAS LEGISLATURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JIM SULLINGER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPEKA, Kan. _ The debate over state-funded private school
vouchers has changed this year, and some believe the new focus
might be gaining ground in the Kansas Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Past proposals, mainly offered by state Rep. Kay O'Connor of
Olathe, have gone nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, O'Connor prodded a voucher bill out of the
House Education Committee only to see it crushed 98-23 on the House
floor. The issue has never been considered by the full Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But times have changed.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, a House majority leader is proposing a
limited ``research project'' on vouchers as part of an overall
education improvement package. State Rep. Kent Glasscock, the
majority leader, is co-sponsoring the bill with the chairman of the
House Education Committee, state Rep. Ralph Tanner, a Baldwin City
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, Barbara Lawrence, a Wichita Republican who is
chairwoman of the Senate Education Committee, is sponsoring a bill
to start a pilot project on vouchers. A hearing on the measure is
scheduled for Tuesday in her committee.
</P>
<P>
   Under voucher programs, students receive funds that can be used
to pay tuition at the private school of their choice.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Grant, a lobbyist for the Kansas chapter of the National
Education Association, said he had never seen this much support
among legislative leaders for a voucher plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a little more steam this year but not enough,
at least currently, to get it out of the House or Senate
committees,'' Grant said.
</P>
<P>
   Grant said he was worried that the Glasscock-Tanner legislation
could capture a lot more votes than O'Connor's ever did.
</P>
<P>
   Glasscock, a voucher opponent, said some of his friends are
wondering if he's lost his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``While school choice has been hotly debated around the country,
as far as we can tell there hasn't been a controlled research
project anywhere that answers the question: Is there a positive
correlation between school choice and student learning?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Glasscock and Tanner want Kansas to do the first definitive
study, something they believe could have national significance.
</P>
<P>
   Their idea is to give state vouchers to one group of
economically disadvantaged students and then track their academic
progress over several years. A control group from the same area
would be identified and tracked through the public school system.
At the end of the study, their academic progress would be compared.
</P>
<P>
   Students taking part would have to be eligible for
government-subsidized lunches.
</P>
<P>
   Glasscock said the number of students involved and how the
evaluation would be conducted would be left up to researchers. His
proposal only directs the State Department of Education to find a
reputable researcher to do the project. He's not certain, at this
time, how much such a study would cost.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Bill 295, Lawrence's bill, would allow 100 pupils to
receive vouchers in four school districts _ Kansas City, Kan.,
Wichita, Garden City and Topeka _ and their academic progress would
be monitored each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps we owe it to our children to have the courage to ask
the question and find the answer,'' Glasscock said.
</P>
<P>
   He expects major opposition from public school organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Tallman, an assistant executive director for advocacy at
the Kansas Association of School Boards, won't disappoint him.
</P>
<P>
   Tallman said adopting a research or pilot program would only be
the first step toward an eventual full-fledged voucher program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the Legislature adopts this idea, they're not going to
back away from it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tallman said a study wasn't necessary because many private
schools take the same tests as public schools and comparisons could
be made from the results.
</P>
<P>
   He added that any such study won't address the underlying
problem with vouchers _ public funds being used to send students to
private schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact you have someone like Kent Glasscock saying, `Let's
study it,' will change the complexion of the debate,'' Tallman
said. ``Now, we'll be portrayed as being against gaining
knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, who directs a pro-voucher organization called Parents
in Control, said interest in vouchers is picking up nationally. She
said there are more than 75 voucher programs nationwide using
private funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those involve 50,000 students with another 1.25 million on
waiting lists,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor said she is backing the current efforts in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the fact that we're having this discussion pleases me,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Glasscock acknowledged that passage of either bill would be an
uphill battle.
</P>
<P>
   He said his legislation won't be ready for introduction in the
House for another couple of weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
