<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORBES ACCUSES BUSH OF SABOTAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY KRIS MAYES  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(AMES, Iowa) - With voting in the Iowa caucuses a day away, the
skirmishing between the Republican presidential hopefuls
intensified Sunday as Steve Forbes accused front-runner George W.
Bush of last-minute political sabotage.
</P>
<P>
   The Forbes campaign accused the Bush campaign of using a new
method of negative campaigning, a charge the Bush camp denied.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Leadership Council, a group of moderates who
support abortion rights, are calling Forbes supporters through a
Phoenix-based telecommunications company and asking them whether
they disapprove of Forbes' television ads in Iowa. If they answer
with anything that resembles an affirmative, the call is switched
to the Forbes campaign headquarters in Iowa, Forbes charged on
Sunday, Jan. 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a pro-abortion, liberal organization that is
supporting George Bush, and then they go and do a job on me,''
Forbes said at a campaign stop in central Iowa. ``I think that
underscores that we are a threat for the political establishment.
It says it all that they have to do this on the QT.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Leadership Council has run a series of television
ads in Iowa and New Hampshire accusing Forbes of negative
campaigning. The group is made up largely of Bush financial backers
and includes several members of Bush's ``Pioneers,'' the group of
financial donors who have helped Bush raise $100,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days in Iowa, reporters and Forbes supporters have
been pushing Bush to clarify his stand on abortion rights, and he
has been making statements opposing them. Many observers of the
campaign believe that Bush has moved further to the right in his
public statements on the issue than he is comfortable with.
</P>
<P>
   John McCain has also recently complained about negative tactics
by Bush, and Forbes took the opportunity to associate himself with
the Arizona senator, saying, ``The Bush campaign has used other
outsiders to attack me and John McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Bush denied any part in the negative telephone
campaigning, saying the Texas governor has focused his efforts on a
get-out-the-vote effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's categorically not true,'' said Brian Jones, a Bush
spokesman. ``Our phone banks are calling people to inform them of
where their caucus locations are and to remind them to come out and
support the governor.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the close ties between the Bush campaign and
the Republican Leadership Council, Jones said, ``I'm not aware of
what the RLC is doing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Forbes aides pressed their point, saying the Bush campaign
is desperately trying to suppress what is expected to be a muscular
turnout for Forbes today, Jan. 24.
</P>
<P>
   The Forbes team produced a pamphlet from the Phoenix-based
political firm. It contained an endorsement from Karl Rove, Bush's
campaign chairman, and boasts of having the Republican Leadership
Council as a client. The company specializes in patch-through
calls, according to the Forbes campaign, and was responsible for
making phone calls on behalf of Bob Dole's 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the age of modern communications there is much that can be
done, and they are doing it,'' said Bill Dal Col, Forbes' campaign
manager.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, some Bush supporters say the Forbes
campaign is doing negative calling of its own. Dal Col acknowledged
the campaign was calling Bush supporters in Iowa to try to sway
them at the 11th hour on four issues: taxes, education, Social
Security and abortion.
</P>
<P>
   One resident who said he received such a call, Brad Trow, a Bush
precinct leader, said he considered the appeal ``negative
calling.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the caller identified himself as a Forbes campaign
representative and said Bush had broken a pledge not to raise taxes
in Texas. ``They are not pushing their candidate, they are trying
to push negative information about other candidates,'' Trow said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's phone-call campaign could hurt Forbes, who is expected to
place second in the Iowa caucuses to Bush's first place. A Research
2000 survey of 311 likely GOP voters earlier this week had Bush at
43 percent, Forbes with 25 percent and Alan Keyes with 9 percent.
McCain and Gary Bauer had 7 percent each. The poll had a margin of
error of plus or minus 5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Dal Col acknowledged that last-minute dog-fighting is the norm
for the Iowa caucuses, but insisted that it has never been
perpetrated by a third party. He vowed to amend a recent complaint
he had filed with the Federal Elections Commission about the
Republican Leadership Council television ads against Forbes to
include the phone-call campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``However this campaign turns out, this is going to be the start
of a fund-raising investigation not unlike the Democrats had in
1996,'' Dal Col said. ``The questions will be raised, `Who was it,
where did the money come from? Who made the calls?' ''
</P>
<P>
   At a Forbes campaign stop in Waterloo, several undecided voters
expressed their dissatisfaction with the growing bitterness between
the campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like little kids tattling on each other,'' Claudia
Martin of Cedar Falls said. ``After a while, you start to tune it
out.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Associated Press contributed to this article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
