A4364 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w BC-IOWA-CAUCUSES-KAN &LR;      01-23 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-CAUCUSES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOWA CAUCUSES MORE ABOUT EXPECTATIONS THAN OUTCOMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Ah, the incredible clout of the Iowa
presidential caucus. Without it, there'd have been no President
Muskie, no President Gephardt, no President Harkin.
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe the small Midwestern state falls a bit short in the
game of picking winners. But presidential nominees Walter Mondale,
Gerald Ford and Bob Dole did survive to the general election in
large part by virtue of their Iowa victories.
</P>
<P>
   And surprising second-place finishes in the state propelled
George McGovern and Ronald Reagan to bigger things. Jimmy Carter
came from near anonymity in his close loss to ``undecided'' to
charge ahead of more prominent politicians in 1976 on his way to
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Today in tiny Iowa _ population less than 3 million in a nation
of more than 275 million _ perhaps 100,000 voters will gather for
an hour or three in school cafeterias and church basements to kick
off America's race to November.
</P>
<P>
   One in three caucus voters will have seen a White House wannabe
in person during the last four months, scholars say.
</P>
<P>
   In the voters' choices, the infancy of a prolonged process of
picking the state's paltry number of delegates to the Republican
and Democratic national conventions, candidates will find varying
measures of victory. Others likely will be winnowed out.
</P>
<P>
   Much will turn not on who wins, but on how much. Historically
reliable polls suggest Texas Gov. George W. Bush will top the
Republican field and Vice President Al Gore will win among
Democrats. Bush and Gore concur. So do those predicted to run
behind them.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the focus among politicians and pundits is whether
Steve Forbes, for instance, can do better than the 18 percent he
scored in an August straw poll of Republicans. Or whether former
Sen. Bill Bradley can meet the 31 percent target the New Jersey
Democrat has set for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like sports contests because there's a winner,'' said Hugh
Winebrenner, a Drake University professor who studies the caucuses.
``In politics, you can lose when you win and win when you lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, it's all about expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years have passed since the expectations mattered so
much. In 1996, President Clinton was unopposed in the Democratic
race. In 1992, favorite son Sen. Tom Harkin of Iowa robbed the
Democratic contest of any meaning and President George Bush had the
GOP race to himself. So not since 1988 _ when the elder Bush and
Michael Dukakis finished embarrassing but surmountable thirds _
have both party races mattered.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the attention and the open nature of this year's
races, it could bring in more people,'' said Donn Stanley, Iowa's
deputy secretary of state. ``But if the weather's bad, you can have
trouble getting people out on a Monday night.''
</P>
<P>
   Typical turnout is one in 18 of the state's registered voters,
as opposed to the 70 percent that usually show for Iowa's general
elections. So few come partly because going to a caucus is not as
simple, or as quick, as simply voting.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the state doesn't run the election. Political
parties do. And the rules for each are different.
</P>
<P>
   At 2,131 precincts across Iowa's 99 counties, Republicans will
file in to select temporary caucus chairmen. Voters can register,
even switch party allegiances, on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   Then they'll agree on rules for the caucus. Next, they'll select
delegates to their county conventions. Months later, those
delegates will select delegates to district and state conventions,
who will, in turn, choose delegates to the national convention.
</P>
<P>
   The caucus voters also will fill out ballots marking their
presidential preferences. It's all for show, but those are the
numbers reported to party headquarters tonight, and that will trim
the field of candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats meet in much the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Their votes on president, however, are not by secret ballot.
Instead, the participants will declare their preferences publicly
with a show of hands or by standing in Gore and Bradley clumps. If
one group makes up less than 15 percent of the caucus, the process
is repeated. If, say, Bradley supporters can't gather more than 10
out of a caucus of 100, their numbers are called into Des Moines as
undecided.
</P>
<P>
   At Democratic and Republican caucuses, voters also will chew
over planks to party platforms. With 30 to 700 people at any
caucus, the discussions can run long or short.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa Citizens Action Network, a self-styled consumer group,
plans to send 700 persons to nearly as many caucuses to insist on
``comprehensive campaign finance reform,'' although the group
doesn't say what reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make our politicians and elected officials know
that this is something people care about,'' said Betty Ahrens, the
group's program director. ``The caucuses give us a forum.''
</P>
<P>
   Some critics claim that a campaign season that begins with
overwhelmingly white Iowa and New Hampshire overlooks much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long time into the process where you have people who
are black and brown having much influence,'' said Ron Walters, who
was a senior adviser in Jesse Jackson's two runs at the presidency.
``This is a state that doesn't reflect the demographics of the
country. That means issues of race get left out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
