<HEADER>
A4371 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-TITANS-HNS &LR;      01-23 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OILERS-TURNED-TITANS SUPER BOWL-BOUND 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID BARRON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
HOUSTON _ If you laughed or cried in good times and bad with a pro
football team that for 37 seasons was known as the Houston Oilers,
the team's coach has a message for you.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We're Super Bowl-bound,'' Jeff Fisher said Sunday afternoon.
``Please come with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher and his team will make their long-awaited trek to Atlanta
for Sunday's Super Bowl XXXIV against the St. Louis Rams in the
guise of the Tennessee Titans, the corporate name of the NFL
franchise that owner K.S. ``Bud'' Adams after the 1996 season moved
from Houston to Memphis and then to Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   But for thousands of Houston football fans who watched the
American Football Conference Championship Game at home or who
gathered with friends at sports bars around the city, under the
hide of the Tennessee Titans beats the heart of the Houston Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   Only this time, the Titans didn't falter on the verge of
greatness. For the first time in four tries dating to the days of
the old American Football League, the franchise was victorious in a
championship game with a Super Bowl berth on the line, beating the
Jacksonville Jaguars 33-14 for the AFC title.
</P>
<P>
   They finally kicked in the door, and their reward is a date with
the Rams in Super Bowl XXXIV.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about time,'' Adams said while accepting the AFC
championship trophy. ``I'm getting pretty old. I didn't want to go
to the Super Bowl in a wheelchair.''
</P>
<P>
   During the team's days as the Oilers, Adams and Houston fans had
become accustomed to disappointment. After winning AFL
championships in 1960 and '61, Houston lost to the Dallas Texans in
the 1962 AFL Championship Game, to the Oakland Raiders in the 1967
AFL Championship Game and to the Pittsburgh Steelers in the 1978
and 1979 AFC title games. In each of the last three losses they
fell one game short of the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the ultimate disappointment _ a landmark January 1993
loss to the Buffalo Bills in the biggest choke in NFL playoff
history _ and what fans viewed as the ultimate betrayal _ Adams'
move to Tennessee when he was unable to obtain the backing of
then-Mayor Bob Lanier for a new stadium in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday against the Jaguars, the Titans were as ruthlessly
efficient in the second half as the Oilers were haphazardly
wretched in the second half of that memorable loss to the Bills.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee rallied from a 14-10 deficit with 16 points in 4{
minutes of the second half _ a one-yard touchdown run by
quarterback Steve McNair, a safety and an 80-yard return of the
ensuing free kick by Derrick Mason. McNair, who threw a nine-yard
pass to Yancey Thigpen for the Titans' first TD, later added a
second one-yard scoring run.
</P>
<P>
   Even as a standing-room-only crowd at the SRO sports bar in West
Houston cheered the Titans' comeback, a few fans couldn't help but
think about what might have been had the Oilers not moved to
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel so bad that they're not here, because if they were we'd
have a Super Bowl team,'' said Todd Mason, who wore an Oilers
replica McNair jersey. ``I hope they win the Super Bowl. I really
do. I'd like them to be here, but money talks these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost my voice screaming, and I'm going to be here for them
again next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the sting over the Oilers' departure may have been
blunted by the impending arrival of a new NFL franchise, owned by
local businessman Bob McNair, that will begin play in a new stadium
for the 2002 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bud was asking for $100 million, and what is McNair forking
over _ about a billion?'' said fan Bill Clark, who watched the game
at Dave and Buster's on Richmond Avenue. ``It doesn't seem quite as
stinky as it did a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm all for the Titans. I'm sure I'll be a total Texans fan or
whatever when that team starts here, but I love the Titans now.''
</P>
<P>
   At the SRO-OT Sports Bar and Grill in North Houston, the packed
house cheered enthusiastically when the CBS cameras focused on such
former Houston favorites as offensive lineman Bruce Matthews and
booed lustily when Adams was on camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bittersweet, because this is supposed to be Houston's
celebration,'' Tara Davis said. ``The city went through so much
with that team, and to see them finally get to the top is great,
but there is supposed to be a big welcoming party at
Intercontinental tonight, not in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is supposed to be a parade downtown after the Super Bowl
like we had for the Rockets and Comets, not some Grand Ole Opry
hoedown.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pulling for the guys, not the owner,'' said fan Bruce
Myers, who gleefully participated in a mock fund-raiser during the
game to raise money for a replacement hairpiece for Adams. ``The
guys on the team that have always put their heart into it like
Matthews, (Blaine) Bishop those guys. But not the owner.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all fans were so anti-Adams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a business decision, and that you have to understand,''
said Ronnie Adams, who is not related to the Titans owner. ``I can
separate the business from the spectator part. I hated to see them
leave, but the team's leaving didn't stop me from rooting for them.
So if they win it all, it won't be the same as if they were here,
but I'll pull for them, and I'll be happy for them if they win
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Titans general manager Floyd Reese, who came to Houston as an
assistant coach in 1986 before rising through the ranks, said the
team is glad to embrace fans from any locale.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that we've got a lot of fans in Houston,''
Reese said in the Titans' locker room in Jacksonville. ``It
wouldn't matter if they were from Houston or Juneau, Alaska; we
love them. We're happy for the fans in Houston, too.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Fisher. Even though the AFC championship trophy will bear
the name of the Tennessee Titans, Fisher thinks there will be
enough glory for Houston fans to share as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I followed Luv Ya Blue (the nickname for the Bum
Phillips-coached Oilers of the late 1970s and 1980),'' Fisher said.
``The team came so close so many times, and a lot of people in
Houston are pulling for us. We left behind a legacy, and our fans
in Houston deserve to enjoy this with us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Staff writers John McClain, MK Bower and Jerome Solomon contributed
to this report.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
