<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-HOPE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARNEVIK WINS HOPE TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY MORGAN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERMUDA DUNES, Calif. _ Jesper Parnevik often has been regarded
as one of the PGA Tour's most-unusual characters, a reputation
earned from the upturned bill on his cap to eating volcanic ash and
wearing unusual golf outfits.
</P>
<P>
   But there is nothing unusual about his game. Parnevik not only
is a top international player and a two-time member of the European
Ryder Cup team, but he's also a three-time winner in the U.S. His
latest victory occurred Sunday at Bermuda Dunes Country Club, when
he outlasted Rory Sabbatini to win the $3 million Bob Hope Classic.
</P>
<P>
   The 34-year-old Swede came from three shots down with a 6-under
65 to defeat Sabbatini for the first-place check of $540,000.
Sabbatini, a second-year touring pro who also let a lead slip away
in last year's Bell South Classic in Atlanta, won $324,000 for his
68 and solo second-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion David Duval, expected to make a final-round
push like last year, when he shot a 59 at the Arnold Palmer Course
at PGA West, instead tied Hal Sutton for fifth place.
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik, who had a 64 at Bermuda Dunes on Sunday, finally
passed Sabbatini with a 15-foot birdie on the par-4 11th hole, and
then it came down to who would falter first down the stretch. It
wasn't the best golf, but it did have its share of drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little more interesting than I wanted,'' Parnevik
said. ``That's just the way I do things, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabbatini birdied five of his first nine holes and had a
two-stroke lead on Parnevik at the turn when his driver
</P>
<P>
   and a marshal _ gave him trouble. He bogeyed the 10th hole when
a marshal almost stepped on his ball _ twice _ next to the green.
Sabbatini had to sink a six-footer for bogey to salvage what he
could on the hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very unnecessary,'' he said of the marshal's actions.
``He decided he was going to play soccer with my golf ball. It took
me out of my chain of thought. For a while, it kind of played on my
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabbatini bogeyed the 11th hole, and an errant driver forced him
to make three consecutive saving pars on holes 15-17.
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik, meanwhile, had birdied holes 11 and 13 for a
two-stroke lead, but he gave one back with a six-foot miss on the
385-yard 14th hole. He had his own problems with his driver and
even hit a spectator on the 15th hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked terrible,'' Parnevik said. ``It looked like a golf
ball was growing out of his forehead. He said, ``As long as you win
the tournament, I'll be OK.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik, playing one hole ahead of Sabbatini, birdied the 18th
hole by two-putting from 40 feet, and then it was Sabbatini's turn.
</P>
<P>
   He left his drive on No. 18 ``about five yards too far left,''
he said, and it stopped behind a tree. He pitched out with a wedge,
but the ball stopped next to a group of palm trees alongside a
pond. He then hit a 114-yard sand wedge over the trees to 25 feet,
but his effort to force a tie missed short and low of the hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very happy with that shot,'' he said, ``considering what
I had facing me. These things ... they occur, but hopefully, less
frequently in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik, who is No. 1 on this year's tour money list with
$808,700 _ he earlier tied for sixth and third at the Mercedes
Championships and Sony Open, respectively _ said a 10-week break he
took at the end of last year has helped him start well in 2000. He
also is feeling better after being a diagnosed with an irregular
heartbeat last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did the same thing three years ago,'' he said, referring to
his extended break from the game. ``I probably took 15 weeks off to
just relax and play for fun with friends at home, and I did well in
my first four tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think any time I feel like I have a good time on the golf
course, I have a lot of fun and play well.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was one of those.
</P>
<P>
   First-round leader David Toms challenged for the lead Sunday but
settled for a third-place finish with J.L. Lewis at 25-under. Each
player won $174,000. Fred Funk had the low round of the day, an
8-under 63, and tied John Huston and tour rookie Matt Gogel for
seventh and $93,500.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
