<DOCNO> NYT20000123.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-23 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4376 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     01-23 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMS SAVE SUPER BOWL FROM BEING TOTAL SNOOZER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Look at it this way:
</P>
<P>
   The Super Bowl was saved.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, there is no known reason on this little plastic
parcel of God's green turf that the St. Louis Rams deserve to be
Georgia-bound.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL's most entertaining team _ and that has definitely been
the Rams _ was reduced to an offensive version of the Cowboys here
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Frustration, futility and yellow-flag stupidity _ it all came
tumbling down on the Rams in the NFC Championship Game. St. Louis
was an outplayed team, and seemed to be a beaten team.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay came ``this'' close to pulling off the largest post
season upset since Namath's Jets. In no way, defensively, did the
Buccaneers remotely resemble a 14-point underdog. For the Bucs,
there would be no football justice in the Trans World Dome.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, it's best this way. Best the Rams didn't fade,
and finally survived with a wing, a prayer and, yes, a ``fade.''
The wing belonged to quarterback Kurt Warner. The prayer was the
jump ball Warner tossed toward a single-covered Ricky Proehl in the
end zone. It's called a ``fade'' route. Proehl won his battle, and
the Rams won the game, 11-6. Aaron Sele can relate. He won many
games for the Rangers, 11-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel fortunate we escaped with this one,'' said St. Louis
coach Dick Vermeil, an honest man supplying the understatement of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   But go ahead and rejoice, all you neutral observers of the Super
Bowl. Despite what didn't happen here yesterday, the Rams will
still bring to Atlanta plenty of razzle-dazzle. At least the
potential for fun and fireworks will be there Sunday against
Tennessee. When St. Louis has the ball, butts will be planted on
sofas all over America. Step away for a beer, and you might miss
something.
</P>
<P>
   If the NFL is going to be reduced to Brand X teams now playing
for conference championships _ hello again, Mr. Parity _ then the
entertainment value of the Super Bowl becomes more important than
quality. Particularly when the NFL has become void of quality.
</P>
<P>
   A Super Bowl being played with teams that have name value and
regal history on their resumes is now doubtful. Yesterday, in the
conference championship games, there were exactly none of those
among the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Rams and Titans kick it off Sunday in Atlanta _
hey, this match-up is OK. The Rams bring their offense, and the
Titans bring their January mojo. From that disputed miracle ending
against Buffalo three weeks ago, to yesterday in Jacksonville, when
a lost fumble on the 1-yard line ended up producing nine points _
for some unknown reason, is Tennessee being blessed, or being just
flat lucky?
</P>
<P>
   By the way, the Titans also beat St. Louis, 24-21, in the
regular season. But as Tennessee had to have the ``Music City
Miracle'' to get to Atlanta, maybe yesterday was the Rams' divine
moment of the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   They won when they shouldn't have won, partly became Tampa Bay's
rookie quarterback made a very poor choice on a mid-field pass late
in the game. The Bucs were up 6-5 and were holding all the
defensive trump cards, including field position.
</P>
<P>
   On third-and-11 from the 50, Shaun King didn't need to be
reckless, particularly with eight minutes to play. A punt from
there was as a good as a first down. The Rams' offense would be
pinned deep again, and this was an offense in turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   King, normally a heady kid, tried to connect with running back
Warrick Dunn on a timing route underneath the defensive coverage.
``The timing wasn't there, and a good defense will capitalize on
that,'' said the rookie. His poorly thrown duck to the left flat
was intercepted by nickel back Dre' Bly. Life returned to the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   King's mistake would become the second biggest play of the
afternoon. The biggest would follow nearly four minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   The deeply religious Warner became a cold-blooded gambling man
with the ball at the Tampa Bay 30. On third-and-four, Warner read a
blitz by safety Damien Robinson, and immediately shoved all his
chips to the middle of the table.
</P>
<P>
   Proehl, a 10-year veteran, made the same read as his quarterback
when he saw the safety blitz. He streaked toward the end zone,
locked in one-on-one coverage with nickel back Brian Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the ``fade'' Troy Aikman attempted with Nine-Toed Deion
at a critical point in the Jets' game? Except Deion was outmuscled
and the ball was intercepted, and Aikman was wrongly blamed by many
for ``underthrowing'' his receiver?
</P>
<P>
   Aikman made the same throw Warner did yesterday. The difference
was Proehl, and how he played the fade. The pattern is about
you-against-him. Go get the jump ball. Proehl did. His first TD
catch of the season was the biggest of the season for the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   With the lead, St. Louis still had a late sweat. But the Bucs'
final drive was stalled, and then killed, by a controversial
instant-replay overturn of a pass completion.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams, of course, were very lucky to win. For entertainment
purposes next week, be glad they did.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
