<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-23 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4379 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     01-23 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'LL STILL BE A SUPER GAME TO WATCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Amen for Tennessee and St. Louis. The Titans and
Rams making it to Super Bowl XXXIV is the best thing to happen to
the NFL since instant replay (Sorry, Tampa Bay).
</P>
<P>
   We realize in sports bars and other such places of idle worship
there are many who don't share our belief. It's six days before
sport's biggest excuse for a party and already some casual fans are
moaning and groaning as though they just swallowed a stale tortilla
chip covered in rotten guacamole.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, we have no patience for those fixated on John Elway's
retirement and Vinny Testaverde's season-ending injury and Dan
Marino's naked ring finger and Nashville's status as the
30th-largest television market.
</P>
<P>
   To say there are no immortals in Sunday's game and little
imperative to watch is as off the mark as the Jaguars' Super Bowl
ditty, ``Uh-oh,'' henceforth known as ``The Oh-No Song.''
</P>
<P>
   What advertisers are paying $3 million for 30 seconds of airtime
for, what ESPN is sending 18 reporters to Atlanta for and what a
television audience in the billions will tune in for is something
very sacred indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Call it the NFL's Salvation Bowl I.
</P>
<P>
   Honest-to-God, if you're a faithful football fan, you have to
thank heaven for the Titans and Rams. From NFL parvenu Kurt Warner
to the long-suffering Bruce Matthews, this Super Bowl promises to
deliver the league from every evil that assailed it this season.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL, you'll remember, gave us:
</P>
<P>
   The throat-slashing gesture;
</P>
<P>
   Randy Moss squirting a referee with a water bottle;
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Brown toppling a referee;
</P>
<P>
   Cecil Collins' arrest on burglary charges;
</P>
<P>
   Rae Carruth's arrest on first-degree murder charges, and:
</P>
<P>
   Tony Martin's federal money-laundering trial.
</P>
<P>
   Just when it was starting to seem the NFL stood for Narcissists,
Felons and Louts, the league somehow assembled a cast of solid
citizens and commendable characters for the season's final act.
</P>
<P>
   Angelenos, forget if you can that the Rams' 11-6 win over Tampa
Bay in the NFC Championship Game was a feather in the boa of
Georgia Frontiere, who on any given Sunday will never be confused
with Cameron Diaz.
</P>
<P>
   Focus instead on how fitting it is that Jeff Fisher will grace
the sidelines of the first Super Bowl contested since the death of
one of the game's all-time finest players and people, Walter
Payton.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, an L.A. native who attended Taft High in Woodland Hills,
was a teammate of Payton on the Chicago Bears. He also was a
teammate of Titans offensive guard Bruce Matthews at USC.
</P>
<P>
   Matthews showed the patience of Susan Lucci. He persevered, and
in his 17th season, he finally was rewarded with a trip to the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always told myself it didn't bother me `never to have played
in a Super Bowl,' '' Matthews finally was free to admit. ``But it
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Until this year, the Titans were the Cal State Northridge of the
NFL. That's right; in a league where money flows like Dom Perignon,
the Titans' coaching brain trust was housed in one portable trailer
while meetings were held in another. Another Jeff, the Matadors'
Kearin, can relate.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN players, take note: The Titans didn't get an inferiority
complex, they got fortitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four years, four stadiums, three cities, two states, two names
and we heard almost no complaints,'' Titans general manager Floyd
Reese has said, alluding to Tennessee's nomadic existence after
departing Houston. ``The way our players handled the adversity has
made everyone in the organization proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee running back Eddie George is a pretty fair Payton
knockoff, rushing for more than 1,000 yards in four consecutive
seasons. Not that many people noticed. It says a lot about George
that he didn't pound his chest and roar to draw raves. He was too
busy pumping iron.
</P>
<P>
   George is so durable he hasn't missed a game in four seasons and
so diligent he had to check himself into a hospital last year after
working himself to exhaustion in Ohio's searing summer heat.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher is forever telling George he should go easier on himself.
Think Lawrence Phillips' actions prompted the same lectures from
the Rams' Dick Vermeil and Miami's Jimmy Johnson?
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Titans quarterback Steve McNair, the anti-Ryan
Leaf. The next arrogant remark he makes will be his first.
</P>
<P>
   McNair's athleticism, not his ancestry, is what makes him such a
great story. Heaven help our society if McNair has to field the
same question asked of Washington's Doug Williams before Super Bowl
XXII: ``How long have you been a black quarterback?''
</P>
<P>
   The Titans assembled their team the old-fashioned way; they
started 16 draft picks Sunday in their 33-14 victory over
Jacksonville. In this age of free agency and salary cap
maneuverings, the Titans are throwbacks. They hark back to a
simpler era when you didn't buy championships, you built them.
</P>
<P>
   Warner, the Rams' quarterback, also is old-school. His story is
the stuff of which Johnny Unitas' legend was made. A one-year
starter (and four-year benchwarmer) at Division I-AA Northern Iowa,
Warner went undrafted in the NFL and was rejected by the Canadian
Football League.
</P>
<P>
   He worked for a while stocking shelves for minimum wage at a
Hy-Vee supermarket in Cedar Falls, Iowa. That was followed by short
stints in the Arena Football League and NFL Europe. The Rams signed
him in 1998, but he appeared in only one game. They thought so much
of him, they left him unprotected in the expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   But Cleveland didn't want him, either. And so Warner remained in
the shadows of well-compensated starter Trent Green.
</P>
<P>
   Green got injured in the exhibition season, Warner stepped in
and the rest is a story that doesn't need to be told by the likes
of the late John Facenda to bring about shivers.
</P>
<P>
   His 19th career start will be in the Super Bowl. Amazing.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing Warner did upon being summoned to the microphone
to address the Trans World Dome crowd was praise the Lord. His
expression left no room for questioning his sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   And how about Rams receiver Isaac Bruce, who turned to the
Scriptures for relief (and got it) when his hamstring injury flared
last week?
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that: A Super Bowl that counts the Creator among its
sponsors. In a season that saw so many sacred cows get tipped,
isn't that the best reason of all to embrace Super Bowl XXXIV?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
