<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-USCNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW USC REALLY WILL FEEL THE PRESSURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After their unlikely victory over No. 2-ranked
Arizona, USC basketball players talked about how no one gave the
Trojans a chance to pull off the upset.
</P>
<P>
   But even within the team, there was some doubt over how the
injury-riddled Trojans could defeat the Wildcats, as USC tried to
overcome the loss of forward Sam Clancy (broken foot) and Jarvis
Turner (broken ankle).
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a weird feeling but I wasn't sure we would win this
game,'' USC forward Brian Scalabrine said. ``I could not get those
injuries out of my head. It was hard to believe Sam was hurt but I
said to myself that we've just got to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Trojans are 5-0 (12-5 overall) and in sole
possession of first place in the Pacific-10 Conference, Scalabrine
thinks the task will become considerably tougher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be very difficult to sustain it. Not because
we can't keep it up playing this well. But people will look to
knock us off now, no matter what,'' he said. ``And they know we
won't have our leading scorer and rebounder.''
</P>
<P>
   Clancy led USC in both categories (17.2 points, 7.7 rebounds)
before suffering his injury.
</P>
<P>
   Encore, encore: How will the Trojans top last weekend? After
defeating Arizona State in overtime, overcoming the loss of Clancy
and Turner and upsetting Arizona, what else could they do to top
their current emotional high?
</P>
<P>
   ``We just need to keep winning,'' point guard Brandon Granville
said. ``We're going to ride the roller coaster until it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   But Scalabrine already has an immediate goal in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``How hard is that going to be to top this?'' he asked, then
answered the question. ``A win at the Pit would be huge. If we can
do that ...''
</P>
<P>
   USC plays at Oregon on Thursday night. The Ducks (13-3, 4-1) are
5-2 at home this season.
</P>
<P>
   No fear: Scalabrine said none of the reserves who got their
first significant minutes in weeks were overwhelmed by the thought
of playing against Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different generation. These kids think they can play no
matter who they are. There's no fear,'' Scalabrine said.
</P>
<P>
   Home-court advantage: USC has defeated Arizona three of the past
four seasons at the Sports Arena. The Trojans are also 7-0 at home
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We seem to be getting more support now,'' forward David
Bluthenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   USC has also won seven straight games for the first time since
1992.
</P>
<P>
   Iron man: Granville played all 40 minutes against Arizona, the
fourth time he has done it this season. He had just three
turnovers, and recorded his fourth double-double (12 points, 10
assists).
</P>
<P>
   Football commitment: USC received an oral commitment from
offensive lineman Travis Watkins of Helix High in San Diego.
Watkins (6-foot-4, 290 pounds) selected USC over San Diego State,
Oregon and Washington and is the fifth offensive lineman to commit
to the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   USC now has 17 commitments and has five available scholarships,
although the Trojans could use more with the recent medical
redshirt of Matt Welch and transfer of Darren Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, cornerback Eric Reese, who was in jeopardy of being
ineligible, has met the necessary academic requirements and will be
available to participate in spring practice in March. In another
development, wide receiver Kareem Kelly has experienced a change of
heart and will attempt to run track this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
