<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ICY-ROADS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELEVEN KILLED, DOZENS INJURED IN WRECKS ON ICY STREETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 THE KANSAS CITY STAR STAFF  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A fiery 24-vehicle, chain-reaction crash on
Interstate 29 Sunday afternoon killed 10 people and injured 42
others.
</P>
<P>
   The crash was one of a series of multi-vehicle accidents spawned
by freezing drizzle and snow that transformed highways throughout
the metropolitan area into ice-glazed slides. In all, 11 persons
were killed and 108 injured.
</P>
<P>
   Quantifying the tragedy was difficult Sunday because police and
fire departments as well as ambulance services and hospitals were
too overwhelmed by the volume of accidents and injuries to compile
complete figures.
</P>
<P>
   By 8:30 p.m. law enforcement agencies had reported at least 430
accidents in the metropolitan area and the number was bound to
increase, officers said. Kansas City had more than 200 accidents
and Independence had logged 70.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals in Jackson, Clay and Platte counties in MIssouri and
Johnson and Wyandotte counties in Kansas had reported treating 108
accident victims with injuries ranging from critical to minor. Most
of the injuries were not life-threatening.
</P>
<P>
   On the stretch of Interstate 29 between Kansas City
International Airport and St. Joseph, Mo., there were at least 50
accidents involving 100 vehicles from about 1 to 3 p.m., according
to the Missouri Highway Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Interstates and highways in the metropolitan area fared little
better. Damaged cars and trucks littered the shoulders and medians
of I-435, I-70, I-29 and I-35.
</P>
<P>
   The worst accident was on I-29 near Missouri 273 north of Platte
City where five tractor-trailers and 19 other vehicles were
involved in a chain-reaction crash.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Jim McMillen of the Missouri Highway Patrol said the names
of the dead probably wouldn't be released until today after
relatives were notified. He said one of the victims was a
grandfather from Florida who was visiting family in St. Joseph for
his 16-year-old grandchild's birthday party.
</P>
<P>
   Identification of the victims was made more difficult because
several of the bodies were burned and were difficult to reach
because of the mangled wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities were unsure of the cause of the accident, but
McMillen said one of those involved said visibility on the highway
was near zero.
</P>
<P>
   He said that one or more of the vehicles began sliding about
1:10 p.m. on the ice-covered highway. Before it was all over, five
tractor-trailers had jackknifed and 19 other pickups and cars had
collided in the chain reaction.
</P>
<P>
   One of the semitrailers caught fire. Because it was wedged in
with two other semis and about a dozen other vehicles, those
vehicles also were engulfed in flames.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the dead were burned, according to McMillen.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the vehicles involved were welded together by the
force of the crash and the heat of the fires, and it was difficult
to discern where one began and the other ended.
</P>
<P>
   Rescuers had a difficult time getting to the wreck because of
traffic that was backed up for miles and heavy snow that cut
visibility to about 100 yards at 2:20 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Once they arrived they were met with a grisly scene. Several of
the victims who had burned in their cars were still inside.
</P>
<P>
   The Highway Patrol closed I-29 for about 10 miles north of
Platte City. Traffic south of Platte City slowed to a crawl for
miles because of the fatal wreck.
</P>
<P>
   Truckers were stranded at the nearby QuikTrip Travel Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is absolutely no place to park,'' said Kathy Smith, a
diesel clerk at the store. ``We've got about 20 people standing
around just at the phones. Truckers are parked everywhere, even on
the fuel islands, because there's no place to go. Even the
McDonald's lot is full.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the witnesses at the scene were still too distressed to
comment or declined to comment on the advice of their insurance
agents.
</P>
<P>
   The storm was not expected, and the ice proved a challenge for
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were having a heck of a time just getting around with the
tow trucks,'' said Donald Adamson, a Northland Tow Service driver.
</P>
<P>
   A separate multi-vehicle wreck forced police to close northbound
Interstate 435 at Truman Road. Throughout the metropolitan area,
stretches of road were shut to all but rescuers and tow truck
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Department of Transportation tried to prepare for
the snow that had been forecast as a possibility by pretreating
highways and bridges, and crews expected to be out all Sunday
night. Still, so many cars collided that many drivers were told to
walk into police stations to report their wrecks.
</P>
<P>
   Rescuers looking for a wreck near the Downtown Airport reported
that the Broadway bridge was coated with a sheet of ice.
</P>
<P>
   Other rescuers reported similar scenes.
</P>
<P>
   One ambulance crew reported seeing cars sliding off an exit ramp
from I-29 and ``shooting right off the ramp and going
upside-down.''
</P>
<P>
   The deluge of crashes began about 1:30 p.m., and the pace slowed
two hours later. But rescue crews worked frantically for hours
trying to pull apart the wreckage and treat the injured.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a roundup of accidents in the metro area, culled from
dispatchers' estimates and police reports as of 8 p.m. Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   Jackson County, Mo., had at least 303 accidents. Kansas City had
the most, with 200 as of 5 p.m.; Independence had 70 accidents, one
with a serious injury.
</P>
<P>
   Cass County, Mo., had 12 accidents. Most of them were minor, but
one accident on U.S. 71 South and Missouri 58 near Raymore had
seven injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Clay County, Mo., had five or six minor accidents.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Missouri Highway Patrol handled about 60
accidents between 3 p.m. and 8 p.m. in Platte, Clay and Jackson
counties.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson County, Kan., had 16 accidents, mostly fender benders.
</P>
<P>
   Wyandotte County, Kan., had 14 accidents, none of them serious.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Kansas Highway Patrol handled more than 26
accidents in Johnson and Wyandotte counties. In one of the
accidents, a victim was sent to a hospital with injuries that were
not life-threatening.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
